              "view": {
                "es": "**A continuación tenemos la lista de los verbos que no podemos usar en los tiempos continuos**. La lista se encuentra clasificada en grupos según el tipo. **En general, son verbos estáticos y no de actividad (dinámicos). Algunos de estos verbos pueden tener dos significados, uno de acción y otro estático**. Si hay más de un significado para un mismo verbo, encontrarás el significado que no podemos usar en los tiempos continuos con la traducción al español.\n\n1. **Los verbos de sentido:**\n\n> **Tip:** feel\n>\n> (el tacto, sentir)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> hear\n>\n> (el oído, oír)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> see\n>\n> (la vista, ver)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> smell\n>\n> (el olfato, olor)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> taste\n>\n> (el gusto, sabor)\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Involuntaria:__\n\n> **Example:** I (can) see you.\n> **Translation:** (Te veo.)\n\n> **Avoid:** I am seeing you.\n\n> **Example:** It smells like you are cooking something.\n> **Translation:** (Huele como que estás cocinando algo.)\n\n> **Avoid:** It is smelling like you are cooking something.\n\n__Voluntaria:__\n\n> **Example:** I am seeing you later, right?\n> **Translation:** (¿Te veré luego, no?)\n\n> **Avoid:** I see you later, right?\n\n> **Example:** I am tasting the soup to see if it is as good as it smells.\n> **Translation:** (Estoy probando la sopa para ver si es tan buena como huele. )\n\n> **Avoid:** I taste the soup right now.\n\n> **Nota:** Si la percepción es voluntaria, se puede usar la forma continua. Usamos el verbo \"**to listen**\" para oir de forma voluntaria.\n\n2. **Verbos emotivos:**\n\n> **Tip:** believe\n>\n> (creer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> dislike\n>\n> (no gustar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> doubt\n>\n> (dudar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> imagine\n>\n> (imaginar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> hate\n>\n> (odiar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> know\n>\n> (saber, conocer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> like\n>\n> (gustar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> love\n>\n> (encantar, amar, querer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> prefer\n>\n> (preferir)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> realize\n>\n> (dar cuenta)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> recognize\n>\n> (reconocer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> remember\n>\n> (recordar, acordarse)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> suppose\n>\n> (suponer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> think\n>\n> (creer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> understand\n>\n> (entender, comprender)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> want\n>\n> (querer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> wish\n>\n> (esperar)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** You're lying. I don't believe you!\n> **Translation:** (Mientes. ¡No te creo!)\n\n> **Avoid:** You're lying. I am not believing you!\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, he understands you.\n> **Translation:** (No te preocupes, él te entiende.)\n\n> **Avoid:** Don't worry, he is understanding you.\n\n> **Example:** Do you think there is something wrong?\n> **Translation:** (¿Crees que hay algo mal?)\n\n> **Avoid:** Are you thinking there is something wrong?\n\n3. **Verbos de estado o verbos abstractos:**\n\n> **Tip:** be\n>\n> (ser, estar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> cost\n>\n> (costar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> seem\n>\n> (parecer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> need\n>\n> (necesitar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> care\n>\n> (importar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> contain\n>\n> (contener)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> exist\n>\n> (existir)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I am ill.\n> **Translation:** (Estoy enfermo.)\n\n> **Avoid:** I am being ill.\n\n> **Example:** David needs a new car.\n> **Translation:** (David necesita un nuevo coche.)\n\n> **Avoid:** David is needing a new car.\n\n> **Example:** Cigarettes cost 5 euros now.\n> **Translation:** (Los cigarrillos cuestan 5 euros ahora.)\n\n> **Avoid:** Cigarettes are costing 5 euros now.\n\n> **Example:** I don't care if you don't like it, you are going to eat it!\n> **Translation:** (No me importa si no te gusta, ¡vas a comerlo!)\n\n> **Avoid:** I'm not caring if you are not liking it, you are going to eat it!\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota:\n> >\n> > Normalmente, \"\n> >\n> > to be\n> >\n> > \" es un verbo estático pero\n> >\n> > podemos usarlo también para hablar del comportamiento\n> >\n> > . Para referirnos a la conducta de alguien, podemos usarlo en el tiempo continuo.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** You are silly.\n> > **Translation:** (Significa que \"eres tonto.\")\n>\n> > **Example:** You are being silly.\n> > **Translation:** (Significa que \"ahora te estás portando como un tonto.\")\n\n4. **Verbos de posesión:**\n\n> **Tip:** belong\n>\n> (pertenecer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> have\n>\n> (tener)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> possess\n>\n> (poseer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> own\n>\n> (poseer)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Ann owned a house when she lived in New York.\n> **Translation:** (Ann poseyó una casa cuando vivió en Nueva York.)\n\n> **Avoid:** Ann was owning a house when she lived in New York.\n\n> **Example:** That belongs to me!\n> **Translation:** (¡Eso me pertenece!)\n\n> **Avoid:** That is belonging to me!\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota:\n> >\n> > Cuando usamos \"\n> >\n> > to have\n> >\n> > \" para referirnos a algo que poseemos (una cosa, una cantidad, etc.), no podemos usarlo en el tiempo continuo. Pero\n> >\n> > si es parte de una expresión, podemos usarlo en el continuo\n> >\n> > .\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** I have [I've got] a car.\n> > **Translation:** (Tengo un coche.)\n>\n> > **Avoid:** I am having a car.\n>\n> > **Example:** I am having dinner right now.\n> > **Translation:** (Estoy cenando ahora mismo.)\n>\n> > **Avoid:** I have dinner right now.\n\n5. **Verbos de comunicación:**\n\n> **Tip:** agree\n>\n> (acordar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> astonish\n>\n> (asombrar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> deny\n>\n> (negar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> disagree\n>\n> (no estar de acuerdo)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> impress\n>\n> (impresionar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> mean\n>\n> (significar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> please\n>\n> (agradar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> promise\n>\n> (prometer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> satisfy\n>\n> (satisfacer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> surprise\n>\n> (sorprender)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I disagree, I think it's a great idea.\n> **Translation:** (No estoy de acuerdo, creo que es una gran idea.)\n\n> **Avoid:** I am disagreeing, I am thinking it's a great idea.\n\n> **Example:** You surprised me!\n> **Translation:** (¡Me ha sorprendido!)\n\n> **Avoid:** You were surprising me!",
                "en": "As mentioned in the previous lesson on the present continuous, **there are some verbs which may not be used in the continuous tenses**. Below is a list of the verbs which cannot be used in any of the **continuous verb tenses** (present, past or future). The list is grouped according to the type of verb. **In general, verbs which cannot be used in the continuous are static verbs, rather than active ones (dynamic). Some of the following verbs have two meanings; one which is static and one which is active**. If there is more than one meaning for a verb, you will find below only the meaning of the verb that cannot be used in the continuous.\n\n**1. Sense Verbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** feel\n>\n> ,\n>\n> hear\n>\n> ,\n>\n> see\n>\n> ,\n>\n> smell\n>\n> ,\n>\n> taste\n\nExamples:\n\n__Involuntary/Stative:__\n\n> **Example:** I (can) see you.\n\n> **Avoid:** I am seeing you.\n\n> **Example:** It smells like you are cooking something.\n\n> **Avoid:** It is smelling like you are cooking something.\n\n__Voluntary/Active:__\n\n> **Example:** I am seeing you later, right?\n\n> **Avoid:** I see you later, right?\n\n> **Example:** I am tasting the soup to see if it is as good as it smells.\n\n> **Avoid:** I taste the soup right now.\n\n> **Note:** If the sense is voluntary or active, we can use the continuous form. In the case of \"**to hear**\", the active form is a different verb, \"**to listen to**\".\n\n**2. Emotive Verbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** believe\n>\n> ,\n>\n> dislike\n>\n> ,\n>\n> doubt\n>\n> ,\n>\n> imagine\n>\n> ,\n>\n> hate\n>\n> ,\n>\n> know\n>\n> ,\n>\n> like\n>\n> ,\n>\n> love\n>\n> ,\n>\n> prefer\n>\n> ,\n>\n> realize\n>\n> ,\n>\n> recognize\n>\n> ,\n>\n> remember\n>\n> ,\n>\n> suppose\n>\n> ,\n>\n> think\n>\n> ,\n>\n> understand\n>\n> ,\n>\n> want\n>\n> ,\n>\n> wish\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** You're lying. I don't believe you!\n\n> **Avoid:** You're lying. I am not believing you!\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, he understands you.\n\n> **Avoid:** Don't worry, he is understanding you.\n\n> **Example:** Do you think there is something wrong?\n\n> **Avoid:** Are you thinking there is something wrong?\n\n**3. Stative or Abstract Verbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** be\n>\n> ,\n>\n> cost\n>\n> ,\n>\n> seem\n>\n> ,\n>\n> need\n>\n> ,\n>\n> care\n>\n> ,\n>\n> contain\n>\n> ,\n>\n> exist\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I am ill.\n\n> **Avoid:** I am being ill.\n\n> **Example:** David needs a new car.\n\n> **Avoid:** David is needing a new car.\n\n> **Example:** Cigarettes cost 5 euros now.\n\n> **Avoid:** Cigarettes are costing 5 euros now.\n\n> **Example:** I don't care if you don't like it, you are going to eat it!\n\n> **Avoid:** I'm not caring if you are not liking it, you are going to eat it!\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note:\n> >\n> > Normally, \"\n> >\n> > to be\n> >\n> > \" is a static verb, but it\n> >\n> > can also be used to talk about behavior\n> >\n> > . In this case, when we use \"\n> >\n> > to be\n> >\n> > \" to discuss the conduct of someone, we can use the continuous tense.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** You are silly.\n> > **Translation:** (*Meaning = in general, you are a silly person)\n>\n> > **Example:** You are being silly.\n> > **Translation:** (*Meaning = at the moment, you are acting or behaving in a silly manner)\n\n**4. Possessive Verbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** belong\n>\n> ,\n>\n> have\n>\n> ,\n>\n> possess\n>\n> ,\n>\n> own\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Ann owned a house when she lived in New York.\n\n> **Avoid:** Ann was owning a house when she lived in New York.\n\n> **Example:** That belongs to me!\n\n> **Avoid:** That is belonging to me!\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note:\n> >\n> > When we use the verb \"\n> >\n> > to have\n> >\n> > \" in the possessive sense, we cannot use it in the continuous.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** I have [I've got] a car.\n>\n> > **Avoid:** I am having a car.\n>\n> > **Example:** I am having dinner right now.\n>\n> > **Avoid:** I have dinner right now.\n\n**5. Communication verbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** agree\n>\n> ,\n>\n> astonish\n>\n> ,\n>\n> deny\n>\n> ,\n>\n> disagree\n>\n> ,\n>\n> impress\n>\n> ,\n>\n> mean\n>\n> ,\n>\n> please\n>\n> ,\n>\n> promise\n>\n> ,\n>\n> satisfy\n>\n> ,\n>\n> surprise\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I disagree, I think it's a great idea.\n\n> **Avoid:** I am disagreeing, I am thinking it's a great idea.\n\n> **Example:** You surprised me!\n\n> **Avoid:** You were surprising me!"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
