            {
              "code": 83,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "cardinal-numbers",
                "en": "cardinal-numbers"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Los números cardinales",
                "en": "Cardinal Numbers"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Del 1 al 12**\n\n> **Tip:** one\n>\n> (1),\n>\n> two\n>\n> (2),\n>\n> three\n>\n> (3),\n>\n> four\n>\n> (4),\n>\n> five\n>\n> (5),\n>\n> six\n>\n> (6),\n>\n> seven\n>\n> (7),\n>\n> eight\n>\n> (8),\n>\n> nine\n>\n> (9),\n>\n> ten\n>\n> (10),\n>\n> eleven\n>\n> (11),\n>\n> twelve\n>\n> (12)\n\n**Del 13 al 19**<br>La terminación es \"**-teen**\" que suena como \"tin\" en español.\n\n> **Tip:** thirteen\n>\n> (13),\n>\n> fourteen\n>\n> (14),\n>\n> fifteen\n>\n> (15),\n>\n> sixteen\n>\n> (16),\n>\n> seventeen\n>\n> (17),\n>\n> eighteen\n>\n> (18),\n>\n> nineteen\n>\n> (19)\n\n**20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90**<br>La terminación es \"**-ty**\" y suena como \"ti\" en español.\n\n> **Tip:** twenty\n>\n> (20),\n>\n> thirty\n>\n> (30),\n>\n> forty\n>\n> (40),\n>\n> fifty\n>\n> (50),\n>\n> sixty\n>\n> (60),\n>\n> seventy\n>\n> (70),\n>\n> eighty\n>\n> (80),\n>\n> ninety\n>\n> (90)\n\n**Para formar decenas se añade un guión entre la decenas y el número.**\n\n> **Tip:** twenty-one\n>\n> (21),\n>\n> thirty-two\n>\n> (32),\n>\n> forty-three\n>\n> (43),\n>\n> fifty-four\n>\n> (54),\n>\n> sixty-five\n>\n> (65),\n>\n> seventy-six\n>\n> (76),\n>\n> eighty-seven\n>\n> (87),\n>\n> ninety-eight\n>\n> (98)\n\n**Para formar centenas:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one hundred\n>\n> (100),\n>\n> two hundred\n>\n> (200),\n>\n> three hundred\n>\n> (300)...\n\n**Para unir las centenas con las decenas se unirán con \"and\".**\n\n> **Tip:** two hundred and fifty-five\n>\n> (255),\n>\n> six hundred and forty-eight\n>\n> (648)...\n\n**Para los millares:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one thousand\n>\n> (1,000),\n>\n> two thousand\n>\n> (2,000),\n>\n> ten thousand\n>\n> (10,000)...\n\n**Para los millones:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one million\n>\n> (1,000,000),\n>\n> two million\n>\n> (2,000,000),\n>\n> three million\n>\n> (3,000,000)...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** a/one hundred and two\n> **Translation:** (102)\n\n> **Example:** three hundred and twelve\n> **Translation:** (312)\n\n> **Example:** five thousand and ten\n> **Translation:** (5,010)\n\n> **Example:** two million five hundred thousand / two and a half million\n> **Translation:** (2,500,000)\n\n> **Example:** six thousand two hundred and seventy-nine\n> **Translation:** ( 6,279)\n\n> **Example:** two thousand two hundred and twenty-two\n> **Translation:** (2,222)\n\n> **Example:** three thousand three hundred and thirty-three\n> **Translation:** (3,333)\n\n| Números | Inglés |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1 | one |\n| 2 | two |\n| 3 | three |\n| 4 | four |\n| 5 | five |\n| 6 | six |\n| 7 | seven |\n| 8 | eight |\n| 9 | nine |\n| 10 | ten |\n| 11 | eleven |\n| 12 | twelve |\n| 13 | thirteen |\n| 14 | fourteen |\n| 15 | fifteen |\n| 16 | sixteen |\n| 17 | seventeen |\n| 18 | eighteen |\n| 19 | nineteen |\n| 20 | twenty |\n| 21 | twenty-one |\n| 22 | twenty-two |\n| 30 | thirty |\n| 40 | forty |\n| 50 | fifty |\n| 60 | sixty |\n| 70 | seventy |\n| 80 | eighty |\n| 90 | ninety |\n| 100 | a/one hundred |\n| 101 | a/one hundred and one |\n| 200 | two hundred |\n| 1,000 | a/one thousand |\n| 1,001 | a/one thousand and one |\n| 1,100 | one thousand one hundred<br>eleven hundred |\n| 10,000 | ten thousand |\n| 100,000 | a/one hundred thousand |\n| 1,000,000 | a/one million |",
                "en": "**From 1 al 12**\n\n> **Tip:** one\n>\n> (1),\n>\n> two\n>\n> (2),\n>\n> three\n>\n> (3),\n>\n> four\n>\n> (4),\n>\n> five\n>\n> (5),\n>\n> six\n>\n> (6),\n>\n> seven\n>\n> (7),\n>\n> eight\n>\n> (8),\n>\n> nine\n>\n> (9),\n>\n> ten\n>\n> (10),\n>\n> eleven\n>\n> (11),\n>\n> twelve\n>\n> (12)\n\n**From 13 to 19 we use the termination \"-teen\".**\n\n> **Tip:** thirteen\n>\n> (13),\n>\n> fourteen\n>\n> (14),\n>\n> fifteen\n>\n> (15),\n>\n> sixteen\n>\n> (16),\n>\n> seventeen\n>\n> (17),\n>\n> eighteen\n>\n> (18),\n>\n> nineteen\n>\n> (19)\n\n**20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90** end in \"**-ty**\".\n\n> **Tip:** twenty\n>\n> (20),\n>\n> thirty\n>\n> (30),\n>\n> forty\n>\n> (40),\n>\n> fifty\n>\n> (50),\n>\n> sixty\n>\n> (60),\n>\n> seventy\n>\n> (70),\n>\n> eighty\n>\n> (80),\n>\n> ninety\n>\n> (90)\n\n**For compound numbers in the tens, we use a hyphen (\"-\").**\n\n> **Tip:** twenty-one\n>\n> (21),\n>\n> thirty-two\n>\n> (32),\n>\n> forty-three\n>\n> (43),\n>\n> fifty-four\n>\n> (54),\n>\n> sixty-five\n>\n> (65),\n>\n> seventy-six\n>\n> (76),\n>\n> eighty-seven\n>\n> (87),\n>\n> ninety-eight\n>\n> (98)\n\n**To form hundreds:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one hundred\n>\n> (100),\n>\n> two hundred\n>\n> (200),\n>\n> three hundred\n>\n> (300)...\n\n**To join hundreds and tens we use \"and\".**\n\n> **Tip:** two hundred and fifty-five\n>\n> (255),\n>\n> six hundred and forty-eight\n>\n> (648)...\n\n**For thousands:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one thousand\n>\n> (1,000),\n>\n> two thousand\n>\n> (2,000),\n>\n> ten thousand\n>\n> (10,000)...\n\n**For millions:**\n\n> **Tip:** a/one million\n>\n> (1,000,000),\n>\n> two million\n>\n> (2,000,000),\n>\n> three million\n>\n> (3,000,000)...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** a/one hundred and two\n> **Translation:** (102)\n\n> **Example:** three hundred and twelve\n> **Translation:** (312)\n\n> **Example:** five thousand and ten\n> **Translation:** (5,010)\n\n> **Example:** two million five hundred thousand / two and a half million\n> **Translation:** (2,500,000)\n\n> **Example:** six thousand two hundred and seventy-nine\n> **Translation:** ( 6,279)\n\n> **Example:** two thousand two hundred and twenty-two\n> **Translation:** (2,222)\n\n> **Example:** three thousand three hundred and thirty-three\n> **Translation:** (3,333)\n\n| Numbers |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1 | one |\n| 2 | two |\n| 3 | three |\n| 4 | four |\n| 5 | five |\n| 6 | six |\n| 7 | seven |\n| 8 | eight |\n| 9 | nine |\n| 10 | ten |\n| 11 | eleven |\n| 12 | twelve |\n| 13 | thirteen |\n| 14 | fourteen |\n| 15 | fifteen |\n| 16 | sixteen |\n| 17 | seventeen |\n| 18 | eighteen |\n| 19 | nineteen |\n| 20 | twenty |\n| 21 | twenty-one |\n| 22 | twenty-two |\n| 30 | thirty |\n| 40 | forty |\n| 50 | fifty |\n| 60 | sixty |\n| 70 | seventy |\n| 80 | eighty |\n| 90 | ninety |\n| 100 | a/one hundred |\n| 101 | a/one hundred and one |\n| 200 | two hundred |\n| 1,000 | a/one thousand |\n| 1,001 | a/one thousand and one |\n| 1,100 | one thousand one hundred<br>eleven hundred |\n| 10,000 | ten thousand |\n| 100,000 | a/one hundred thousand |\n| 1,000,000 | a/one million |"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 203,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "ordinal-numbers",
                "en": "ordinal-numbers"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Los números ordinales",
                "en": "Ordinal Numbers"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**La abreviatura de los números ordinales se forma con el número en cifra seguido por las últimas dos letras de la palabra completa**. Las decenas, millares y el millón se unen con un guión o \"**and**\", al igual que los números cardinales.\n\n> **Tip:** 1st (first), 2nd (second), 3rd (third), 7th (seventh), 15th (fifteenth),\n>\n> 20th (twentieth), 23rd (twenty-third), 31st (thirty-first)...\n\n| Números | Inglés |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1st | first |\n| 2nd | second |\n| 3rd | third |\n| 4th | fourth |\n| 5th | fifth |\n| 6th | sixth |\n| 7th | seventh |\n| 8th | eighth |\n| 9th | ninth |\n| 10th | tenth |\n| 11th | eleventh |\n| 12th | twelfth |\n| 13th | thirteenth |\n| 14th | fourteenth |\n| 15th | fifteenth |\n| 16th | sixteenth |\n| 17th | seventeenth |\n| 18th | eighteenth |\n| 19th | nineteenth |\n| 20th | twentieth |\n| 21st | twenty-first |\n| 22nd | twenty-second |\n| 30th | thirtieth |\n| 40th | fortieth |\n| 50th | fiftieth |\n| 60th | sixtieth |\n| 70th | seventieth |\n| 80th | eightieth |\n| 90th | ninetieth |\n| 100th | hundredth |\n| 101st | hundred and first |\n| 200th | two hundredth |\n| 1,000th | thousandth |\n| 10,000th | ten thousandth |\n| 100,000th | hundred thousandth |\n| 1,000,000th | millionth |",
                "en": "**The abbreviation of ordinal numbers is formed using the number and the last two letters of the word**. The rules for the written words are the same as those of ordinal numbers (we use a hyphen for tens and for hundreds, thousands and millions, we use \"**and**\").\n\n> **Tip:** 1st (first), 2nd (second), 3rd (third), 7th (seventh), 15th (fifteenth),\n>\n> 20th (twentieth), 23rd (twenty-third), 31st (thirty-first)...\n\n| Numbers |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1st | first |\n| 2nd | second |\n| 3rd | third |\n| 4th | fourth |\n| 5th | fifth |\n| 6th | sixth |\n| 7th | seventh |\n| 8th | eighth |\n| 9th | ninth |\n| 10th | tenth |\n| 11th | eleventh |\n| 12th | twelfth |\n| 13th | thirteenth |\n| 14th | fourteenth |\n| 15th | fifteenth |\n| 16th | sixteenth |\n| 17th | seventeenth |\n| 18th | eighteenth |\n| 19th | nineteenth |\n| 20th | twentieth |\n| 21st | twenty-first |\n| 22nd | twenty-second |\n| 30th | thirtieth |\n| 40th | fortieth |\n| 50th | fiftieth |\n| 60th | sixtieth |\n| 70th | seventieth |\n| 80th | eightieth |\n| 90th | ninetieth |\n| 100th | hundredth |\n| 101st | hundred and first |\n| 200th | two hundredth |\n| 1,000th | thousandth |\n| 10,000th | ten thousandth |\n| 100,000th | hundred thousandth |\n| 1,000,000th | millionth |"
              }
            },
