              },
              "view": {
                "es": "## Vocabulary (Vocabulario)\n\n| English<br>Español |\n| --- |\n| day<br>día |\n| daily<br>diario |\n| today<br>hoy |\n| tonight<br>esta noche |\n| yesterday<br>ayer |\n| tomorrow<br>mañana |\n| week<br>semana |\n| weekly<br>semanal |\n| weekend<br>fin de semana |\n| month<br>mes |\n| monthly<br>mensual |\n| year<br>año |\n| yearly<br>anual |\n| decade<br>década |\n| century<br>siglo |\n| calendar<br>calendario |\n| schedule<br>horario |\n\n| Days of the Week<br>Los días de la semana |\n| --- |\n| Monday<br>lunes |\n| Tuesday<br>martes |\n| Wednesday<br>miércoles |\n| Thursday<br>jueves |\n| Friday<br>viernes |\n| Saturday<br>sábado |\n| Sunday<br>domingo |\n\n| Months of the Year<br>Los meses del año |\n| --- |\n| January<br>enero |\n| February<br>febrero |\n| March<br>marzo |\n| April<br>abril |\n| May<br>mayo |\n| June<br>junio |\n| July<br>julio |\n| August<br>agosto |\n| September<br>septiembre |\n| October<br>octubre |\n| November<br>noviembre |\n| December<br>diciembre |\n\n| The Seasons<br>Las estaciones del año |\n| --- |\n| winter<br>invierno |\n| spring<br>primavera |\n| summer<br>verano |\n| autumn, fall(US)<br>otoño |\n\n| Holidays<br>Días festivos |\n| --- |\n| Easter<br>Pascua |\n| Halloween<br>Víspera de Todos los Santos/Noche de Brujas |\n| Christmas<br>Navidad |\n| New Year's day<br>Día de año nuevo |\n| New Year's eve<br>Víspera de año nuevo |\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n**1. Los meses y los días se escriben en mayúscula.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **J**uly\n> **Translation:** (julio)\n\n> **Example:** **T**hursday\n> **Translation:** (jueves)\n\n**2. Las fechas se expresan con números ordinales.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Today is the 1st (**first**) of April.\n> **Translation:** (Hoy es el primero de abril.)\n\n> **Example:** His birthday is the 14th (**fourteenth**) of October.\n> **Translation:** (Su cumpleaños es el 14 de octubre.)\n\n**3. Formato de fechas.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** June 30, 2006\n> **Translation:** (30 de junio de 2006)\n\n> **Example:** November 10, 1968\n> **Translation:** (10 de noviembre de 1968)\n\n__Formato US: **mes/día/año**__\n\n> **Example:** 04/18/2010\n\n__Formato UK: **día/mes/año**__\n\n> **Example:** 18/04/2010",
                "en": "| Vocabulary |\n| --- |\n| day |\n| daily |\n| today |\n| tonight |\n| yesterday |\n| tomorrow |\n| week |\n| weekly |\n| weekend |\n| month |\n| monthly |\n| year |\n| yearly |\n| decade |\n| century |\n| calendar |\n| schedule |\n\n| Days of the Week |\n| --- |\n| Monday |\n| Tuesday |\n| Wednesday |\n| Thursday |\n| Friday |\n| Saturday |\n| Sunday |\n\n| Months of the Year |\n| --- |\n| January |\n| February |\n| March |\n| April |\n| May |\n| June |\n| July |\n| August |\n| September |\n| October |\n| November |\n| December |\n\n| The Seasons |\n| --- |\n| winter |\n| spring |\n| summer |\n| autumn, fall (US) |\n\n| Holidays |\n| --- |\n| Easter |\n| Halloween |\n| Christmas |\n| New Year's day |\n| New Year's eve |\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n**1. The days of the week and the months are capitalized.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **J**uly\n\n> **Example:** **T**hursday\n\n**2. Dates are expressed using ordinal numbers.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Today is the 1st (**first**) of April.\n\n> **Example:** His birthday is the 14th (**fourteenth**) of October.\n\n**3. Date format:**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** June 30, 2006\n\n> **Example:** November 10, 1968\n\n__**US Format: month/day/year**__\n\n> **Example:** 04/18/2010\n\n__**UK Format: day/month/year**__\n\n> **Example:** 18/04/2010"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 86,
              "order": 4,
              "slug": {
                "es": "time",
                "en": "time"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "La hora",
                "en": "Time"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Hay muchas maneras de decir la hora en inglés.\n\n**1. Podemos decir los números tal cual:**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** ten twenty\n> **Translation:** (10:20)\n\n> **Example:** two fifteen\n> **Translation:** (2:15)\n\n> **Example:** five forty-five\n> **Translation:** (5:45)\n\n**2. Para decir las horas en punto podemos decir:**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** nine or nine o'clock\n> **Translation:** (nueve en punto)\n\n> **Example:** twelve or twelve o'clock\n> **Translation:** (doce en punto)\n\nPero no podemos decir:\n\n> **Avoid:** six-thirty o'clock\n\n**3. No se utiliza oralmente el reloj de 24 horas.** Para diferenciar la mañana de la tarde podemos decir si es la mañana o la tarde o se emplea \"**am**\" y \"**pm**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Four [o'clock] in the morning / 4 **am**\n> **Translation:** (4:00)\n\n> **Example:** Five [o'clock] in the afternoon / 5 **pm**\n> **Translation:** (17:00)\n\n**4. Otra maneras de decir la hora son las siguientes:**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** one o'clock\n> **Translation:** (1:00)\n\n> **Example:** 7am\n> **Translation:** (7:00)\n\n> **Example:** 3pm\n> **Translation:** (15:00)\n\n> **Example:** ten past [after] five\n> **Translation:** (5:10/17:10)\n\n> **Example:** quarter past [after] six\n> **Translation:** (6:15/18:15)\n\n> **Example:** half past eight / eight thirty\n> **Translation:** (8:30/20:30)\n\n> **Example:** twenty to eleven\n> **Translation:** (10:40/22:40)\n\n> **Example:** quarter to twelve\n> **Translation:** (11:45/23:45)\n\n> **Nota:** En inglés británico se dice \"**quarter past**\" o \"**half past**\" y en inglés americano \"**quarter after**\" o \"**thirty**\" (no se dice \"**half after**\").\n\n**5. Preguntar y decir la hora:**\n\n__Question (pregunta)__\n\n> **Example:** What time is it?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué hora es?)\n\n> **Example:** What's the time?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué hora es?)\n\n__Answer (respuesta)__\n\n> **Example:** It's...\n> **Translation:** (Es la... /Son las...)",
                "en": "There are many ways to express time in English.\n\n**1. We can say the numbers as they are:**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** ten twenty\n> **Translation:** (10:20)\n\n> **Example:** two fifteen\n> **Translation:** (2:15)\n\n> **Example:** five forty-five\n> **Translation:** (5:45)\n\n**2. When the hour is on the hour, it is expressed using \"o'clock\":**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** nine or nine o'clock\n\n> **Example:** twelve or twelve o'clock\n\nWe cannot say:\n\n> **Avoid:** six-thirty o'clock\n\n**3. When speaking, we do not use the 24 hour clock.** To differentiate between the morning and the afternoon, we use \"**am**\" (morning) and \"**pm**\" (afternoon).\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Four [o'clock] in the morning / 4 **am**\n> **Translation:** (4:00)\n\n> **Example:** Five [o'clock] in the afternoon / 5 **pm**\n> **Translation:** (17:00)\n\n**4. The following are further examples of how to say the time:**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** one o'clock\n> **Translation:** (1:00)\n\n> **Example:** 7am\n> **Translation:** (7:00)\n\n> **Example:** 3pm\n> **Translation:** (15:00)\n\n> **Example:** ten past [after] five\n> **Translation:** (5:10/17:10)\n\n> **Example:** quarter past [after] six\n> **Translation:** (6:15/18:15)\n\n> **Example:** half past eight / eight thirty\n> **Translation:** (8:30/20:30)\n\n> **Example:** twenty to eleven\n> **Translation:** (10:40/22:40)\n\n> **Example:** quarter to twelve\n> **Translation:** (11:45/23:45)\n\n> **Note**: In British English, 15 minutes after the hour is \"**quarter past**\" and in American English, it is more often said, \"**quarter after**\".\n\n**5. Asking and telling the time:**\n\n__Question:__\n\n> **Example:** What time is it?\n\n> **Example:** What's the time?\n\n__Answer__\n\n> **Example:** It's..."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
