          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 36,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "comparatives-and-superlatives",
                "en": "comparatives-and-superlatives"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Los comparativos y superlativos",
                "en": "Comparatives and Superlatives"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Como hemos visto, **los adjetivos describen cualidades de sustantivos. Algunas de estas cualidades pueden variar en el grado o intensidad**. Al igual que en español, cuando queremos hacer comparaciones contrastamos cualidades o atributos por medio de adjetivos en sus diversos grados.\n\n## Grades of Adjectives (Grados de adjetivos)\n\n**Los adjetivos que pueden variar en el grado o intensidad tienen formas comparativas y superlativas**. En la siguiente sección, están las reglas sobre cómo formar estas formas comparativas y superlativas.\n\n### El grado positivo\n\n**El grado positivo** de los adjetivos, que hemos visto anteriormente, es la cualidad en el grado más simple.\n\n> **Tip:** fast\n>\n> (rápido)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> hard\n>\n> (duro)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> smart\n>\n> (listo)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> pretty\n>\n> (bonito)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> clean\n>\n> (limpio)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> large\n>\n> (grande)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> small\n>\n> (pequeño)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> old\n>\n> (viejo)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> easy\n>\n> (fácil)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Juan runs **fast**.\n> **Translation:** (Juan corre rápido.)\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is **clean**.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación de Angela está limpia.)\n\n> **Example:** I am **tall**.\n> **Translation:** (Soy alto.)\n\n> **Example:** New York is **big**.\n> **Translation:** (Nueva York es grande.)\n\n### **El grado comparativo**\n\nAl hacer comparaciones, podemos destacar la superioridad, inferioridad o igualdad de calidad de uno a otro. La estructura de cada uno de estos grados de comparación es diferente.\n\n**1. Comparativos de superioridad**. En las comparaciones de superioridad, el adjetivo, que está en la forma comparativa (véase más adelante), es seguido por **\"__than__\"**.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Juan runs **faster** __than__ Mark.\n> **Translation:** (Juan corre más rápido que Mark.)\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is **cleaner** __than__ Sue's.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación de Angela está más limpia que la de Sue.)\n\n> **Example:** I am **taller** __than__ Beth.\n> **Translation:** (Soy más alto que Beth.)\n\n> **Example:** New York is **bigger** __than__ Los Angeles.\n> **Translation:** (Nueva York es más grande que Los Angeles.)\n\n**2. Comparativos de inferioridad**. Para formar este tipo de comparación podemos usar las conjunciones **\"__not as...as__\"** or **\"__less...than__\"**. En ambos casos, el adjetivo está en el grado positivo.\n\n> **Example:** Mark is not __as__ **fast** __as__ Juan.\n> **Translation:** (Mark no corre tan rápido como Juan.)\n\n> **Example:** Sue's room is __less__ **clean** __than__ Angela's.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación de Sue no es tan limpia como la de Angela.)\n\n> **Example:** Beth is __not as__ **tall** __as__ me.\n> **Translation:** (Beth no es tan alta como yo.)\n\n> **Example:** Los Angeles is __not as__ **big** __as__ New York.\n> **Translation:** (Los Angeles no es tan grande como Nueva York.)\n\n**3. Comparativos de igualdad**. Con el adjetivo en el grado positivo, utilizamos la conjunción **\"__as...as__\"** para formar las comparaciones de igualdad.\n\n> **Example:** Mark is __as__ **fast** __as__ Juan.\n> **Translation:** (Mark corre tan rápido como Juan.)\n\n> **Example:** Sue's room is __as__ **clean** __as__ Angela's.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación de Sue es tan limpia como la de Angela.)\n\n> **Example:** Beth is __as__ **tall** __as__ I am.\n> **Translation:** (Beth es tan alta como yo.)\n\n> **Example:** Los Angeles is __as__ **big** __as__ New York.\n> **Translation:** (Los Angeles es tan grande como Nueva York.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Podemos modificar un comparativo con un\n> >\n> > cuantificador\n> >\n> > (much, a lot, a little, slightly...).\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Juan is __a lot__ **faster** than Mark.\n> > **Translation:** (Juan corre mucho más rápido que Mark.)\n>\n> > **Example:** I am __a little__ **taller** than Beth.\n> > **Translation:** (Soy un poco más alta que Beth.)\n\n### El grado superlativo\n\n**El grado superlativo** denota la calidad en el grado más alto y como en español, se usa **\"the\"** delante del adjetivo en la forma superlativa (véase más adelante).\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Juan is __the__ **fastest**.\n> **Translation:** (Juan es el más rápido.)\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is __the__ **cleanest**.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación de Angela es la más limpia.)\n\n> **Example:** I am __the__ **tallest**.\n> **Translation:** (Soy el más alto.)\n\n> **Example:** New York is __the__ **biggest** city in the United States.\n> **Translation:** (Nueva York es la ciudad más grande de los Estados Unidos.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Si el adjetivo es posesivo, no se usa\n> >\n> > \"the\"\n> >\n> > . Además no se usa\n> >\n> > \"the\"\n> >\n> > si comparamos algo con si mismo.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** His **smartest** student is Lisa.\n> > **Translation:** (Su estudiante más lista es Lisa.)\n>\n> > **Example:** New York is **coldest** in January.\n> > **Translation:** (Nueva York es más frío en enero.)\n\n## Form (Forma)\n\nHay unas reglas para formar el comparativo y superlativo.\n\n**1. Para adjetivos de una sílaba:**\n\n| Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- |\n| añade: \"**-er**\"<br>faster | añade: \"**-est**\"<br>fastest |\n\n**2. Para adjetivos de una sílaba que terminan en \"e\":**\n\n| Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- |\n| añade: \"**-r**\"<br>nicer | añade: \"**-st**\"<br>nicest |\n\n**3. Para adjetivos de una sílaba que terminan en consonante + vocal + consonante:**\n\n| Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- |\n| añade: consonante + \"**-er**\"<br>hotter | añade: consonante + \"**-est**\"<br>hottest |\n\n**4. Para adjetivos de dos silabas que terminan en \"y\":**\n\n| Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- |\n| sustituye **\"y\"** por: \"**-ier**\"<br>funnier | sustituye **\"y\"** por: \"**-iest**\"<br>funniest |\n\n**5. Para adjetivos de dos o más silabas:**\n\n| Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- |\n| añade: \"**more**\"/\"**less**\"<br>**more** beautiful<br>**less** beautiful | añade: \"**the most**\"/\"**the least**\"<br>**the most** beautiful<br>**the least** beautiful |\n\n**6. Adjetivos irregulares:**\n\n| Adjetivo | Comparativo | Superlativo |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| good | better | best |\n| bad | worse | worst |\n| far | further | furthest |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Algunas cualidades no pueden variar en intensidad o grado porque son extremos, absolutos o adjetivos de clasificación. Estas cualidades no tienen forma comparativa o superlativa.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> __Extremos__\n>\n> > **Example:** freezing\n> > **Translation:** (helado)\n>\n> > **Example:** excellent\n> > **Translation:** (excelente)\n>\n> __Absolutos__\n>\n> > **Example:** dead\n> > **Translation:** (muerto)\n>\n> > **Example:** unique\n> > **Translation:** (único)\n>\n> __Clasificación__\n>\n> > **Example:** married\n> > **Translation:** (casado\n>\n> > **Example:** domestic\n> > **Translation:** (doméstico)",
                "en": "As we have seen, **adjectives describe qualities of nouns. Some of these qualities can vary in degree or intensity (gradable adjectives)**. When we want to make comparisons contrasting qualities or attributes of a noun, we do so by means of an adjective in one of three grades.\n\n## Grades of Adjectives\n\n**Gradable adjectives can vary in degree or intensity and therefore can have comparative and superlative forms**. See below for rules on how to form the comparative and superlative forms.\n\n### The positive grade\n\n**The positive grade**, which we saw previously, is the quality in the simplest grade.\n\n> **Tip:** fast,\n>\n> hard,\n>\n> smart,\n>\n> pretty,\n>\n> clean,\n>\n> large,\n>\n> small,\n>\n> old,\n>\n> easy...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Juan runs **fast**.\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is **clean**.\n\n> **Example:** I am **tall**.\n\n> **Example:** New York is **big**.\n\n### **The Comparative Grade**\n\nWhen making comparisons, we can highlight the superiority, inferiority or equality of one quality or another. The structure of each of these grades of comparison is different.\n\n**1. Comparisons of superiority**. In comparisons of superiority, the adjective, which is in the comparative form (see below), is followed by \"__**than**__\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Juan runs **faster** __than__ Mark.\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is **cleaner** __than__ Sue's.\n\n> **Example:** I am **taller** __than__ Beth.\n\n> **Example:** New York is **bigger** __than__ Los Angeles.\n\n**2. Comparisons of inferiority**. To form this type of comparison we can use the conjunctions \"**__not as__...__as__**\" or \"**__less__...__than__**\". In both cases, the adjective is in the positive grade.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Mark is not __as__ **fast** __as__ Juan.\n\n> **Example:** Sue's room is __less__ **clean** __than__ Angela's..\n\n> **Example:** Beth is __notas__ **tall** __as__ me.\n\n> **Example:** Los Angeles is __not as__ **big** __as__ New York.\n\n**3. Comparisons of equality**. With the adjective in the positive grade, we use the conjunction \"**__as__...__as__**\" to form comparisons of equality.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Mark is __as__ **fast** __as__ Juan.\n\n> **Example:** Sue's room is __as__ **clean** __as__ Angela's.\n\n> **Example:** Beth is __as__ **tall** __as__ I am.\n\n> **Example:** Los Angeles is __as__ **big** __as__ New York.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : We can modify a comparison using a\n> >\n> > quantifier\n> >\n> > such as \"\n> >\n> > much\n> >\n> > \", \"\n> >\n> > a lot\n> >\n> > \", \"\n> >\n> > a little\n> >\n> > \", etc.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Juan is __a lot__ **faster** than Mark.\n>\n> > **Example:** I am __a little__ **taller** than Beth.\n\n### The Superlative Grade\n\n**The superlative grade** denotes a quality at its highest degree and is formed using the article \"**__the__**\" in front of the superlative form of the adjective (see below).\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Juan is __the__ **fastest**.\n\n> **Example:** Angela's room is __the__ **cleanest**.\n\n> **Example:** I am __the__ **tallest**.\n\n> **Example:** New York is __the__ **biggest** city in the United States.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : If the adjective is possessive, we don't use \"\n> >\n> > the\n> >\n> > \". In addition, we don't use \"\n> >\n> > the\n> >\n> > \" when comparing something with itself.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** His **smartest** student is Lisa.\n>\n> > **Example:** New York is **coldest** in January.\n\n## Form\n\nBelow are the rules for forming the comparative and superlative forms of gradable adjectives.\n\n1. For one syllable adjectives:\n\n| Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- |\n| add: \"-**er**\"<br>faster | add: \"-**est**\"<br>fastest |\n\n2. For one syllable adjectives that end in \"-**e**\":\n\n| Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- |\n| add: \"-**r**\"<br>nicer | add: \"-**st**\"<br>nicest |\n\n3. For one syllable adjectives that end in \"**consonant + vowel + consonant**\":\n\n| Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- |\n| add: **consonant** + \"-**er**\"<br>hotter | add: **consonant** + \"-**est**\"<br>hottest |\n\n4. For two syllable adjectives that end in \"-**y**\":\n\n| Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- |\n| substitute **\"y\"** for:\"-**ier**\"<br>funnier | substitute \"**y**\" for: \"-**iest**\"<br>funniest |\n\n5. For adjectives of two syllables or more:\n\n| Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- |\n| add: \"**more**\"/ \"**less**\"<br>**more** beautiful<br>**less** beautiful | add: \"**the most**\"/ \"**the least**\":<br>**the most** beautiful<br>**the least** beautiful |\n\n6. Irregular adjectives:\n\n| Adjetive | Comparative | Superlative |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| good | better | best |\n| bad | worse | worst |\n| far | further | furthest |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : Some qualities cannot vary in intensity or degree because they are extremes, absolutes or classifying adjectives. These qualities are known as\n> >\n> > non-gradable adjectives\n> >\n> > and they don't have either comparative or superlative forms.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> __Extreme__\n>\n> > **Example:** freezing\n>\n> > **Example:** excellent\n>\n> __Absolute__\n>\n> > **Example:** dead\n>\n> > **Example:** unique\n>\n> __Classifying__\n>\n> > **Example:** married\n>\n> > **Example:** domestic"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 106,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "adjectives-ending-in-ed-and-ing",
                "en": "adjectives-ending-in-ed-and-ing"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Los adjetivos terminando en \"-ed\" y \"-ing\"",
                "en": "Adjectives Ending in \"-ed\" and \"-ing\""
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Las terminaciones \"-ed\" y \"-ing\" no sólo se usan para formar los tiempos verbales del pasado y presente continuo, también se usan con adjetivos**. Estos adjetivos están compuestos de un verbo y estas dos terminaciones, pero ten en cuenta que el sentido cambia dependiendo de que terminación se use.\n\n## \"-ed\" Adjectives (Adjetivos terminando en \"-ed\")\n\n**Los adjetivos que terminan en \"-ed\" indican o describen emociones**. Estos adjetivos suelen acabar en \"-ado\" o \"-ido\" en español y van después del verbo \"estar\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** John is **interested** in art.\n> **Translation:** (John está interesado en el arte.)\n\n> **Example:** Denise was **bored** in class.\n> **Translation:** (Denise estaba aburrida en clase.)\n\n> **Example:** Luke is **excited** about his new job.\n> **Translation:** (Luke está emocionado con su nuevo empleo.)\n\n## \"-ing\" Adjectives (Adjetivos terminando en \"-ing\")\n\n**Los adjetivos que terminan en \"-ing\" indican o describen una característica de algo o alguien**. A diferencia de los adjetivos que terminan en (**\"‑ed\"**), no hay regla en español para formar estos adjetivos y van después del verbo \"ser\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** John is an **interesting** person.\n> **Translation:** (John es una persona interesante.)\n\n> **Example:** The class was **boring** so Denise fell asleep.\n> **Translation:** (La clase era aburrida así que Denise se durmió.)\n\n> **Example:** Luke started an **exciting** new job.\n> **Translation:** (Luke acaba de empezar un nuevo empleo emocionante.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Como hemos mencionado anteriormente, el uso de un adjetivo en vez de otro cambia el sentido de la frase.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Steve is **embarrassed**.\n> > **Translation:** (Steve está avergonzado.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Steve is **embarrassing**.\n> > **Translation:** (Steve es vergonzoso.)\n\nA continuación tienes una lista de algunos de los adjetivos más comunes terminando en (**\"‑ed\"**) y \"**-ing**\".\n\n| \"-ed\" Adjetivo | \"-ing\" Adjetivo |\n| --- | --- |\n| alarmed<br>alarmado | alarming<br>alarmante |\n| aggravated<br>agravado | aggravating<br>agravante |\n| annoyed<br>molesto | annoying<br>molesto |\n| astonished<br>asombrado | astonishing<br>asombroso |\n| astounded<br>asombrado | astounding<br>asombroso |\n| bored<br>aburrido | boring<br>aburrido |\n| captivated<br>cautivado | captivating<br>cautivador |\n| challenged<br>desafiado | challenging<br>desafiante |\n| charmed<br>encantado | charming<br>encantador |\n| comforted<br>consolado | comforting<br>consolador |\n| confused<br>confuso | confusing<br>confuso |\n| convinced<br>convencido | convincing<br>convincente |\n| depressed<br>deprimido | depressing<br>deprimente |\n| disappointed<br>decepcionado | disappointing<br>decepcionante |\n| discouraged<br>desalentado | discouraging<br>desalentador |\n| disgusted<br>indignado | disgusting<br>repugnante |\n| distressed<br>preocupado | distressing<br>preocupante |\n| disturbed<br>perturbado | disturbing<br>pertubador |\n| embarrassed<br>avergonzado | embarrassing<br>vergonzoso |\n| encouraged<br>animado | encouraging<br>alentador |\n| entertained<br>entretenido | entertaining<br>entretenido |\n| excited<br>emocionado | exciting<br>emocionante |\n| exhausted<br>agotado | exhausting<br>agotador |\n| fascinated<br>fascinado | fascinating<br>fascinante |\n| frightened<br>asustado | frightening<br>espantoso |\n| frustrated<br>frustrado | frustrating<br>frustrante |\n| fulfilled<br>satisfecho | fulfilling<br>satisfactorio |\n| gratified<br>satisfecho | gratifying<br>gratificante |\n| inspired<br>inspirado | inspiring<br>inspirador |\n| insulted<br>insultado | insulting<br>insultante |\n| interested<br>interesado | interesting<br>interesante |\n| moved<br>emocionado | moving<br>emocionante |\n| overwhelmed<br>abrumado | overwhelming<br>abrumador |\n| perplexed<br>desconcertado | perplexing<br>desconcertante |\n| pleased<br>satisfecho | pleasing<br>satisfactorio |\n| relaxed<br>relajado | relaxing<br>relajante |\n| relieved<br>consolado | relieving<br>consolador |\n| satisfied<br>satisfecho | satisfying<br>satisfactorio |\n| shocked<br>conmocionado | shocking<br>chocante |\n| sickened<br>asqueado | sickening<br>asqueroso |\n| soothed<br>relajado | soothing<br>relajante |\n| surprised<br>sorprendido | surprising<br>sorprendente |\n| tempted<br>tentado | tempting<br>tentador |\n| terrified<br>aterrado | terrifying<br>aterrador |\n| threatened<br>amenazado | threatening<br>amenazante |\n| thrilled<br>emocionado | thrilling<br>emocionante |\n| tired<br>cansado | tiring<br>agotador |\n| touched<br>conmovido | touching<br>conmovedor |\n| unsettled<br>perturbado | unsettling<br>perturbador |\n| worried<br>preocupado | worrying<br>preocupante |",
                "en": "**The \"-ed\" and \"-ing\" endings are not only used to form the past and continuous verb tenses, they are used with adjectives as well**. These adjectives are made using a verb and one of these two terminations, but be careful because the meaning of the adjective changes depending on which ending is used.\n\n## \"-ed\" Adjectives\n\n**Adjectives ending in \"-ed\" indicate or describe feelings.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** John is **interested** in art.\n\n> **Example:** Denise was **bored** in class.\n\n> **Example:** Luke is **excited** about his new job.\n\n## \"-ing\" Adjectives\n\n**Adjectives ending in \"-ing\" indicate or describe a characteristic of something or someone.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** John is an **interesting** person.\n\n> **Example:** The class was **boring**, so Denise fell asleep.\n\n> **Example:** Luke started an **exciting** new job.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : As mentioned above, the use of one adjective over the other changes the meaning of the sentence.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Steve is **embarrassed**.\n> > **Translation:** (**Meaning**: Steve feels embarrassed.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Steve is **embarrassing**.\n> > **Translation:** (**Meaning**: Steve acts in a manner which is embarrassing.)\n\nThe following is a list of some of the more common adjectives ending in \"**-ed**\" and \"**-ing**\".\n\n| \"-ed\" Adjective | \"-ing\" Adjective |\n| --- | --- |\n| alarmed | alarming |\n| aggravated | aggravating |\n| annoyed | annoying |\n| astonished | astonishing |\n| astounded | astounding |\n| bored | boring |\n| captivated | captivating |\n| challenged | challenging |\n| charmed | charming |\n| comforted | comforting |\n| confused | confusing |\n| convinced | convincing |\n| depressed | depressing |\n| disappointed | disappointing |\n| discouraged | discouraging |\n| disgusted | disgusting |\n| distressed | distressing |\n| disturbed | disturbing |\n| embarrassed | embarrassing |\n| encouraged | encouraging |\n| entertained | entertaining |\n| excited | exciting |\n| exhausted | exhausting |\n| fascinated | fascinating |\n| frightened | frightening |\n| frustrated | frustrating |\n| fulfilled | fulfilling |\n| gratified | gratifying |\n| inspired | inspiring |\n| insulted | insulting |\n| interested | interesting |\n| moved | moving |\n| overwhelmed | overwhelming |\n| perplexed | perplexing |\n| pleased | satisfying |\n| relaxed | relaxing |\n| relieved | relieving |\n| satisfied | satisfying |\n| shocked | shocking |\n| sickened | sickening |\n| soothed | soothing |\n| surprised | surprising |\n| tempted | tempting |\n| terrified | terrifying |\n| threatened | threatening |\n| thrilled | thrilling |\n| tired | tiring |\n| touched | touching |\n| unsettled | unsettling |\n| worried | worrying |"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 105,
              "order": 3,
              "slug": {
                "es": "intensifiers-and-mitigators",
                "en": "intensifiers-and-mitigators"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Los intensificadores y mitigadores",
                "en": "Intensifiers and Mitigators"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Los intensificadores y mitigadores** se usan para variar el grado o fuerza de un adjetivo, verbo o adverbio.\n\n## Intensifiers (Los intensificadores)\n\n1. Los intensificadores añaden fuerza al sentido de un __adjetivo__.\n\n> **Tip:** very\n>\n> (muy)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> really\n>\n> (verdaderamente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> extremely\n>\n> (extremadamente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> amazingly\n>\n> (sorprendentemente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> exceptionally\n>\n> (excepcionalmente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> incredibly\n>\n> (increíblemente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> remarkably\n>\n> (notablemente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> particularly\n>\n> (particularmente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> enough\n>\n> (suficiente)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** Kate is **really** __beautiful__.\n> **Translation:** (Kate es verdaderamente guapa.)\n\n> **Example:** Michael can run **very** __fast__.\n> **Translation:** (Michael puede correr muy rápido.)\n\n> **Example:** Sharks are **extremely** __dangerous__.\n> **Translation:** (Los tiburones son extremadamente peligrosos.)\n\n> **Example:** The restaurant was **remarkably** __empty__ for a Saturday.\n> **Translation:** (El restaurante estaba notablemente vacío para un sábado.)\n\n> **Example:** It's **incredibly** __kind__ of you to help.\n> **Translation:** (Es increíblemente amable de su parte de ayudar.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : \"\n> >\n> > Enough\n> >\n> > \" se puede usar como intensificador, pero ten cuidado porque\n> >\n> > \"enough\"\n> >\n> > se encuentra detrás del adjetivo que modifica.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Dan is not __old__ **enough** to vote.\n> > **Translation:** (Dan no tiene la edad suficiente para votar)\n>\n> > **Example:** My sister isn't __tall__ **enough** to ride on the roller coaster.\n> > **Translation:** (Mi hermana no es suficientemente alta para subir a la montaña rusa.)\n\n2. Cuando queremos indicar que algo o alguien es excepcional, podemos usar __los adjetivos fuertes__.\n\n> **Tip:** enormous\n>\n> (enorme)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> terrible\n>\n> (terrible)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> tiny\n>\n> (diminuto)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> excellent\n>\n> (excelente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> brilliant\n>\n> (brillante)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> perfect\n>\n> (perfecto)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> marvelous\n>\n> (maravilloso)\n>\n> ...\n\n**Como estos adjetivos fuertes ya indican un extremo** (\"enorme\" = \"muy grande\"), **no usamos el intensificador \"very\"**. Como intensificador para adjetivos fuertes, se usa generalmente: \"absolutamente\", \"excepcionalmente\", \"particularmente\", \"realmente\" o \"bastante\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Their house is **absolutely** __enormous__.\n> **Translation:** (Su casa es absolutamente enorme.)\n\n> **Example:** Her son is **exceptionally** __brilliant__.\n> **Translation:** (Su hijo es excepcionalmente brillante.)\n\n> **Example:** The dinner you made last night was **really** __marvelous__.\n> **Translation:** (La cena que hiciste ayer noche era realmente maravillosa.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Algunos intensificadores sólo se pueden usar con\n> >\n> > adjetivos\n> >\n> > particulares.\n>\n> ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** **dangerously** __ill__\n> > **Translation:** (peligrosamente enfermo)\n>\n> > **Example:** **dangerously** __fast__\n> > **Translation:** (peligrosamente rápido)\n>\n> > **Example:** **seriously** __injured__\n> > **Translation:** (seriamente herido)\n>\n> > **Example:** **seriously** __damaged__\n> > **Translation:** (seriamente dañado)\n>\n> > **Example:** **highly** __successful__\n> > **Translation:** (altamente exitosa)\n>\n> > **Example:** **highly** __intelligent__\n> > **Translation:** (altamente inteligente)\n>\n> > **Example:** **bitterly** __disappointed__\n> > **Translation:** (terriblemente decepcionado)\n>\n> > **Example:** **bitterly** __cold__\n> > **Translation:** (terriblemente frío)\n\n3. Con __adjetivos comparativos__ se usan palabras o frases particulares como intensificadores.\n\n> **Tip:** much\n>\n> (mucho)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> a lot\n>\n> (mucho)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> a great deal\n>\n> (mucho)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> a good bit\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Dave is **much** __faster__ than me.\n> **Translation:** (Dave es mucho más rápido que yo.)\n\n> **Example:** My brother is **a lot** __taller__ than my father.\n> **Translation:** (Mi hermano es mucho más grande que mi padre.)\n\n4. Con __adjetivos superlativos__ usamos lo siguiente:\n\n> **Tip:** easily\n>\n> (fácilmente)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> by far\n>\n> (sin duda)\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Paul is **by far** __the most intelligent__ person I know.\n> **Translation:** (Paul es sin duda la persona más inteligente que conozco.)\n\n> **Example:** Her essay was **easily** __the longest__ in the class.\n> **Translation:** (Su ensayo era fácilmente el más largo de la clase.)\n\n## Mitigators (Los mitigadores)\n\n1. Mientras los intensificadores refuerzan el sentido de un __adjetivo__, los mitigadores los debilitan.\n\n> **Tip:** fairly\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> rather\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> quite\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> pretty\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The movie was **fairly** __boring__.\n> **Translation:** (La película era bastante aburrida.)\n\n> **Example:** The students were **rather** __quiet__ in class.\n> **Translation:** (Los estudiantes eran bastante tranquilos en clase.)\n\n> **Example:** It's a **pretty** __nice__ day.\n> **Translation:** (Es un día bastante bonito.)\n\n> **Nota: \"Pretty\"** se usa en un inglés más informal.\n\n2. Con __adjetivos comparativos__ se usan las siguientes palabras o frases como mitigadores:\n\n> **Tip:** a bit\n>\n> (un poco)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> rather\n>\n> (bastante)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> a little bit\n>\n> (un poco)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> slightly\n>\n> (un poco)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Dave is **a bit** __faster__ than me.\n> **Translation:** (Dave es un poco más rápido que yo.)\n\n> **Example:** My brother is **slightly** __taller__ than my father.\n> **Translation:** (Mi hermano es un poco más alto que mi padre.)",
                "en": "**Intensifiers and mitigators** are used to vary the degree or strength of an adjective, verb or adverb.\n\n## Intensifiers\n\n1. Intensifiers add strength or force to the meaning of an __adjective__.\n\n> **Tip:** very,\n>\n> really,\n>\n> extremely,\n>\n> amazingly,\n>\n> exceptionally,\n>\n> incredibly,\n>\n> remarkably,\n>\n> particularly,\n>\n> enough...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Kate is **really** __beautiful__.\n\n> **Example:** Michael can run **very** __fast__.\n\n> **Example:** Sharks are **extremely** __dangerous__.\n\n> **Example:** The restaurant was **remarkably** __empty__ for a Saturday.\n\n> **Example:** It's **incredibly** __kind__ of you to help.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note:\n> >\n> > \"Enough\"\n> >\n> > can be used as an intensifier, but be careful, as \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" is found after the adjective it modifies.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Dan is not __old__ **enough** to vote.\n>\n> > **Example:** My sister isn't __tall__ **enough** to ride on the roller coaster.\n\n2. When we want to indicate that something or someone is exceptional, we can use __strong adjectives__.\n\n> **Tip:** enormous,\n>\n> terrible,\n>\n> tiny,\n>\n> excellent,\n>\n> brilliant,\n>\n> perfect,\n>\n> marvelous...\n\n**As these strong adjectives already indicate an extreme** (\"enormous\" = \"very big\"), **we do not use the intensifier \"very\"**. As an intensifier with strong adjectives, we generally use: \"**absolutely**\", \"**exceptionally**\", \"**particularly**\", \"**really**\" or \"**quite**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Their house is **absolutely** __enormous__.\n\n> **Example:** Her son is **exceptionally** __brilliant__.\n\n> **Example:** The dinner you made last night was **really** __marvelous__.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : Some intensifiers may only be used with particular\n> >\n> > adjectives\n> >\n> > .\n>\n> examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** **dangerously** __ill__\n>\n> > **Example:** **dangerously** __fast__\n>\n> > **Example:** **seriously** __injured__\n>\n> > **Example:** **seriously** __damaged__\n>\n> > **Example:** **highly** __successful__\n>\n> > **Example:** **highly** __intelligent__\n>\n> > **Example:** **bitterly** __disappointed__\n>\n> > **Example:** **bitterly** __cold__\n\n3. With __comparative adjectives__ we use particular words or phrases as intensifiers.\n\n> **Tip:** much,\n>\n> a lot,\n>\n> a great deal,\n>\n> a good bit...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Dave is **much** __faster__ than me.\n\n> **Example:** My brother is **a lot** __taller__ than my father.\n\n4. With __superlative adjectives__ we use the following:\n\n> **Tip:** easily,\n>\n> by far\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Paul is **by far** __the most intelligent__ person I know.\n\n> **Example:** Her essay was **easily** __the longest__ in the class.\n\n## Mitigators\n\n1. While intensifiers strengthen the meaning of an __adjective__, mitigators make them less strong.\n\n> **Tip:** fairly,\n>\n> rather,\n>\n> quite,\n>\n> pretty\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The movie was **fairly** __boring__.\n\n> **Example:** The students were **rather** __quiet__ in class.\n\n> **Example:** It's a **pretty** __nice__ day.\n\n> **Note: \"Pretty\"** is used in more informal English.\n\n2. With __comparative adjectives__ we use the following words and phrases as mitigators:\n\n> **Tip:** a bit,\n>\n> rather,\n>\n> a little bit,\n>\n> slightly\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Dave is **a bit** __faster__ than me.\n\n> **Example:** My brother is **slightly** __taller__ than my father."
              }
            },
