          "code": 21,
          "order": 5,
          "slug": {
            "es": "the-gerund-and-infinitive",
            "en": "the-gerund-and-infinitive"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "El gerundio e infinitivo",
            "en": "The Gerund and Infinitive"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 40,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "the-gerund-and-infinitive",
                "en": "the-gerund-and-infinitive"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El gerundio y infinitivo",
                "en": "The Gerund and Infinitive"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**El gerundio y el infinitivo son formas de los verbos que actúan como nombres**. El gerundio se forma con \"**-ing**\" (**walking**, **eating**, etc.). Como hemos visto en la lección sobre los verbos, el infinitivo se forma con la preposición \"**to**\" (**to walk**, **to eat**, etc.).\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n**1. Cuando un verbo sigue a otro verbo, siempre necesitamos usar el infinitivo o el gerundio**. Normalmente usamos el infinitivo después de algunos verbos y el gerundio después de otros. También hay verbos con los que podemos usar el gerundio o el infinitivo.\n\n| Verbo | Gerundio | Infinitivo |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| afford |  | X |\n| agree |  | X |\n| attempt |  | X |\n| begin | X | X |\n| choose |  | X |\n| continue | X | X |\n| decide |  | X |\n| detest | X |  |\n| enjoy | X |  |\n| expect |  | X |\n| fail |  | X |\n| finish | X |  |\n| hate | X | X |\n| hope |  | X |\n| imagine | X |  |\n| intend |  | X |\n| keep | X |  |\n| learn |  | X |\n| like | X | X |\n| love | X | X |\n| manage |  | X |\n| need |  | X |\n| offer |  | X |\n| plan |  | X |\n| prefer | X | X |\n| promise |  | X |\n| quit | X |  |\n| recommend | X |  |\n| refuse |  | X |\n| regret | X |  |\n| seem |  | X |\n| start | X | X |\n| suggest | X |  |\n| tend |  | X |\n| threaten |  | X |\n| tolerate | X |  |\n| try | X | X |\n| understand | X |  |\n| want |  | X |\n| wish | X | X |\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I can't __afford__ **to buy** a new car.\n> **Translation:** (No puedo permitirme comprar un coche nuevo.)\n\n> **Example:** He __began__ **to doubt** himself. / He __began__ **doubting** himself.\n> **Translation:** (Comenzó a dudar de sí mismo.)\n\n> **Example:** They __decided__ **to move** to Australia in May.\n> **Translation:** (Decidieron mudarse a Australia en Mayo.)\n\n> **Example:** I __enjoy__ **listening** to music.\n> **Translation:** (Disfruto escuchando música.)\n\n> **Example:** She __hates__ **studying**. / She __hates__ **to study**.\n> **Translation:** (Odia estudiar.)\n\n> **Example:** You __love__ **dancing**. / You __love__ **to dance**.\n> **Translation:** (Te encanta bailar.)\n\n> **Example:** He __needed__ **to leave** class early because he had an appointment.\n> **Translation:** (Tenía que salir de la clase pronto porque tenía una cita.)\n\n> **Example:** She can't __tolerate__ **complaining**.\n> **Translation:** (No puede tolerar quejas.)\n\n> **Example:** I __tried__ **learning** English. / I __tried__ **to learn** English.\n> **Translation:** (He intentado aprender inglés.)\n\n> **Example:** My mother could retire, but she __keeps__ **working**.\n> **Translation:** (Mi madre podría jubilarse, pero sigue trabajando.)\n\n**2. Podemos usar el gerundio o el infinitivo como objeto, sujeto o complemento de una frase,** pero en general, es mucho más común usar el gerundio como sujeto.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Objeto:__\n\n> **Example:** I like **cooking**. / I like **to cook**.\n> **Translation:** (Me gusta cocinar)\n\n> **Example:** She continued **working**. / She continued **to work**.\n> **Translation:** (Continuó trabajando.)\n\n__Sujeto:__\n\n> **Example:** **Swimming** is good exercise.\n> **Translation:** (Nadar es un buen ejercicio)\n\n> **Example:** **Drinking** and **driving** is dangerous.\n> **Translation:** (Beber y conducir es peligroso.)\n\n__Complemento:__\n\n> **Example:** The best thing to do when you are sick is **to drink** a lot of water.\n> **Translation:** (Lo mejor que puedes hacer cuando estás enfermo es beber mucha agua.)\n\n> **Example:** My favorite exercise is **swimming**.\n> **Translation:** (Mi ejercicio favorito es la natación.)\n\n**3. Con algunos verbos, cuando usamos el gerundio y el infinitivo, el significado cambia.**\n\n> **Tip:** forget\n>\n> (olvidar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> mean\n>\n> (significar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> remember\n>\n> (recordar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> stop\n>\n> (parar)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Gerundio:__\n\n> **Example:** I forgot **writing** that email.\n> **Translation:** (Me **olvidé que escribí** ese correo electrónico.)\n\n__Infinitivo:__\n\n> **Example:** I forgot **to write** that email.\n> **Translation:** (Me **olvidé de escribir** el correo electrónico.)\n\n__Gerundio:__\n\n> **Example:** Stop **watching** the news.\n> **Translation:** (**Deja** de ver las noticias)\n\n__Infinitivo:__\n\n> **Example:** Stop **to watch** the news.\n> **Translation:** (**Para**, para ver las noticias.)\n\n**4. Se usa el infinitivo después de __adjetivos.__**\n\n> **Tip:** disappointed\n>\n> (decepcionado)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> glad\n>\n> (contento)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> happy\n>\n> (feliz)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> pleased\n>\n> (satisfecho)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> relieved\n>\n> (aliviado)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> sad\n>\n> (triste)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> surprised\n>\n> (sorprendido)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I'm glad **to see** you.\n> **Translation:** (Me alegro de verte.)\n\n> **Example:** She was surprised **to find** the door unlocked.\n> **Translation:** (Se sorprendió al encontrar la puerta abierta.)\n\n**5. Después de __preposiciones__ solo podemos usar el gerundio.**\n\n> **Tip:** about\n>\n> (sobre)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> against\n>\n> (contra)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> at\n>\n> (a)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> after\n>\n> (después de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> before\n>\n> (antes)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> by\n>\n> (por)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> on\n>\n> (en)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> without\n>\n> (sin)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** He's good at **listening**.\n> **Translation:** (Escucha bien.)\n\n> **Example:** I always read before **going** to bed.\n> **Translation:** (Siempre leo antes de acostarme.)\n\n> **Example:** You can't leave without **saying** goodbye.\n> **Translation:** (No puedes salir sin despedirte.)\n\n**6. Se usa el gerundio después de unos __nombres__.**\n\n> **Tip:** advantage/disadvantage of\n>\n> (la ventaja de, la desventaja de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> danger of\n>\n> (el peligro de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> experience in\n>\n> (experiencia en)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> interested in\n>\n> (interesado en)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> opportunity of\n>\n> (oportunidad de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> reason for\n>\n> (la razón de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> problem with\n>\n> (el problema con)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** What is the advantage of **waiting**?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuál es la ventaja de esperar?)\n\n> **Example:** I am interested in **taking** English classes.\n> **Translation:** (Estoy interesado en tomar clases de inglés.)\n\n> **Example:** His problem **finding** a new job was his lack of experience.\n> **Translation:** (Su problema para encontrar un nuevo empleo era su falta de experiencia.)\n\n**7. Se usa el gerundio después de unas expresiones o verbos frasales.**\n\n> **Tip:** to look forward to\n>\n> (tener ganas de)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> to be worth\n>\n> (valer)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> can't help\n>\n> (no poder evitar)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> don't mind\n>\n> (no importarse)\n>\n> ,\n>\n> feel like\n>\n> (no apetecerse)\n>\n> ...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** We're really looking forward to **seeing** you.\n> **Translation:** (Tenemos muchas ganas de verte.)\n\n> **Example:** That movie is not worth **seeing**.\n> **Translation:** (No vale la pena ver esa película.)\n\n> **Example:** I can't help **falling** in love.\n> **Translation:** (No puedo evitar enamorarme.)",
                "en": "**The gerund and the infinitive are forms of verbs that act as nouns**. The gerund is formed using the ending \"**-ing**\" (**walking, eating, etc**...). As we saw in the verbs lesson, the infinitive is formed using the preposition \"**to**\" (**to walk, to eat, etc**...).\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n**1. When one verb is followed by another verb, that verb must be in the gerund or the infinitive.** Generally, we use the infinitive after some verbs and the gerund after others, but there are some verbs with which we can use either the gerund of the infinitive.\n\n| Verb | Gerund | Infinitive |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| afford |  | X |\n| agree |  | X |\n| attempt |  | X |\n| begin | X | X |\n| choose |  | X |\n| continue | X | X |\n| decide |  | X |\n| detest | X |  |\n| enjoy | X |  |\n| expect |  | X |\n| fail |  | X |\n| finish | X |  |\n| hate | X | X |\n| hope |  | X |\n| imagine | X |  |\n| intend |  | X |\n| keep | X |  |\n| learn |  | X |\n| like | X | X |\n| love | X | X |\n| manage |  | X |\n| need |  | X |\n| offer |  | X |\n| plan |  | X |\n| prefer | X | X |\n| promise |  | X |\n| quit | X |  |\n| recommend | X |  |\n| refuse |  | X |\n| regret | X |  |\n| seem |  | X |\n| start | X | X |\n| suggest | X |  |\n| tend |  | X |\n| threaten |  | X |\n| tolerate | X |  |\n| try | X | X |\n| understand | X |  |\n| want |  | X |\n| wish | X | X |\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I can't __afford__ **to buy** a new car.\n\n> **Example:** He __began__ **to doubt** himself. / He __began__ **doubting** himself.\n\n> **Example:** They __decided__ **to move** to Australia in May.\n\n> **Example:** I __enjoy__ **listening** to music.\n\n> **Example:** She __hates__ **studying**. / She __hates__ **to study**.\n\n> **Example:** You __love__ **dancing**. / You __love__ **to dance**.\n\n> **Example:** He __needed__ **to leave** class early because he had an appointment.\n\n> **Example:** She can't __tolerate__ **complaining**.\n\n> **Example:** I __tried__ **learning** English. / I __tried__ **to learn** English.\n\n> **Example:** My mother could retire, but she __keeps__ **working**.\n\n**2. We can use the gerund or the infinitive as the object, subject or complement of a sentence**, but in general it is more common to use the gerund as the subject.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Object:__\n\n> **Example:** I like **cooking**. / I like **to cook**.\n\n> **Example:** She continued **working**. / She continued **to work**.\n\n__Subject:__\n\n> **Example:** **Swimming** is good exercise.\n\n> **Example:** **Drinking** and **driving** is dangerous.\n\n__Complement:__\n\n> **Example:** The best thing to do when you are sick is **to drink** a lot of water.\n\n> **Example:** My favorite exercise is **swimming**.\n\n**3. With some verbs, the meaning of the sentence can change with the use of the gerund or the infinitive**.\n\n> **Tip:** forget,\n>\n> mean,\n>\n> remember,\n>\n> stop...\n\nExamples:\n\n__Gerund:__\n\n> **Example:** I forgot **writing** that email.\n> **Translation:** (**Meaning**: I wrote the email, but I forgot that I wrote it.)\n\n__Infinitive:__\n\n> **Example:** I forgot **to write** that email.\n> **Translation:** (**Meaning**: I never wrote the email.)\n\n__Gerund:__\n\n> **Example:** Stop **watching** the news.\n> **Translation:** (**Meaning**: Stop watching the news.)\n\n__Infinitive:__\n\n> **Example:** Stop **to watch** the news.\n> **Translation:** (**Meaning**: Stop what you are doing and watch the news.)\n\n**4. The infinitive is used after adjectives.**\n\n> **Tip:** disappointed,\n>\n> glad,\n>\n> happy,\n>\n> pleased,\n>\n> relieved,\n>\n> sad,\n>\n> surprised...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I'm glad **to see** you.\n\n> **Example:** She was surprised **to find** the door unlocked.\n\n**5. Only the gerund can be used after prepositions.**\n\n> **Tip:** about,\n>\n> against,\n>\n> at,\n>\n> after,\n>\n> before,\n>\n> by,\n>\n> on,\n>\n> without...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** He's good at **listening**.\n\n> **Example:** I always read before **going** to bed.\n\n> **Example:** You can't leave without **saying** goodbye.\n\n**6. The gerund is used after certain nouns.**\n\n> **Tip:** advantage/disadvantage of,\n>\n> danger of,\n>\n> experience in,\n>\n> interested in,\n>\n> opportunity of,\n>\n> reason for,\n>\n> problem with...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** What is the advantage of **waiting**?\n\n> **Example:** I am interested in **taking** an English class.\n\n> **Example:** His problem **finding** a new job was his lack of experience.\n\n**7. The gerund is also used after some expressions and phrasal verbs.**\n\n> **Tip:** to look forward to,\n>\n> to be worth,\n>\n> can't help,\n>\n> don't mind,\n>\n> feel like...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** We're really looking forward to **seeing** you.\n\n> **Example:** That movie was not worth **seeing**.\n\n> **Example:** I can't help **falling** in love."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 22,
          "order": 6,
          "slug": {
            "es": "questions",
            "en": "questions"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Preguntas",
            "en": "Questions"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 41,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "constructing-questions",
                "en": "constructing-questions"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Construir preguntas",
                "en": "Constructing Questions"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Hay dos tipos de preguntas: las preguntas cerradas y las preguntas abiertas.\n\n## Closed Questions (Preguntas Cerradas)\n\n**Las Preguntas cerradas requieren una respuesta \"yes\" o \"no\", \"right\" o \"wrong\"**. Ya hemos visto algunos ejemplos de preguntas cerradas en la lección de construir frases. Estas preguntas se forman con un verbo auxiliar (\"**do**\", \"**be**\" o \"**have got**\").\n\n**1. Con los verbos \"to be\" y \"have got\":**\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo + sujeto + sustantivo, adjetivo...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Is** she tall? **Yes**, she is.\n> **Translation:** (¿Ella es alta? Sí, lo es.)\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **got** a pet? **No**, I haven't.\n> **Translation:** (¿Tienes una mascota? No, no tengo.)\n\n**2. Todos los otros verbos:**\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to do) + sujeto + verbo principal + sustantivo, adjetivo...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Does** he work in a school? **No**, he doesn't.\n> **Translation:** (¿Trabaja en una escuela? No, no trabaja en una escuela.)\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you like New York? **Yes**, I did.\n> **Translation:** (¿Te gustó Nueva York? Sí, me gustó.)\n\n> **Example:** **Do** their children play sports? **Yes**, they do.\n> **Translation:** (¿Sus hijos juegan deportes? Sí, juegan.)\n\n## Open Questions (Preguntas abiertas)\n\n**Las Preguntas abiertas no se pueden contestar con un simple \"yes\" o \"no\", pero obtienen información, explicación, descripción u opinión**. Las preguntas abiertas se crean utilizando pronombres interrogativos o \"**question words**\". Dentro de las preguntas abiertas, podemos distinguir entre preguntas del objeto y preguntas del sujeto.\n\n| Pronombre interrogativo | Ejemplos |\n| --- | --- |\n| **What**...?<br>¿Qué...? | **What** do you want?<br>¿Qué quieres? |\n| **Where**...?<br>¿Dónde...? | **Where** do they live?<br>¿Dónde viven? |\n| **When**...?<br>¿Cuándo...? | **When** do you go to work?<br>¿Cuándo vas a tu trabajo? |\n| **Who**...?<br>¿Quién...? | **Who** is he?<br>¿Quién es él? |\n| **Whose**...?<br>¿De quién...? | **Whose** bag is this?<br>¿De quién es esta bolsa? |\n| **Why**...?<br>¿Por qué...? | **Why** are they here?<br>¿Por qué están aquí? |\n| **Which**...?<br>¿Cuál...? | **Which** car is his?<br>¿Cuál es su coche? |\n| **How**...?<br>¿Cómo...? | **How** are you?<br>¿Cómo estás? |\n\n**1. Con los verbos \"to be\" y \"have got\":**\n\n> **Tip:** Pronombre interrogativo + verbo + sujeto + sustantivo, adjetivo...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **What** have you got in your bag?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué tienes en tu bolsa?)\n\n> **Example:** **Where** are you?\n> **Translation:** (¿Dónde estás?)\n\n> **Example:** **When** is he available?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuándo está disponible?)\n\n> **Example:** **How** are the cookies?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cómo están las galletas?)\n\n**2. Todos los otros verbos:**\n\n> **Tip:** Pronombre interrogativo + verbo auxiliar (to do) + sujeto + verbo principal + sustantivo, adjetivo...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **What do** you like to eat?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué te gusta comer?)\n\n> **Example:** **Where does** she work?\n> **Translation:** (¿Dónde trabaja?)\n\n> **Example:** **When do** they go on vacation?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuándo se van de vacaciones?)\n\n> **Example:** **Why do** you study English?\n> **Translation:** (¿Por qué estudias inglés?)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : En las preguntas, a diferencia del español, las preposiciones se encuentran generalmente al final de la frase.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** What are you thinking **about**?\n> > **Translation:** (¿En qué estás pensando?)\n>\n> > **Example:** Where's she driving **to**?\n> > **Translation:** (¿A dónde conduce?)\n>\n> > **Example:** Who are they laughing **at**?\n> > **Translation:** (¿De quién te estás riendo?)\n\n### Object Questions (Preguntas del objeto)\n\n**Las Preguntas del objeto** solicitan el objeto de la frase y requieren el uso del verbo auxiliar \"**do**\".\n\n> **Tip:** Pronombre interrogativo + verbo auxiliar + sujeto + verbo (infinitivo)...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Who did** you call last night?\n> **Translation:** (¿A quién llamaste anoche?)\n\n> **Example:** **What did** you do to yourself?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué te has hecho?)\n\n### Subject Questions (Preguntas del sujeto)\n\n**Preguntas del sujeto** son aquellas en que el pronombre interrogativo o \"**question word**\" sirve como el sujeto de la frase. En las preguntas del sujeto, no se utiliza un verbo auxiliar y el orden de las palabras no se invierte.\n\n> **Tip:** Pronombre interrogativo + verbo + objeto...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Who** called last night?\n> **Translation:** (¿Quién llamó anoche?)\n\n> **Example:** **What** happened to you?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué te ha pasado?)\n\n**Mira otra vez la diferencia entre preguntas del objeto y preguntas del sujeto:**\n\n__Frase principal:__\n\n> **Example:** Danny asks the teacher a question.\n> **Translation:** (Danny pregunta al profesor.)\n\n__Pregunta del objeto:__\n\n> **Example:** **Who did** Danny ask? The teacher.\n> **Translation:** (¿A quién preguntó Danny? Al profesor.)\n\n__Pregunta del sujeto:__\n\n> **Example:** **Who** asked the question? Danny.\n> **Translation:** (¿Quién preguntó? Danny.)\n\n> **Nota**: En la pregunta del objeto anterior, Danny es el sujeto. En la pregunta del sujeto, \"**who**\" actúa como sujeto.",
                "en": "## There are 2 types of questions:\n\n> **Example:** **Does** he work in a school? **No**, he doesn't.\n\n**1. Closed questions require a \"yes\" or \"no\", \"right\" or \"wrong\" response**.\n\n> **Example:** **Do** their children play sports? **Yes**, they do.\n\nThese questions are formed using an auxiliary verb, in this case \"**do**\".\n\n> **Example:** **Is** she tall? **Yes**, she is.\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **got** a pet? **No**, I haven't.\n\nWith the verbs \"**be**\" and \"**have got**\", closed questions begin with the verb.\n\n---\n\n> **Example:** **Where** does she work?\n\n**2. Open questions cannot be answered with a simple \"yes\" or \"no\", but elicit information, explanation, description or opinion**.\n\n> **Example:** **What** do you like to eat?\n\nOpen questions are created using **interrogative pronouns** or **question words**.\n\n> **Example:** **What** are you thinking __about__?\n\n> **Note**: In questions, __prepositions__ are generally found at the end of the sentence.\n\n> **Example:** **Who did** you call last night?\n\nWithin open questions, we can distinguish between object questions and subject questions. **Object questions** ask for the object of a sentence and require the use of the auxiliary verb \"**do**\".\n\n> **Example:** **Who called** last night?\n\n**Subject questions** are those questions in which the interrogative pronoun or question word acts as the subject of the sentence. In subject questions, we do not use an auxiliary verb and the word order is not inverted."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 42,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "question-tags",
                "en": "question-tags"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Las preguntas coletilla",
                "en": "Question Tags"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**En inglés es frecuente terminar las frases con otra frase corta, de signo contrario, la cual tiene la intención de pedir la opinión o buscar la aprobación del interlocutor: son las llamadas question tags (preguntas coletillas)**. Estas frases equivalen a: ¿verdad?, ¿no es verdad?, ¿no?, ¿no es así? ¿en serio?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** You eat meat, **don't you?**\n> **Translation:** (Comes carne, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** She doesn't like to dance, **does she?**\n> **Translation:** (No le gusta bailar, ¿no?)\n\n> **Example:** Alex and Sergio are friends, **aren't they?**\n> **Translation:** (Alex y Sergio son amigos, ¿no?)\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n**Para formar esta pregunta corta utilizaremos el auxiliar de la frase principal y su sujeto pero de signo contrario**. Si no tuviera auxiliar entonces utilizaríamos el auxiliar **\"to do\"**.\n\nSi la oración es afirmativa, la pregunta coletilla es negativa y viceversa.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Oraciones afirmativas__\n\n> **Example:** Your brother is older than you, **isn't he?**\n> **Translation:** (Tu hermano es mayor que tú, ¿no es así?)\n\n> **Example:** You can help me, **can't you?**\n> **Translation:** (Puedes ayudarme, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** John is getting married, **isn't he?**\n> **Translation:** (John se casará, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** You worked yesterday, **didn't you?**\n> **Translation:** (Trabajaste ayer, ¿no?)\n\n> **Example:** Sarah likes ice cream, **doesn't she?**\n> **Translation:** (A Sarah le gusta el helado, ¿no?)\n\n__Oraciones negativas__\n\n> **Example:** You're not from here, **are you?**\n> **Translation:** (No eres de aquí, ¿no?)\n\n> **Example:** Kate's not American, **is she?**\n> **Translation:** (Kate no es americana, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** Peter never liked Susan, **did he?**\n> **Translation:** (A Peter nunca le gustó Susan, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** They didn't go to class yesterday, **did they?**\n> **Translation:** (No fueron a la clase ayer, ¿verdad?)\n\n> **Example:** You can't dance, **can you?**\n> **Translation:** (No puedes bailar, ¿no?)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Ten cuidado con los verbos\n> >\n> > \"to have\"\n> >\n> > y\n> >\n> > \"to have got\"\n> >\n> > .\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> __To have got:__\n>\n> > **Example:** They've got a dog, **haven't they?**\n> > **Translation:** (Tienen un perro, ¿no?)\n>\n> __To have:__\n>\n> > **Example:** They have a dog, **don't they?**\n> > **Translation:** (Tienen un perro, ¿no?)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Exception:** **Excepción**: Con el verbo **\"to be\"** en la primera persona de oraciones negativas, se usa **\"aren't\"** en la pregunta coletilla.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** I am not wrong, **am I**?\n>\n> > **Example:** I am wrong, **aren't I**?",
                "en": "**In English it is common to add a short question to the end of an affirmative or negative sentence. These short questions are known as question tags** and they are used to ask the opinion or seek the approval of the person with whom we are speaking.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** You eat meat, **don't you?**\n\n> **Example:** She doesn't like to dance, **does she?**\n\n> **Example:** Alex and Sergio are friends, **aren't they?**\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n**To form question tags, we use the auxiliary verb from the main phrase in the opposite form plus the subject**. If there is no auxiliary in the main phrase, we use \"**to do**\".\n\nIf the sentence is affirmative, the question tag is therefore in the negative and vice versa.\n\nExamples:\n\n__Affirmative sentences:__\n\n> **Example:** Your brother is older than you, **isn't he?**\n\n> **Example:** You can help me, **can't you?**\n\n> **Example:** John is getting married, **isn't he?**\n\n> **Example:** You worked yesterday, **didn't you?**\n\n> **Example:** Sarah likes ice cream, **doesn't she?**\n\n__Negative sentences:__\n\n> **Example:** You're not from here, **are you?**\n\n> **Example:** Kate's not American, **is she?**\n\n> **Example:** Peter never liked Susan, **did he?**\n\n> **Example:** They didn't go to class yesterday, **did they?**\n\n> **Example:** You can't dance, **can you?**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : Be careful with the verbs \"\n> >\n> > to have\n> >\n> > \" and \"\n> >\n> > have got\n> >\n> > \".\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> __To have got:__\n>\n> > **Example:** They've got a dog, **haven't they?**\n>\n> __To have:__\n>\n> > **Example:** They have a dog, **don't they?**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Exception:** With the verb \"**to be**\" in the first person in affirmative sentences, we use the third person in the question tag (\"**aren't**\").\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** I am not wrong, **am I**?\n>\n> > **Example:** I am wrong, **aren't I**?"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 43,
              "order": 3,
              "slug": {
                "es": "what-vs-which",
                "en": "what-vs-which"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "¿Cuál?/¿Qué?",
                "en": "What vs. Which"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**\"What\" y \"which\" son dos pronombres interrogativos que se confunden con frecuencia**. A continuación se presenta una explicación de los diferentes usos de estos pronombres.\n\n## What\n\nSe utiliza **\"what\"** para hacer una pregunta cuando hay un número desconocido o infinitas posibilidades de respuestas u opciones. **Se usa para preguntar en general.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **What** is your favorite food?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuál es tu comida favorita?)\n\n> **Example:** **What** did you do yesterday?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué hiciste ayer?)\n\n> **Example:** **What** type of music do you like?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué tipo de música te gusta?)\n\n> **Example:** **What** would you like to drink?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué te gustaría beber?)\n\n## Which\n\nEn contraste con \"**what**\", **usamos \"which\" cuando las opciones posibles son limitadas a un pequeño número** (quizás 2, 3 o 4) y hay que seleccionar una entre ellas. Se puede utilizar tanto con cosas como con personas.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Which** jacket should I buy, the brown one or the black one?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué chaqueta debería comprar, la marrón o la negra?)\n\n> **Example:** **Which** of you would like to help me?\n> **Translation:** (¿A cuál de vosotros le gustaría ayudarme?)\n\n> **Example:** **Which** would you like, wine or beer?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué quieres, vino o cerveza?)\n\n> **Nota:** El uso de **\"what\"** y **\"which\"** en inglés está determinado por las respuestas posibles a diferencia del español donde las reglas de uso de \"¿qué?\" y \"¿cuál?\" están determinadas por la sintaxis.",
                "en": "**\"What\" and \"which\" are two interrogative pronouns that are frequently confused.** Below is an explanation of the different uses of these pronouns.\n\n## What\n\n\"**What**\" is used to ask a question when there is an unknown or infinite number of possible answers or options. It is **used for asking questions in general.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **What** is your favorite food?\n\n> **Example:** **What** did you do yesterday?\n\n> **Example:** **What** type of music do you like?\n\n> **Example:** **What** would you like to drink?\n\n## Which\n\nIn contrast to \"**what**\", **we use \"which\" when the possible answers are limited to a small quantity** (perhaps 2, 3 or 4) and it is necessary to choose among them. This interrogative pronoun can be used with both things and people.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Which** jacket should I buy, the brown one or the black one?\n\n> **Example:** **Which** of you would like to help me?\n\n> **Example:** **Which** would you like, wine or beer?"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 23,
          "order": 7,
          "slug": {
            "es": "verb-tenses-past",
            "en": "verb-tenses-past"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Tiempos verbales: El pasado",
            "en": "Verb Tenses: Past"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 44,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "past-simple",
                "en": "past-simple"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El pasado simple",
                "en": "Past Simple"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Hay muchas maneras de hablar del pasado en inglés, pero el pasado simple es la forma más común**. El pasado simple en inglés es equivalente al pretérito imperfecto y pretérito indefinido del español. **Usamos el pasado simple para acciones completas en el pasado**. El período de tiempo de estas acciones no es importante como en el español. En el pasado simple hay verbos regulares y verbos irregulares.\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Form (Forma)\n\nPara formar el pasado simple con verbos regulares, usamos el infinitivo y añadimos la terminación \"**-ed**\". La forma es la misma para todas las personas (I, you, he, she, it, we, they).\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** want → **wanted**\n\n> **Example:** learn → **learned**\n\n> **Example:** stay → **stayed**\n\n> **Example:** walk → **walked**\n\n> **Example:** show → **showed**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Exception:** **Excepciones:**\n>\n> 1. Para verbos que terminan en una **\"e\"**, sólo añadimos \"**-d**\".\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** change → **changed**\n>\n> > **Example:** believe → **believed**\n>\n> 2. Si el verbo termina en una vocal corta y una consonante (excepto **\"y\"** o **\"w\"**), doblamos la consonante final.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** stop → **stopped**\n>\n> > **Example:** commit → **committed**\n>\n> 3. Con verbos que terminan en una consonante y una **\"y\"**, se cambia la **\"y\"** por una **\"i\"**.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** study → **studied**\n>\n> > **Example:** try → **tried**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota: Hay muchos verbos irregulares en inglés.\n> >\n> > Desafortunadamente, no hay una norma establecida para formarlos. A continuación tienes los tres verbos irregulares más comunes y los que actúan como verbos auxiliares.\n>\n> | Verb | Past simple |\n> | --- | --- |\n> | be | **was** (I, he, she, it)<br>**were** (you, we, they) |\n> | do | **did** |\n> | have | **had** |\n\n### Pronunciation (Pronunciación)\n\nPronunciamos la terminación **\"-ed\"** de forma diferente dependiendo de la letra que va al final del infinitivo. En general la **\"e\"** es muda.\n\n1. Con los infinitivos que terminan en **\"p\"**, **\"f\"**, **\"k\"** o **\"s\"** (consonantes sordas, excepto **\"t\"**) pronunciamos la terminación **\"-ed\"** como una **\"t\"**.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** looked\n> **Translation:** [lukt]\n\n> **Example:** kissed\n> **Translation:** [kisst]\n\n2. Con los infinitivos que terminan en **\"b\"**, **\"g\"**, **\"l\"**, **\"m\"**, **\"n\"**, **\"v\"**, **\"z\"** (consonantes sonoras, excepto **\"d\"**) o una vocal, pronunciamos sólo la **\"d\"**.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** yelled\n> **Translation:** [jeld]\n\n> **Example:** cleaned\n> **Translation:** [klind]\n\n3. Con los infinitivos que terminan en **\"d\"** o **\"t\"**, pronunciamos la **\"e\"** como una **\"i\"**.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** ended\n> **Translation:** [endid]\n\n> **Example:** waited\n> **Translation:** [weitid]\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo principal...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** She **was** a doctor.\n> **Translation:** (Era doctora.)\n\n> **Example:** The keys **were** in the drawer.\n> **Translation:** (Las llaves estaban en el cajón.)\n\n> **Example:** I **wanted** to dance.\n> **Translation:** (Quería bailar.)\n\n> **Example:** They **learned** English.\n> **Translation:** (Aprendieron inglés.)\n\n> **Example:** We **believed** him.\n> **Translation:** (Le creímos.)\n\n> **Example:** I **bought** a blue car.\n> **Translation:** (Compré un coche azul.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n__To be:__\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"to be\" + \"not\"...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** She **wasn't** a doctor.\n> **Translation:** (Ella no era doctora.)\n\n> **Example:** The keys **weren't** in the drawer.\n> **Translation:** (Las llaves no estaban en el cajón.)\n\n> **Nota**: El verbo **\"to have got\"**, que en el presente simple sigue las mismas reglas que el verbo **\"to be\"**, no puede ser utilizado en el pasado. Para indicar la posesión en el pasado, usamos el verbo **\"to have\"**.\n\n__Todos los verbos demás:__\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to do) + \"not\" + verbo principal (en infinitivo)...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't want** to dance.\n> **Translation:** (No quería bailar.)\n\n> **Example:** They **didn't learn** English.\n> **Translation:** (No aprendieron inglés)\n\n> **Example:** We **didn't believe** him.\n> **Translation:** (No le creímos.)\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't buy** a blue car.\n> **Translation:** (No compré un coche azul.)\n\n> **Nota**: En frases negativas, el verbo auxiliar va en pasado (\"**did**\") y el verbo principal se queda en el infinitivo.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n__To be:__\n\n> **Tip:** \"To be\" + sujeto...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Was** she a doctor?\n> **Translation:** (¿Era doctora?)\n\n> **Example:** **Were** the keys in the drawer?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estaban las llaves en el cajón?)\n\n__Todos los demás verbos:__\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to do) + sujeto + verbo principal (en infinitivo)...?\n\n__Ejemplos__\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **want** to dance?\n> **Translation:** (¿Querías bailar?)\n\n> **Example:** **Did** they **learn** English?\n> **Translation:** (¿Aprendieron inglés?)\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **believe** him?\n> **Translation:** (¿Le creíste?)\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **buy** a blue car?\n> **Translation:** (¿Compraste un coche azul?)\n\n> **Nota:** Al igual que en las frases negativas, el verbo auxiliar va en pasado (**\"did\"**) y el verbo principal se queda en el infinitivo.\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n**1. El pasado simple se utiliza para hablar de una acción concreta que comenzó y acabó en el pasado**. En este caso equivale al pretérito indefinido español. Generalmente, lo usamos con adverbios de tiempo como **\"last year\"**, **\"yesterday\"**, **\"last night\"**...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Tom **stayed** at home __last night__.\n> **Translation:** (Tom se quedó en casa anoche.)\n\n> **Example:** Kate **worked** __last Saturday__.\n> **Translation:** (Kate trabajó el sábado pasado.)\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't go** to the party __yesterday__.\n> **Translation:** (No fui a la fiesta ayer.)\n\n> **Example:** **Did** they **walk** to school __this morning__?\n> **Translation:** (¿Han andado a la escuela esta mañana?)\n\n**2. Se usa el pasado simple para un serie de acciones en el pasado.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **received** the good news and immediately **called** my husband.\n> **Translation:** (Recibí la buena noticia y llamé de inmediato a mi marido.)\n\n> **Example:** He **studied** for an hour in the morning, **worked** all afternoon and **didn't return** home until 10 at night.\n> **Translation:** (Estudió durante una hora por la mañana, trabajó toda la tarde y no regresó a casa hasta las 10 de la noche.)\n\n**3. También lo usamos para acciones repetidas o habituales en el pasado**, como se usa el pretérito imperfecto español.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** We always **traveled** to Cancun for vacation when we were young.\n> **Translation:** (Siempre viajábamos a Cancun durante las vacaciones cuando éramos jóvenes.)\n\n> **Example:** He **walked** 5 kilometers every day to work.\n> **Translation:** (Caminaba 5 kilómetros hasta el trabajo cada día.)\n\n**4. Lo usamos para narraciones o acciones de períodos de largo tiempo en el pasado**, como el pretérito imperfecto español.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **worked** for many years in a museum.\n> **Translation:** (Trabajaba en un museo durante muchos años.)\n\n> **Example:** She **didn't eat** meat for years.\n> **Translation:** (No comía carne durante años.)\n\n**5. Se utiliza para hablar de generalidades o hechos del pasado.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The Aztec **lived** in Mexico.\n> **Translation:** (Los aztecas vivían en México)\n\n> **Example:** I **played** the guitar when I was a child.\n> **Translation:** (Tocaba la guitarra cuando era niño.)",
                "en": "**There are several tenses for speaking about the past in English, but the past simple is the most commonly used. It is used for actions completed in the past**. In the past tense there are both regular verbs and irregular verbs.\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Form\n\nTo form the past simple of regular verbs we add the ending \"**-ed**\" to the verb. The form is the same for all persons (I, you, he, she, it, we, they).\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** want → **wanted**\n\n> **Example:** learn → **learned**\n\n> **Example:** stay → **stayed**\n\n> **Example:** walk → **walked**\n\n> **Example:** show → **showed**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Exceptions:**\n>\n> 1. For verbs that end in \"**e**\", we only need to add \"**-d**\":\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** change → **changed**\n>\n> > **Example:** believe → **believed**\n>\n> 2. If the verb ends in a short vowel plus a consonant (except \"**y**\" o \"**w**\"), we double the final consonant:\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** stop → **stopped**\n>\n> > **Example:** commit → **committed**\n>\n> 3. When the verb ends in a consonant and \"**y**\", the \"**y**\" becomes an \"**i**\":\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** study → **studied**\n>\n> > **Example:** try → **tried**\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note: There are many irregular verbs in English\n> >\n> > and unfortunately there are no fixed rules for forming them. Below are the three most commonly used irregular verbs which also are used as auxiliary verbs.\n>\n> | Verb | Past simple |\n> | --- | --- |\n> | be | **was** (I, he, she, it)<br>**were** (you, we, they) |\n> | do | **did** |\n> | have | **had** |\n\n### Pronunciation\n\nThe pronunciation of the ending \"**-ed**\" is different depending on the letter with which the verb ends. In general though, the \"**e**\" is silent.\n\n1. For those verbs which end in \"**p**\", \"**f**\", \"**k**\" o \"**s**\" (voiceless consonants, except \"**t**\"), we pronounce the \"**-ed**\" as a \"**t**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** looked\n> **Translation:** [lukt]\n\n> **Example:** kissed\n> **Translation:** [kisst]\n\n2. For those verbs which end in \"**b**\", \"**g**\", \"**l**\", \"**m**\", \"**n**\", \"**v**\", \"**z**\" (voiced consonants, except \"**d**\") or a vowel, we pronounce only the \"**d**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** yelled\n> **Translation:** [jeld]\n\n> **Example:** cleaned\n> **Translation:** [klind]\n\n3. Verbs that end in \"**d**\" o \"**t**\", we pronounce the \"**e**\" as an \"**i**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** ended\n> **Translation:** [endid]\n\n> **Example:** waited\n> **Translation:** [weitid]\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + principal verb...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** She **was** a doctor.\n\n> **Example:** The keys **were** in the drawer.\n\n> **Example:** I **wanted** to dance.\n\n> **Example:** They **learned** English.\n\n> **Example:** We **believed** him.\n\n> **Example:** I **bought** a blue car.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n__To be:__\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"to be\" + \"not\"...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** She **wasn't** a doctor.\n\n> **Example:** The keys **weren't** in the drawer.\n\n> **Note:** The verb \"**to have got**\", which in the present simple follows the same rules as \"**to be**\", cannot be used in the past. To indicate possession in the past, we use the verb \"**to have**\".\n\n__All other verbs:__\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to do) + \"not\" + principal verb (in infinitive)...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't want** to dance.\n\n> **Example:** They **didn't learn** English.\n\n> **Example:** We **didn't believe** him.\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't buy** a blue car.\n\n> **Note**: As in the present simple, in negative sentences in the past simple the auxiliary verb is conjugated (\"**did**\") and the principal verb remains in the infinitive.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n__To be:__\n\n> **Tip:** \"To be\" + subject...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Was** she a doctor?\n\n> **Example:** **Were** the keys in the drawer?\n\n__All other verbs:__\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to do) + subject + principal verb...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **want** to dance?\n\n> **Example:** **Did** they **learn** English?\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **believe** him?\n\n> **Example:** **Did** you **buy** a blue car?\n\n> **Note:** As with negative sentences, the auxiliary verb is conjugated (\"**did**\") and the principal verb remains in the infinitive.\n\n## Uses\n\n**1. The past simple is used to talk about a specific action or event that began and ended in the past**. It is generally used with adverbs of time such as \"**last year**\", \"**yesterday**\", \"**last night**\"...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Tom **stayed** at home __last night__.\n\n> **Example:** Kate **worked** __last Saturday__.\n\n> **Example:** I **didn't go** to the party __yesterday__.\n\n> **Example:** **Did** they **walk** to school __this morning__?\n\n**2. The past simple is used to talk about a series of actions that occurred in the past.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **received** the good news and immediately **called** my husband.\n\n> **Example:** He **studied** for an hour in the morning, **worked** all afternoon and **didn't return** home until 10 at night.\n\n**3. We also use the past simple for repeated actions or habits in the past.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** We always **traveled** to Cancun for vacation when we were young.\n\n> **Example:** He **walked** 5 kilometers every day to work.\n\n**4. The past simple is also used for narrations or actions that occurred over a long period of time in the past.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **worked** for many years in a museum.\n\n> **Example:** She **didn't eat** meat for years.\n\n**5. We use the past simple to speak about facts or things in the past in general.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The Aztec **lived** in Mexico.\n\n> **Example:** I **played** the guitar when I was a child."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 45,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "past-continuous",
                "en": "past-continuous"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El pasado continuo",
                "en": "Past Continuous"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**El pasado continuo se utiliza para acciones que estaban pasando en un momento específico en el pasado**. Como el presente continuo, se forma con el verbo auxiliar \"**to be**\" y el verbo+ing.\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Form (Forma)\n\n**Para formar el pasado continuo se utiliza el verbo auxiliar \"to be\" y el verbo+ing.** El verbo auxiliar \"**to be**\" está en el pasado simple, pero ten en cuenta que \"**to be**\" es un verbo irregular.\n\n| Sujeto | Auxiliar (to be) | Verb+ing |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I, he, she, it | **was** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| you, we, they | **were** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **was talking**.\n> **Translation:** (Estaba hablando.)\n\n> **Example:** He **was eating**.\n> **Translation:** (Estaba comiendo.)\n\n> **Example:** They **were learning**.\n> **Translation:** (Estaban aprendiendo.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + \"not\" + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **was not [wasn't] talking**.\n> **Translation:** (No estaba hablando.)\n\n> **Example:** He **was not [wasn't] eating**.\n> **Translation:** (No estaba comiendo.)\n\n> **Example:** They **were not [weren't] learning**.\n> **Translation:** (No estaban aprendiendo.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to be) + sujeto + verbo+ing?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Were** you **talking**?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estabas hablando?)\n\n> **Example:** **Was** he **eating**?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estaba comiendo?)\n\n> **Example:** **Were** they **learning**?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estaban aprendiendo?)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n**1. El pasado continuo se usa para una acción en desarrollo en el pasado cuando otra acción la interrumpe.** La acción que interrumpe está en __el pasado simple__. \"**__When__**\" y \"**__while__**\" señalan el uso del pasado simple y continuo. En general, usamos el pasado simple directamente después de \"**when**\" y el pasado continuo después de \"**while**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Jose called __while__ I **was watching** the news.\n> **Translation:** (Jose llamó mientras estaba mirando las noticias.)\n\n> **Example:** He **was walking** to work __when__ he fell.\n> **Translation:** (Estaba caminando hacia su trabajo cuando se cayó.)\n\n> **Example:** **Was** it **raining** __when__ you left?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estaba lloviendo cuando te fuiste?)\n\n**2. Se usa el pasado continuo para hablar sobre acciones en un __tiempo específico__ en el pasado.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Paula **wasn't living** in Spain in __2005__.\n> **Translation:** (Paula no estaba viviendo en España en el 2005.)\n\n> **Example:** We **were** still **working** at __10 o'clock__ last night.\n> **Translation:** (Todavía estábamos trabajando a las 10 anoche. )\n\n**3. Se usa el pasado continuo para dos acciones que estaban ocurriendo al mismo tiempo en el pasado.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** My son **was reading** __while__ I **was cooking**.\n> **Translation:** (Mi hijo estaba leyendo mientras que yo estaba cocinando.)\n\n> **Example:** They **were talking** very loudly while we **were trying** to watch the movie.\n> **Translation:** (Estaban hablando muy alto mientras nosotros estábamos intentando mirar la película.)\n\n> **Nota:** Hay unos verbos que no solemos usar en los tiempos continuos. Ver una lista y explicación en la lección de los tiempos continuos de los verbos.",
                "en": "**The past continuous tense is used for actions that occurred at a specific time in the past**. Like the present continuous, it is formed using the verb \"**to be**\" as well as the verb+ing.\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Form\n\n**To form the past continuous we use the auxiliary verb \"to be\" as well as the verb+ing.** The auxiliary verb \"**to be**\" is in the past simple tense, but keep in mind that \"**to be**\" is an irregular verb.\n\n| Subject | Auxiliary (to be) | Gerund |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I, he, she, it | **was** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| you, we, they | **were** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + verb+ing.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **was talking**.\n\n> **Example:** He **was eating**.\n\n> **Example:** They **were learning**.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"not\" + verb+ing.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **was not [wasn't] talking**.\n\n> **Example:** He **was not [wasn't] eating**.\n\n> **Example:** They **were not [weren't] learning**.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to be) + subject + verb+ing?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Were** you **talking**?\n\n> **Example:** **Was** he **eating**?\n\n> **Example:** **Were** they **learning**?\n\n## Uses\n\n**1. The past continuous is used for an action in progress in the past and that was interrupted.** The action that caused the interruption is in the __past simple__. \"**__When__**\" and \"**__while__**\" signal the use of the past simple and past continuous. In general, we use the past simple directly after \"**when**\" and the past continuous after \"**while**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Jose called __while__ I **was watching** the news.\n\n> **Example:** He **was walking** to work __when__ he fell.\n\n> **Example:** **Was** it **raining** __when__ you left?\n\n**2. We use the past continuous to talk about actions or events that happened at a __specific time__ in the past.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Paula **wasn't living** in Spain in __2005__.\n\n> **Example:** We **were** still **working** at __10 o'clock__ last night.\n\n**3. The past continuous is used for two actions that were occurring simultaneously in the past.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** My son **was reading** __while__ I **was cooking**.\n\n> **Example:** They **were talking** very loudly __while__ we **were trying** to watch the movie.\n\n> **Note**: As we have seen, there are some verbs which may not be used in the continuous tenses. Further explanation, as well as a list of such verbs that cannot be used in the continuous tenses can be found in the lesson on the continuous verb tenses."
              }
            },
