              "view": {
                "es": "Hay dos formas principales para expresar **el futuro**. A veces son intercambiables, pero a menudo pueden tener significados diferentes.\n\n## Future: \"Will\"\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n> **Nota:** Existe una forma corta del verbo modal \"**will**\" tanto en el afirmativo como en el negativo.\n\n| Afirmativo | Forma corta | Negativo | Forma corta |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| I will | **I'll** | I will not | I **won't**<br>**I'll** not |\n| you will | **you'll** | you will not | you **won't**<br>**you'll** not |\n| he will | **he'll** | he will not | he **won't**<br>**he'll** not |\n| she will | **she'll** | she will not | she **won't**<br>**she'll** not |\n| it will | **it'll** | it will not | it **won't**<br>**it'll** not |\n| we will | **we'll** | we will not | we **won't**<br>**we'll** not |\n| they will | **they'll** | they will not | they **won't**<br>**they'll** not |\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will\" + verbo principal.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **will [I'll] call** you tonight.\n> **Translation:** (Te llamaré esta noche.)\n\n> **Example:** She **will [She'll] arrive** late.\n> **Translation:** (Llegará tarde.)\n\n> **Example:** They **will [They'll] be** happy to see you.\n> **Translation:** (Estarán felices de verte.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will\" + \"not\" + verbo principal.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **will not [won't] call** you tonight.\n> **Translation:** (No te llamaré esta noche.)\n\n> **Example:** She **will not [won't] arrive** late.\n> **Translation:** (No llegará tarde.)\n\n> **Example:** They **will not [won't] be** happy to see you.\n> **Translation:** (No estarán felices de verte.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + sujeto + verbo principal?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **call** me tonight?\n> **Translation:** (¿Me llamarás esta noche?)\n\n> **Example:** **Will** she **arrive** late?\n> **Translation:** (¿Llegará tarde?)\n\n> **Example:** **Will** they **be** happy to see you?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estarán felices de verte?)\n\n## Future: \"Going to\"\n\n\"**Going to**\" equivale a \"**ir a**\" en español.\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + \"going to\" + verbo principal.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **am going to call** you tonight.\n> **Translation:** (Voy a llamarte esta noche.)\n\n> **Example:** She **is going to arrive** late.\n> **Translation:** (Va a llegar tarde.)\n\n> **Example:** They **are going to be** happy to see you.\n> **Translation:** (Van a estar felices de verte.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to\" + verbo principal.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **am not going to call** you tonight.\n> **Translation:** (No voy a llamarte esta noche.)\n\n> **Example:** She **is not going to arrive** late.\n> **Translation:** (No va a llegar tarde.)\n\n> **Example:** They **are not going to be** happy to see you.\n> **Translation:** (No van a estar felices de verte.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to be) + sujeto + \"going to\" + verbo principal?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Are** you **going to call** me tonight?\n> **Translation:** (¿Vas a llamarme esta noche?)\n\n> **Example:** **Is** she **going to arrive** late?\n> **Translation:** (¿Va a llegar tarde?)\n\n> **Example:** **Are** they **going to be** happy to see you?\n> **Translation:** (¿Van a estar felices de verte?)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Para acciones o eventos inminentes, podemos decir \"\n> >\n> > about to\n> >\n> > \" (a punto de). La estructura es la misma de \"\n> >\n> > going to\n> >\n> > \".\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** I **am about to leave**.\n> > **Translation:** (Estoy a punto de irme.)\n>\n> > **Example:** The concert **is about to begin**.\n> > **Translation:** (El concierto está a punto de comenzar.)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\nLas formas \"**will**\" y \"**going to**\" se utilizan para expresar el futuro. **La diferencia entre \"going to\" y \"will\" es el sentido de planificación y probabilidad de que suceda una acción.** En general, se usa \"**going to**\" para planes concretos, cuando estamos seguros de que algo va a suceder.\n\n**1. Se usa \"will\" con acciones voluntarias.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **help** me move?\n> **Translation:** (¿Me ayudarás a mudarme?)\n\n> **Example:** They **will clean** their rooms.\n> **Translation:** (Limpiarán sus habitaciones.)\n\n> **Example:** She **won't work** with Paul.\n> **Translation:** (No trabajará con Paul.)\n\n**2. Se utiliza \"will\" para expresar una promesa.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** When I am president, I **will lower** taxes.\n> **Translation:** (Cuando sea presidente, bajaré los impuestos.)\n\n> **Example:** He promises he **will call** when he arrives.\n> **Translation:** (Promete que llamará cuando llegue.)\n\n**3. Se usa \"going to\" para planes.** Se indica la intención de hacer algo.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** We **are going to have** a party tonight.\n> **Translation:** (Vamos a dar una fiesta esta noche.)\n\n> **Example:** Richard **is going to take** an English class.\n> **Translation:** (Richard va a realizar un clase de inglés.)\n\n> **Example:** **Are** they **going to play** football later?\n> **Translation:** (¿Van a jugar a fútbol luego?)\n\n**4. Se puede usar \"will\" o \"going to\" para hacer predicciones**. Cuando hay evidencia de que algo va a pasar usamos \"**going to**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** It **will be** a great party. / It **is going to be** a great party.\n> **Translation:** (Será una fiesta genial.)\n\n> **Example:** It **won't rain**. / It **is not going to rain**.\n> **Translation:** (No va a llover.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Existen algunas situaciones en las que usamos el presente continuo o el presente simple para expresar acciones en el futuro.\n>\n> 1. Se puede usar **el presente continuo** para acciones seguras en el futuro cercano.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Sarah **is arriving** tonight.\n> > **Translation:** (Sarah llega esta noche.)\n>\n> > **Example:** I **am going** to the doctor this afternoon.\n> > **Translation:** (Voy al médico esta tarde.)\n>\n> 2. Se usa **el presente simple** para eventos programados en un futuro próximo y horarios de tren, vuelos, etc.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** The party **starts** at 9pm.\n> > **Translation:** (La fiesta empieza a las 21h.)\n>\n> > **Example:** The train **leaves** at 10am.\n> > **Translation:** (El tren sale a las 10h.)",
                "en": "There are two main ways to express the **future** in English. They are sometimes interchangeable, but they often have different meanings.\n\n## Future: \"Will\"\n\n### Structure\n\n> **Note:** There is a short form for the modal verb \"**will**\" in both the affirmative and negative.\n\n| Afirmativo | Forma corta | Negativo | Forma corta |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| I will | **I'll** | I will not | I **won't**<br>**I'll** not |\n| you will | **you'll** | you will not | you **won't**<br>**you'll** not |\n| he will | **he'll** | he will not | he **won't**<br>**he'll** not |\n| she will | **she'll** | she will not | she **won't**<br>**she'll** not |\n| it will | **it'll** | it will not | it **won't**<br>**it'll** not |\n| we will | **we'll** | we will not | we **won't**<br>**we'll** not |\n| they will | **they'll** | they will not | they **won't**<br>**they'll** not |\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will\" + principal verb...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **will [I'll] call** you tonight.\n\n> **Example:** She **will [She'll] arrive** late.\n\n> **Example:** They **will [They'll] be** happy to see you.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will\" + \"not\" + principal verb...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **will not [won't] call** you tonight.\n\n> **Example:** She **will not [won't] arrive** late.\n\n> **Example:** They **will not [won't] be** happy to see you.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + subject + principal verb...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **call** me tonight?\n\n> **Example:** **Will** she **arrive** late?\n\n> **Example:** **Will** they **be** happy to see you?\n\n## Future: \"Going to\"\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"going to\" + principal verb...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **am going to call** you tonight.\n\n> **Example:** She **is going to arrive** late.\n\n> **Example:** They **are going to be** happy to see you.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to\" + principal verb...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **I'm not going to call** you tonight.\n\n> **Example:** She **isn't going to arrive** late.\n\n> **Example:** They **aren't going to be** happy to see you.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to be) + subject + \"going to\" + principal verb...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Are** you **going to call** me tonight?\n\n> **Example:** **Is** she **going to arrive** late?\n\n> **Example:** **Are** they **going to be** happy to see you?\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : For imminent actions or events, we can say \"\n> >\n> > to be about to\n> >\n> > \". The structure is the same as \"\n> >\n> > to be going to\n> >\n> > \".\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** I **am about to leave**.\n>\n> > **Example:** The concert **is about to begin**.\n\n## Uses\n\nBoth \"**will**\" and \"**to be going to**\" are used for expressing the future, but **the use of one over the other implies something about the probability of the action occurring in the future**. The aspect that differentiates \"**to be going to**\" with \"**will**\" is in the sense of \"**planning**\". In general, \"**to be going to**\" is used for concrete plans, when we are quite certain that something is going to happen.\n\n**1. We use \"will\" with voluntary actions.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **help** me move?\n\n> **Example:** They **will clean** their rooms.\n\n> **Example:** She **won't work** with Paul.\n\n**2. \"Will\" is used to express a promise.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** When I am president, I **will lower** taxes.\n\n> **Example:** He promises he **will call** when he arrives.\n\n**3. \"To be going to\" is used for plans**; it indicates the intention to do something.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** We **are going to have** a party tonight.\n\n> **Example:** Richard **is going to take** an English class.\n\n> **Example:** **Are** they **going to play** football later?\n\n**4. Either \"will\" or \"to be going to\" can be used for making predictions**. When there is evidence that something is going to happen, we use \"**going to**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** It **will be** a great party. / It **is going to be** a great party.\n\n> **Example:** It **won't rain**. / It **isn't going to rain**.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : There are some situations in which we use the present continuous or the present simple to express actions in the future.\n>\n> 1. The **present continuous** can be used for actions in the near future or actions that are certain.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Sarah **is arriving** tonight.\n>\n> > **Example:** I **am going** to the doctor this afternoon.\n>\n> 2. We use the **present simple** for events scheduled in the future and timetables for trains, flights, etc.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** The party **starts** at 9pm.\n>\n> > **Example:** The train **leaves** at 10am."
              }
