              "display": {
                "es": "El futuro continuo",
                "en": "Future Continuous"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Form (Forma)\n\nPara formar el **futuro continuo** se utilizan \"**will be**\" o \"**be going to**\" y el verbo+ing.\n\n| Sujeto | Auxiliares | Verbo+ing |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I | **will be**<br>**am going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| he, she, it | **will be**<br>**is going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| you, we, they | **will be**<br>**are going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will be\" + verbo+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + \"going to be\" + verbo+ing...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I will be talking. / I'm going to be talking.\n> **Translation:** (Estaré hablando.)\n\n> **Example:** He will be eating. / He's going to be eating.\n> **Translation:** (Estará comiendo.)\n\n> **Example:** They will be learning. / They're going to be learning.\n> **Translation:** (Estarán aprendiendo.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"be\" + verbo+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (\"to be\") + \"not\" + \"going to be\" + verbo+ing...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I will not [won't] be talking. / I'm not going to be talking.\n> **Translation:** (No estaré hablando.)\n\n> **Example:** He will not [won't] be eating. / He's not going to be eating.\n> **Translation:** (No estará comiendo.)\n\n> **Example:** They will not [won't] be learning. / They're not going to be learning.\n> **Translation:** (No estarán aprendiendo.)\n\n> **Nota**: En las frases negativas el auxiliar negativo **\"not\"** va entre los verbos auxiliares \"**will**\" y \"**be**\" o entre \"**to be**\" y \"**going to be**\".\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar \"will\" + sujeto + \"be\"+ verbo+ing...?\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (\"to be\") + sujeto + \"going to be\" + verbo+ing...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Will you be talking? / Are you going to be talking?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estarás hablando?)\n\n> **Example:** Will he be eating? / Is he going to be eating?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estará comiendo?)\n\n> **Example:** Will they be learning? / Are they going to be learning?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estarán aprendiendo?)\n\n> **Nota**: En las frases interrogativas el sujeto va entre los verbos auxiliares \"**will**\" y \"**be**\" o entre \"**to be**\" y \"**going to be**\".\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\nA diferencia del futuro simple, **las dos formas del futuro continuo significan casi lo mismo y son intercambiables**. También, los usos del futuro continuo son los mismos del pasado continuo, pero en el futuro.\n\n**1. El futuro continuo describe la acción que estará en desarrollo en el futuro y que será interumpida**. El verbo que interrumpe está en __presente simple__.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Jose will be [Jose's going to be] watching the news when you __call__.\n> **Translation:** (Jose estará mirando las noticias cuando le llames.)\n\n> **Example:** Will it be [Is it going to be] raining when l __leave__?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estará lloviendo cuando salga?)\n\n**2. Se usa el futuro continuo para hablar sobre acciones en __un tiempo específico__ en el futuro.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Paula will be [Paula's going to be] living in Spain __next April__.\n> **Translation:** (Paula estará viviendo en España el próximo abril.)\n\n> **Example:** We' ll still be working [ We're still going to be working] at __10 o'clock tomorrow__ night.\n> **Translation:** (Todavía estaremos trabajando a las 10 mañana por la noche.)\n\n> **Nota**: Ten en cuenta que **hay verbos que no solemos usar en los tiempos continuos**. Ver una lista y una explicación en la lección sobre los tiempos continuos.",
                "en": "## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Form\n\nTo form the future continuous we use \"**will be**\" or \"**be going to**\" along with the verb+ing.\n\n| Subject | Auxiliaries | Verb+ing |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I | **will be**<br>**am going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| he, she, it | **will be**<br>**is going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n| you, we, they | **will be**<br>**are going to be** | talking, eating, learning, doing, going... |\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will be\" + verb+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"going to be\" + verb+ing...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **will be talking**. / I **am going to be talking**.\n\n> **Example:** He **will be eating**. / He **is going to be eating**.\n\n> **Example:** They **will be learning**. / They **are going to be learning**.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"be\" + verb+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to be\" + verb+ing...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **will not [won't] be talking**. / I **am not going to be talking**.\n\n> **Example:** He **will not [won't] be eating**./ He **isn't going to be eating**.\n\n> **Example:** They **will not [won't] be learning**. / They **aren't going to be learning**.\n\n> **Note**: In negatives sentences, the negative auxiliary \"**not**\" is found between the auxiliaries \"**will**\" and \"**be**\" or between \"**to be**\" and \"**going to be**\".\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + subject + \"be\"+ verb+ing...?\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to be) + subject + \"going to be\" + verb+ing...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **be talking**? / **Are** you **going to be talking**?\n\n> **Example:** **Will** he **be eating**? / **Is** he **going to be eating**?\n\n> **Example:** **Will** they **be learning**? / **Are** they **going to be learning**?\n\n> **Note**: In interrogative sentences, the subject is located between the auxiliaries \"**will**\" and \"**be**\" or between \"**to be**\" and \"**going to be**\".\n\n## Uses\n\nIn contrast to the future simple, **the two forms of the future continuous have the same meaning and can be used interchangeably**. The use of the future continuous is the same as the past continuous, in that it is used for actions that occur at a specific time, but in this case, in the future.\n\n**1. The future continuous is used for an action or event that will be occurring in the future and that will be interrupted**. The action that will cause the interruption is in the __present simple__.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Jose **will be [Jose's going to be] watching** the news when you __call__.\n\n> **Example:** **Will** it **be [Is it going to be] raining** when l __leave__?\n\n**2. We use the future continuous to talk about actions or events that will happen at a __specific time__ in the future.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Paula **will be [Paula's going to be] living** in Spain __next April__.\n\n> **Example:** We **will** still **be working [We're still going to be working]** at __10 o'clock tomorrow__ night.\n\n> **Note**: As we have seen, **there are some verbs which may not be used in the continuous tenses**. Further explanation, as well as a list of such verbs that cannot be used in the continuous tenses, can be found in the lesson on the continuous verb tenses."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
