            {
              "code": 48,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "present-perfect",
                "en": "present-perfect"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El presente perfecto",
                "en": "Present Perfect"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**El presente perfecto equivale más o menos al pretérito perfecto del español**. Veremos las diferencias en la sección sobre usos. En general, es una mezcla entre el presente y el pasado. **Lo usamos para acciones en el pasado que tienen importancia en el presente.**\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Form (Forma)\n\n**Para formar el presente perfecto, se usa el verbo auxiliar \"to have\" en el presente y el participio pasado del verbo**. Para verbos regulares, el participio pasado es la forma simple del pasado. Ver la lección sobre el pasado simple para más información sobre como formar el pasado.\n\n| Sujeto | Verbo auxiliar | Forma Corta | Participio Pasado |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| I, you, we, they | **have** | I've, you've, we've, they've | talked, learned, traveled... |\n| he, she, it | **has** | he's, she's, it's | talked, learned, traveled... |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota:\n> >\n> > Ten en cuenta que\n> >\n> > hay muchos participios pasados irregulares en inglés\n> >\n> > . A continuación tienes una lista de unos de los participios pasados irregulares más comunes.\n>\n> | Verbo | Pasado Simple | Participio pasado |\n> | --- | --- | --- |\n> | be | was/were | **been** |\n> | do | did | **done** |\n> | go | went | **gone** |\n> | make | made | **made** |\n> | see | saw | **seen** |\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to have) + participio pasado...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **have [I've] talked** to Peter.\n> **Translation:** (He hablado con Peter.)\n\n> **Example:** She **has [She's] gone** to work.\n> **Translation:** (Ha ido a su trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** We **have [We've] been** to London.\n> **Translation:** (Hemos ido a Londres.)\n\n> **Example:** They **have [They've] learned** English.\n> **Translation:** (Han aprendido inglés.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to have) + \"not\" + participio pasado...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **haven't talked** to Peter.\n> **Translation:** (No he hablado con Peter.)\n\n> **Example:** She **hasn't gone** to work.\n> **Translation:** (No ha ido a su trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** We **haven't been** to London.\n> **Translation:** (No hemos ido a Londres.)\n\n> **Example:** They **haven't learned** English.\n> **Translation:** (No han aprendido inglés.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to have) + sujeto + participio pasado...?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **talked** to Peter?\n> **Translation:** (¿Has hablado con Peter?)\n\n> **Example:** **Has** she **gone** to work?\n> **Translation:** (¿Ha ido a su trabajo?)\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been** to London?\n> **Translation:** (¿Has ido a Londres?)\n\n> **Example:** **Have** they **learned** English?\n> **Translation:** (¿Han aprendido inglés?)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n**Se usa el presente perfecto para acciones que ocurrieron en un tiempo no concreto antes de ahora**. El tiempo específico no es importante. Por lo tanto, no solemos usar expresiones de tiempo específicas (\"**this morning**\", \"**yesterday**\", \"**last year**\"...) con el presente perfecto. Se puede usar el presente perfecto __con expresiones de tiempo no concretas__ (\"**never**\", \"**ever**\", \"**many times**\", \"**for**\", \"**since**\", \"**already**\", \"**yet**\"...). Este concepto de tiempo no específico es bastante difícil de comprender, por este motivo, a continuación tienes los usos particulares del presente perfecto.\n\n**1. Se usa el presente perfecto para describir una experiencia.** No lo usamos para acciones específicas.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **have** __never__ **flown** in a plane.\n> **Translation:** (Nunca he volado en un avión.)\n\n> **Example:** He **has worked** in many different museums.\n> **Translation:** (Ha trabajado en muchos museos diferentes.)\n\n> **Example:** We **have been** to Río de Janeiro.\n> **Translation:** (Hemos ido a Río de Janeiro.)\n\n**2. Se utiliza el presente perfecto para un cambio en el tiempo.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **have become** more timid in my old age.\n> **Translation:** (Me he vuelto más tímido en mi vejez.)\n\n> **Example:** Their English **has improved** a lot this year.\n> **Translation:** (Su inglés ha mejorado mucho este año.)\n\n> **Example:** He **has learned** to be more patient.\n> **Translation:** (Ha aprendido a ser más paciente.)\n\n**3. Se usa para los éxitos o logros.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Our football team **has won** the championship three times.\n> **Translation:** (Nuestro equipo de fútbol ha ganado el campeonato tres veces.)\n\n> **Example:** Dan **has finished** writing his first novel.\n> **Translation:** (Dan ha terminado de escribir su primera novela.)\n\n> **Example:** Scientists **have succeeded** in curing many illnesses.\n> **Translation:** (Los científicos han tenido éxito en la curación de muchas enfermedades.)\n\n**4. Usamos el presente perfecto para acciones que todavía no han sucedido.** El uso del presente perfecto en estos casos indica que aún estamos esperando la acción, por eso, frecuentemente usamos los __adverbios__ \"**yet**\" y \"**still**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The plane **hasn't arrived** __yet__.\n> **Translation:** (El avión no ha llegado todavía.)\n\n> **Example:** Our team __still__ **hasn't won** a championship.\n> **Translation:** (Nuestro equipo aún no ha ganado un campeonato.)\n\n> **Example:** You **haven't finished** your homework __yet__?\n> **Translation:** (¿No has acabado todavía los deberes?)\n\n**5. Se utiliza el presente perfecto para hablar sobre acciones en diferentes momentos en el pasado.** El uso del presente perfecto en estos casos indica que son posibles más acciones en el futuro.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** We **have spoken** several times, but we still can't reach an agreement.\n> **Translation:** (Hemos hablado varias veces, pero todavía no podemos llegar a un acuerdo.)\n\n> **Example:** Our team **has played** 4 games so far this year.\n> **Translation:** (Nuestro equipo ya ha jugado 4 partidos este año.)\n\n> **Example:** I love New York! I **have been** there 5 times already and I can't wait to go back.\n> **Translation:** (¡Me encanta Nueva York! Ya he estado allí 5 veces y no puedo esperar para regresar.)\n\n**6. En general, usamos el presente perfecto continuo para situaciones que han empezado en el pasado pero siguen en el presente.** Pero como hemos visto, hay algunos verbos que no podemos usar en los tiempos continuos. En estos casos, usamos el presente perfecto.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** How long has Michael **been** in Barcelona?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuánto tiempo ha estado Michael en Barcelona?)\n\n> **Example:** I **have loved** you since the day I met you.\n> **Translation:** (Te he querido desde el día que te conocí.)",
                "en": "In general, the **present perfect is a mix of the present and the past**. It is used for actions in the past that have significance in the present.\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Form\n\n**To form the present perfect tense we use the auxiliary verb \"to have\" in the present simple tense, as well as the past participle of the principal verb**. For regular verbs, the past participle of verb is the regular past simple form (verb + \"**-ed**\"). See the lesson on the past simple for more information on forming the past tense.\n\n| Subject | Auxiliary | Short Form | Past Participle |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| I, you, we, they | **have** | I've, you've, we've, they've | talked, learned, traveled... |\n| he, she, it | **has** | he's, she's, it's | talked, learned, traveled... |\n\n> **Note:** Keep in mind that **there are many irregular past participles in English**. Below is a list of some of the most common irregular past participles.\n\n| Verb | Past Simple | Past Participle |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| be | was/were | **been** |\n| do | did | **done** |\n| go | went | **gone** |\n| make | made | **made** |\n| see | saw | **seen** |\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to have) + past participle...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **have [I've] talked** to Peter.\n\n> **Example:** She **has [She's] gone** to work.\n\n> **Example:** We **have [We've] been** to London.\n\n> **Example:** They **have [They've] learned** English.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to have) + \"not\" + past participle...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **haven't talked** to Peter.\n\n> **Example:** She **hasn't gone** to work.\n\n> **Example:** We **haven't been** to London.\n\n> **Example:** They **haven't learned** English.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to have) + subject + past participle...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **talked** to Peter?\n\n> **Example:** **Has** she **gone** to work?\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been** to London?\n\n> **Example:** **Have** they **learned** English?\n\n## Uses\n\n**The present perfect is used for actions or events that occurred at an unspecified time before the present**. The specific time is not important and therefore we generally do not use specific time expressions (\"**this morning**\", \"**yesterday**\", \"**last year**\"...) with the present perfect. On the other hand, we can use __nonspecific time expressions__ with the present perfect (\"**never**\", \"**ever**\", \"**many times**\", \"**for**\", \"**since**\", \"**already**\", \"**yet**\"...). This concept of nonspecific time is quite difficult to understand and so below you will find further explanation of the particular uses of the present perfect.\n\n**1. The present perfect is used to describe an experience.** It is not used for specific actions.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **have** __never__ **flown** in a plane.\n\n> **Example:** He **has worked** in many different museums.\n\n> **Example:** We **have been** to Rio de Janeiro.\n\n**2. We use the present perfect to express change over time.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **have become** more timid in my old age.\n\n> **Example:** Their English **has improved** a lot this year.\n\n> **Example:** He **has learned** to be more patient.\n\n**3. The present perfect is used for accomplishments.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Our football team **has won** the championship three times.\n\n> **Example:** Dan **has finished** writing his first novel.\n\n> **Example:** Scientists **have succeeded** in curing many illnesses.\n\n**4. We use the present perfect for actions or events that have not yet happened**. The use of the present perfect in these cases indicates that we are still expecting the event or action to occur. Therefore, we frequently use the __adverbs__ \"**yet**\" y \"**still**\" with the present perfect.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The plane **hasn't arrived** __yet__.\n\n> **Example:** Our team __still__ **hasn't won** a championship.\n\n> **Example:** You **haven't finished** your homework __yet__?\n\n**5. The present perfect is used to discuss actions or events that occurred at various times in the past**. The use of the present perfect in these cases indicates that further actions or events are possible in the future.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** We **have spoken** several times, but we still can't reach an agreement.\n\n> **Example:** Our team **has played** 4 games so far this year.\n\n> **Example:** I love New York! I **have been** there 5 times already and I can't wait to go back.\n\n**6. As we will see, in general we use the present perfect continuous for situations that began in the past and continue into the present.** However, as we have learned, there are some verbs which we cannot use in the continuous tenses. In these cases, we use the present perfect simple.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** How long **has** Michael **been** in Barcelona?\n\n> **Example:** I **have loved** you since the day I met you."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 49,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "present-perfect-continuous",
                "en": "present-perfect-continuous"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El presente perfecto continuo",
                "en": "Present Perfect Continuous"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**El presente perfecto continuo**, muchas veces tiene la equivalencia a la traducción \"llevar + gerundio\" en español, pero el uso de esta forma es más frecuente en inglés. **Se utiliza para acciones que han empezado en el pasado pero continúan en el presente**.\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Form (Forma)\n\nComo en el presente perfecto, usamos el verbo auxiliar \"**to have**\" además de \"**been**\" (el participio pasado del verbo \"**to be**\") más el verbo+ing.\n\n| Subject | Auxiliary | Verbo+ing |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I, you, we, they | **have been** | talking, studying, waiting... |\n| he, she, it | **has been** | talking, studying, waiting... |\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to have) + \"been\" + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** They **have [They've] been talking** for three hours.\n> **Translation:** (Han estado hablando durante tres horas.)\n\n> **Example:** She **has [She's] been studying** English since she was 16.\n> **Translation:** (Ha estado estudiando inglés desde que tenía 16 años.)\n\n> **Example:** I **have [I've] been waiting** for you for over an hour!\n> **Translation:** (¡Te llevo esperando durante más de una hora!)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to have) + \"not\" + \"been\" + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** They **haven't been talking** for more than a few minutes.\n> **Translation:** (No han estado hablando más de unos minutos.)\n\n> **Example:** She **hasn't been studying** English for very long.\n> **Translation:** (No ha estado estudiando inglés durante mucho tiempo.)\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, I **haven't been waiting** long.\n> **Translation:** (No te preocupes, no llevo esperando mucho tiempo.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to have) + sujeto + \"been\" + verbo+ing?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Have** they **been talking** for a long time?\n> **Translation:** (¿Han estado hablando durante mucho tiempo?)\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been waiting** long?\n> **Translation:** (¿Llevas esperando mucho tiempo?)\n\n## Use (Uso)\n\n**Usamos este tiempo cuando queremos expresar el sentido de la continuidad de una acción que ha comenzado en el pasado y que dura todavía en el presente o que acaba de terminar**.\n\nNos referimos a algo que hemos estado haciendo en un período de tiempo, por lo tanto, usamos las __preposiciones de tiempo__ \"**for**\" y \"**since**\".\n\nSi usamos el presente perfecto continuo sin un período de tiempo, significa \"**lately**\" o \"**recently**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I can't believe it is still raining. **It's been raining** __for__ a week now!\n> **Translation:** (No puedo creer que todavía esté lloviendo. Lleva lloviendo desde hace una semana!)\n\n> **Example:** John **has been working** at the bank __since__ 2003.\n> **Translation:** (John lleva trabajando en el banco desde 2003.)\n\n> **Example:** **We've been planning** our vacation __for__ over a month.\n> **Translation:** (Llevamos planeando nuestras vacaciones desde hace más de un mes.)\n\n> **Example:** Amanda and Tom **have been dating** __since__ last June.\n> **Translation:** (Amanda y Tom han estado saliendo desde el junio pasado.)\n\n> **Example:** He **hasn't been studying** enough.\n> **Translation:** (No ha estado estudiando bastante.)\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been feeling** ok lately?\n> **Translation:** (¿Te has sentido bien últimamente?)\n\n> **Example:** **I've been working** too much.\n> **Translation:** (He estado trabajando demasiado.)\n\n> **Nota:** Como hemos visto en las últimas lecciones, no podemos usar las formas continuas con algunos verbos. En estos casos, usamos el presente perfecto.",
                "en": "**The present perfect continuous is used for actions or events that began in the past and continue into the present**.\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Form\n\nAs with the present perfect simple, we use the auxiliary verb \"**to have**\" as well as \"**been**\" (the past participle of the verb \"**to be**\") and the verb+ing.\n\n| Subject | Auxiliary | Verb+ing |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| I, you, we, they | **have been** | talking, studying, waiting... |\n| he, she, it | **has been** | talking, studying, waiting... |\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to have) + \"been\" + verb+ing\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** They **have [They've] been talking** for three hours.\n\n> **Example:** She **has [She's] been studying** English since she was 16.\n\n> **Example:** I **have [I've] been waiting** for you for over an hour!\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to have) + \"not\" + \"been\" + verb+ing\n>\n> ...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** They **haven't been talking** for more than a few minutes.\n\n> **Example:** She **hasn't been studying** English for very long.\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, I **haven't been waiting** long.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to have) + subject + \"been\" + verb+ing...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Have** they **been talking** for a long time?\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been waiting** long?\n\n## Use\n\n**We use the present perfect continuous when we want to express the sense of continuity of an action that began in the past and which continues into the present or which has just finished**.\n\nWe use it to refer to something that we have been doing over a period of time and therefore we use the __prepositions of time__ \"**for**\" and \"**since**\".\n\nIf we use the present perfect continuous without a time reference, it means \"**lately**\" or \"**recently**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I can't believe it is still raining. **It's been raining** __for__ a week now!\n\n> **Example:** John **has been working** at the bank __since__ 2003.\n\n> **Example:** **We've been planning** our vacation __for__ over a month.\n\n> **Example:** Amanda and Tom **have been dating** __since__ last June.\n\n> **Example:** He **hasn't been studying** enough.\n\n> **Example:** **Have** you **been feeling** ok lately?\n\n> **Example:** **I've been working** too much.\n\n> **Note:** As we have learned, we cannot use the continuous tenses with some verbs (see a list of verbs and an explanation here). In these cases, we use the present perfect simple."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 50,
              "order": 3,
              "slug": {
                "es": "present-perfect-vs-past-simple",
