        {
          "code": 27,
          "order": 3,
          "slug": {
            "es": "verb-tenses-future-perfect",
            "en": "verb-tenses-future-perfect"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Tiempos verbales: El futuro perfecto",
            "en": "Verb Tenses: Future Perfect"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 55,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "future-perfect",
                "en": "future-perfect"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El futuro perfecto",
                "en": "Future Perfect"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Como hemos visto en las lecciones anteriores, **hay dos maneras principales para expresar el futuro**. A diferencia del futuro simple, en el tiempo perfecto, el uso de ellas es en general intercambiable.\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will have\" + participio pasado.\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbos auxiliar (to be) + \"going to have\" + participio pasado.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The party **will [is going to] have ended** by the time you finish work.\n> **Translation:** (La fiesta habrá terminado cuando termine el trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** **I'll [I'm going to] have eaten** before we meet.\n> **Translation:** (Habré comido antes de reunirnos.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"have\" + participio pasado.\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to have\" + participio pasado.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The party **won't [isn't going to] have ended** by the time you finish work.\n> **Translation:** (La fiesta no habrá terminado cuando termine el trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** I **won't [I'm not going to] have eaten** before we meet.\n> **Translation:** (No habré comido antes de reunirnos.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + sujeto + \"have\" + participio pasado?\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to be) + sujeto + \"going to have\" + participio pasado?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Will [Is]** the party **[going to] have ended** before you finish work?\n> **Translation:** (¿La fiesta habrá terminado antes de que termine el trabajo?)\n\n> **Example:** **Will [Are]** you **[going to] have eaten** before we meet?\n> **Translation:** (¿Habrás comido antes de reunirnos?)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n**1. Se usa el futuro perfecto para acciones que ya se habrá terminado antes de otra acción en el futuro.** También, se puede usar para expresar que algo va a suceder antes de un momento específico en el futuro.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **I'll have finished** my studies before I start my new job.\n> **Translation:** (Habré terminado mis estudios antes de comenzar mi nuevo trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** **Is** Mike **going to have trained** enough before his first game?\n> **Translation:** (¿Mike habrá entrenado lo suficiente antes de su primer partido?)\n\n> **Example:** We **won't have become** fluent in Spanish by the time we leave for Mexico next month.\n> **Translation:** (No vamos a tener fluidez en español antes de irnos a México el mes que viene.)\n\n**2. Utilizamos el futuro perfecto para mostrar que algo va a continuar hasta otra acción en el futuro.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Karen **is going to have worked** for 50 years by the time she retires.\n> **Translation:** (Karen habrá trabajado durante 50 años cuando se jubile.)\n\n> **Example:** Next week, **I'll have lived** in Germany for 1 year.\n> **Translation:** (La semana que viene habré vivido en Alemania desde hace 1 año.)",
                "en": "As we have seen in the previous lessons on the future tenses, **there are two ways to express the future in English**. In contrast to the future simple, in the future perfect simple the use of the two different forms is generally interchangeable.\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will have\" + past participle...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"going to have\" + past participle...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The party **will [is going to] have ended** by the time you finish work.\n\n> **Example:** **I'll [I'm going to] have eaten** before we meet.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"have\" + past participle...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to have\" + past participle...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The party **won't [isn't going to] have ended** by the time you finish work.\n\n> **Example:** I **won't [I'm not going to] have eaten** before we meet.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + subject + \"have\" + past participle...?\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to be) + subject + \"going to have\" + past participle...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Will [Is]** the party **[going to] have ended** before you finish work?\n\n> **Example:** **Will [Are]** you **[going to] have eaten** before we meet?\n\n## Uses\n\n**1. We use the future perfect for actions that will have finished before another action in the future**. The future perfect can also be used to express something that will happen before a specific time in the future.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **I'll have finished** my studies before I start my new job.\n\n> **Example:** **Is** Mike **going to have trained** enough before his first game?\n\n> **Example:** We **won't have become** fluent in Spanish by the time we leave for Mexico next month.\n\n**2. The future perfect is use to show that something is going to continue until another action or event in the future.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Karen **is going to have worked** for 50 years by the time she retires.\n\n> **Example:** Next week, **I'll have lived** in Germany for 1 year."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 57,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "future-perfect-continuous",
                "en": "future-perfect-continuous"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El futuro perfecto continuo",
                "en": "Future Perfect Continuous"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\n### Structure (Estructura)\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences** (Frases afirmativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will have been\" + verbo+ing.\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbos auxiliar (to be) + \"going to have been\" + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Francis **will have been living** in Italy for 4 years by the time he finishes his studies.\n> **Translation:** (Francis habrá estado viviendo en Italia durante 4 años, para cuando haya terminado sus estudios.)\n\n> **Example:** **We're going to have been working** for 24 hours by the time we finish this project.\n> **Translation:** (Habremos estado trabajando durante 24 horas, para cuando hayamos terminado este proyecto.)\n\n**2. Negative Sentences** (Frases negativas)\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"have been\" + verbo+ing.\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (\"to be\") + \"not\" + \"going to have been\" + verbo+ing.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Francis **won't have been living** in Italy for long when he finishes his studies.\n> **Translation:** (Francis no habrá estado viviendo en Italia mucho tiempo, para cuando haya terminado sus estudios.)\n\n> **Example:** **We're not going to have been working** too long by the time we finish this project.\n> **Translation:** (No habremos estado trabajando demasiado tiempo, para cuando hayamos terminado este proyecto.)\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences** (Frases interrogativas)\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + sujeto + \"have been\" + verbo+ing?\n\n> **Tip:** Verbo auxiliar (to be) + sujeto + \"going to have been\" + verbo+ing?\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** Francis **have been living** in Italy for long by the time he finishes his studies?\n> **Translation:** (¿Habrá estado viviendo Francis en Italia mucho tiempo, para cuando haya terminado sus estudios?)\n\n> **Example:** **Are** you **going to have been working** for a long time when you finish this project?\n> **Translation:** (¿Habremos estado trabajando mucho tiempo cuando hayamos terminado este proyecto?)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n**1. Utilizamos el futuro perfecto continuo para mostrar que algo va a continuar hasta otra acción o tiempo en el futuro.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Jessica **will have been studying** English for 5 years when she moves to England next April.\n> **Translation:** (Jessica habrá estado estudiando inglés durante 5 años cuando se traslade a Inglaterra el próximo abril.)\n\n> **Example:** **I'm going to have been running** 20 kilometers daily for at least a month before the marathon.\n> **Translation:** (Habré estado corriendo 20 kilómetros diarios durante al menos un mes antes de la maratón.)\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **have been living** together for long before you get married?\n> **Translation:** (¿Habréis estado conviviendo durante mucho tiempo antes de casaros?)\n\n**2. El uso del futuro perfecto continuo es una manera de mostrar causa y efecto en el futuro.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Jessica's English will be perfect when she moves to England next year as **she'll have been studying** it for five years.\n> **Translation:** (El nivel de inglés de Jessica será perfecto cuando se traslade a Inglaterra el año que viene, ya que habrá estado estudiando durante 5 años.)\n\n> **Example:** I'm not worried about the marathon as **I'll have been running** 20 kilometers a day for several weeks before.\n> **Translation:** (No me preocupa la maratón, ya que habré estado corriendo 20 km diarios durante varias semanas.)\n\n> **Nota**: Ten en cuenta las reglas sobre el uso de los tiempos perfectos y expresiones de tiempo, además de las reglas sobre los tiempos continuos.",
                "en": "## Grammatical Rules\n\n### Structure\n\n**1. Affirmative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will have been\" + verbo+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"going to have been\" + verb+ing...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Francis **will have been living** in Italy for 4 years by the time he finishes his studies.\n\n> **Example:** **We're going to have been working** for 24 hours by the time we finish this project.\n\n**2. Negative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + \"will\" + \"not\" + \"have been\" + verbo+ing...\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + \"not\" + \"going to have been\" + verb+ing...\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Francis **won't have been living** in Italy for long when he finishes his studies.\n\n> **Example:** **We're not going to have been working** too long by the time we finish this project.\n\n**3. Interrogative Sentences**\n\n> **Tip:** \"Will\" + subject + \"have been\" + verbo+ing...?\n\n> **Tip:** Auxiliary verb (to be) + subject + \"going to have been\" + verb+ing...?\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Will** Francis **have been living** in Italy for long by the time he finishes his studies?\n\n> **Example:** **Are** you **going to have been working** for a long time when you finish this project?\n\n## Uses\n\n**1. We use the future perfect continuous to show that something is going to continue into the future until another action or time in the future.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Jessica **will have been studying** English for 5 years when she moves to England next April.\n\n> **Example:** **I'm going to have been running** 20 kilometers daily for at least a month before the marathon.\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **have been living** together for long before you get married?\n\n**2. The use of the future perfect continuous is a way to show cause and effect in the future.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Jessica's English will be perfect when she moves to England next year as **she'll have been studying** it for five years.\n\n> **Example:** I'm not worried about the marathon as **I'll have been running** 20 kilometers a day for several weeks before.\n\n> **Note**: Keep in mind the rules regarding the use of the perfect tenses and time expressions as well as the rules regarding verbs in the continuous tenses."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 34,
          "order": 4,
          "slug": {
            "es": "conditionals",
            "en": "conditionals"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Condicionales",
            "en": "Conditionals"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 87,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "conditional-sentences",
                "en": "conditional-sentences"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Las frases condicionales",
                "en": "Conditional Sentences"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**El uso del condicional significa que una acción depende de otra**. Los condicionales se utilizan para hablar sobre situaciones reales o irreales. En general, las frases condicionales llevan la palabra \"**if**\" (si).\n\nTen en cuenta que no existe un tiempo verbal para el condicional en inglés como existe en español. A la vez, **se usa el verbo auxiliar \"would\" para formar el condicional en inglés**.\n\n**Hay cuatro tipos de frases condicionales y el uso de uno u otro refleja la probabilidad de la acción.**\n\n## Conditional Types (Tipos de los condicionales)\n\n### Zero Conditional (Tipo 0)\n\nSe usa este tipo de condicional cuando la condición y el resultado siempre es verdad, como por ejemplo los hechos científicos.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __present simple__ | **present simple** |\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** If you __heat__ water to 100° C, it **boils**. / Water **boils** if you __heat__ it to 100° C.\n> **Translation:** (Si calientas agua a 100 ° C hierve.)\n\n> **Example:** If I __don't practice__ the piano everyday I **play** poorly. / I **play** the piano poorly if I __don't practice__ everyday.\n> **Translation:** (Si no practico el piano cada día toco mal.)\n\n> **Example:** **Does** your mom **get** mad if you __don't call__ her? / If you __don't call__ your mom, **does** she **get** mad?\n> **Translation:** (¿Si no llamas a tu madre, se enoja?)\n\n> **Nota**: Podemos cambiar el orden de las frases sin cambiar el significado. También, en general con este tipo de condicional, podemos sustituir \"**if**\" por \"**when**\" sin alterar el significado.\n\n### First Conditional (Tipo 1)\n\nEste tipo de condicional se utiliza para el futuro y en los casos en que es muy probable que la condición pasará.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __present simple__ | **future simple (\"will\")** |\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** If Bill __studies__, he **will pass** the exam. / Bill **will pass** the exam if he __studies__.\n> **Translation:** (Si Bill estudia, aprobará el examen.)\n\n> **Example:** If it __doesn't rain__, we **will go** to the beach. / We **will go** to the beach if it __doesn't rain__.\n> **Translation:** (Si no llueve, iremos a la playa.)\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **take** the train if you __miss__ the bus? If you __miss__ the bus, **will** you **take** the train?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cogerás el tren si pierdes el bus?)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Se pueden usar algunos verbos modales en vez de \"\n> >\n> > will\n> >\n> > \" para cambiar la probabilidad o expresar una opinión. Para más información, ver la lección sobre los verbos modales.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain, we **may** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Significado**: Con el uso de \"**may**\", el significado de esta frase cambia. Ahora, el hablante reconoce que puede ir a la playa, pero no está tan seguro de si irá.)\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain we **should** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Significado**: En este caso, el uso de \"**should**\" expresa la opinión del hablante.)\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain we **can** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Significado**: \"**Can**\" significa que es posible ir a la playa, pero no indica la probabilidad.)\n\n### Second Conditional (Tipo 2)\n\nSe utiliza el tipo 2 para expresar una posibilidad irreal en el presente, como un deseo o un sueño, o para una acción en el futuro no tan probable.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __past simple__ | **\"would\" + infinitivo** |\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** If I __won__ the lottery, I **would travel** around the world. / I **would travel** around the world if I __won__ the lottery.\n> **Translation:** (Si ganara la lotería, viajaría alrededor del mundo.)\n\n> **Example:** If Rachel __had__ more time, she **would learn** to play the guitar. / Rachel **would learn** to play the guitar if she __had__ more time.\n> **Translation:** (Si Rachel tuviera más tiempo, aprendería a tocar la guitarra.)\n\n> **Example:** **Would** you **be** happy if you __were__ to get married? / If you __were__ to get married, **would** you **be** happy?\n> **Translation:** (¿Estarías feliz si te casaras?)\n\n> **Nota**: Como en el tipo 1, se pueden usar otros verbos modales en vez de \"**would**\" para cambiar el significado y la posibilidad.\n\n### Third Conditional (Tipo 3)\n\nA diferencia a los tipos 1 y 2, se utiliza el tercer tipo de condicional cuando hablamos de una condición en el pasado que no ha sucedido.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __past perfect__ | **\"would have\" + past participle** |\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** If I __had known__ then what I know now, I **would have done** things differently. / I **would have done** things differently if I __had known__ then what I know now.\n> **Translation:** (Si hubiera sabido en el pasado lo que sé ahora, habría hecho las cosas de manera diferente.)\n\n> **Example:** Suzanne **wouldn't have had** the heart attack if she __had gone__ on a diet as her doctor recommended. / If Suzanne __had gone__ on a diet as her doctor recommended she **wouldn't have had** the heart attack.\n> **Translation:** (Suzanne no hubiera tenido el infarto si hubiera hecho dieta como su médico le recomendó.)\n\n> **Example:** **Would** you **have liked** to go to university if you __had been__ able to afford it? / If you __had been__ able to afford it, **would** you **have liked** to go to university?\n> **Translation:** (¿Te habría gustado ir a la universidad si te lo hubieras permitido pagar?)\n\n> **Nota**: Como en los tipos 1 y 2, se pueden usar otros verbos modales en vez de \"**would**\" para cambiar el significado y la probabilidad.",
                "en": "**The use of the conditional implies that one action in a sentence depends on the other**. The conditionals are used to speak about both real and imaginary situations. Conditional sentences are also known as \"if clauses\".\n\nKeep in mind that there is no conditional verb tense in English as there is in other languages. Instead, **we use the auxiliary verb \"would\" to form the conditional**.\n\n**There are four types of conditional sentences and the use of one type over the other reflects the probability of the dependent action happening.**\n\n## Conditional Types\n\n### Zero Conditional\n\nThe zero conditional is used when the condition and the results are always true, such as with scientific facts.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| if | __present simple__ | **present simple** |\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** If you __heat__ water to 100° C, it **boils**. / Water **boils** if you __heat__ it to 100° C.\n\n> **Example:** If I __don't practice__ the piano everyday I **play** poorly. / I **play** the piano poorly if I __don't practice__ everyday.\n\n> **Example:** **Does** your mom **get** mad if you __don't call__ her? / If you __don't call__ your mom, **does** she **get** mad?\n\n> **Note**: We can change the order of the clauses without changing the meaning. Also, with this type of conditional, we can substitute \"**when**\" for \"**if**\" without changing the meaning.\n\n### First Conditional\n\nWe use the first conditional for expressing the future and in cases when the condition is very likely to occur.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| if | __present simple__ | **future simple (\"will\")** |\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** If Bill __studies__, he **will pass** the exam. / Bill **will pass** the exam if he __studies__.\n\n> **Example:** If it __doesn't rain__, we **will go** to the beach. / We **will go** to the beach if it __doesn't rain__.\n\n> **Example:** **Will** you **take** the train if you __miss__ the bus? / If you __miss__ the bus, **will** you **take** the train?\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : We can use certain modal verbs instead of \"\n> >\n> > will\n> >\n> > \" to change the probability of the condition or to express an opinion. For more information, see the lesson on modal verbs.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain, we **may** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Meaning**: With the use of \"**may**\", the meaning of this sentence changes. The speaker here recognizes that they can go to the beach, but they are not sure if they will.)\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain we **should** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Meaning**: In this case, the use of \"**should**\" expresses the opinion of the speaker.)\n>\n> > **Example:** If it doesn't rain we **can** go to the beach.\n> > **Translation:** (**Meaning**: \"**Can**\" here indicates that it is possible to go to the beach, but says nothing of the probability.)\n\n### Second Conditional\n\nThe second conditional is used to express an unreal possibility in the present, such as a wish or dream, or for an action in the future that is not very probable.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __past simple__ | **\"would\" + infinitive** |\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** If I __won__ the lottery, I **would travel** around the world. / I **would travel** around the world if I __won__ the lottery.\n\n> **Example:** If Rachel __had__ more time, she **would learn** to play the guitar. / Rachel **would learn** to play the guitar if she __had__ more time.\n\n> **Example:** **Would** you **be** happy if you __were__ to get married? / If you __were__ to get married, **would** you **be** happy?\n\n> **Note**: As with the first conditional, we can use other modal verbs instead of \"**would**\" to change the meaning or possibility of the clause.\n\n### Third Conditional\n\nAs opposed to the first and second conditionals, the third conditional is used to speak about a condition in the past that has not occurred.\n\n| IF | Condition | Result |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| If | __past perfect__ | **\"would have\" + past participle** |\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** If I __had known__ then what I know now, I **would have done** things differently. / I **would have done** things differently if I __had known__ then what I know now.\n\n> **Example:** Suzanne **wouldn't have had** the heart attack if she __had gone__ on a diet as her doctor recommended. / If Suzanne __had gone__ on a diet as her doctor recommended she **wouldn't have had** the heart attack.\n\n> **Example:** **Would** you **have liked** to go to university if you __had been__ able to afford it? / If you __had been__ able to afford it, **would** you **have liked** to go to university?\n\n> **Note**: As with the first and second conditionals, we can use other modal verbs instead of \"**would**\" to change the meaning or possibility of the clause."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 28,
          "order": 5,
          "slug": {
            "es": "passive-voice",
            "en": "passive-voice"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "La voz pasiva",
            "en": "Passive voice"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 59,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "the-passive-voice",
                "en": "the-passive-voice"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "La voz pasiva",
                "en": "The Passive Voice"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Hasta ahora hemos hablado de la voz activa donde enfocamos la acción del verbo en el sujeto. Pero **cuando queremos dar más importancia a la acción y no a quien la ha realizado, utilizamos la voz pasiva.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__La voz activa__\n\n> **Example:** He ate all of the cookies.\n> **Translation:** (Comió todas las galletas.)\n\n__La voz pasiva__\n\n> **Example:** All of the cookies **were eaten**.\n> **Translation:** (Todas las galletas fueron comidas.)\n\n## Grammatical Rules (Reglas gramaticales)\n\nSe forma la voz pasiva con el verbo auxiliar \"**to be**\" y el participio pasado del verbo.\n\n> **Tip:** Sujeto + verbo auxiliar (to be) + participio pasado...\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The speech **is written** for the president.\n> **Translation:** (El discurso está escrito para el presidente.)\n\n> **Example:** The house **was built** in 1975.\n> **Translation:** (La casa fue construida en 1975.)\n\n> **Example:** My wallet **has been stolen**.\n> **Translation:** (Ha sido robada mi cartera.)\n\n> **Example:** The room **will be cleaned** while we are out.\n> **Translation:** (Se limpiará la habitación mientras estemos fuera.)\n\nPara transformar una oración activa a pasiva tenemos en cuenta los siguientes puntos:\n\n1. El objeto de la oración activa pasa a ser el sujeto de la pasiva.\n\n2. El verbo principal se sustituye por el auxiliar \"**to be**\", en su mismo tiempo, junto al verbo principal en participio.\n\n3. El sujeto de la oración principal pasa a ser complemento agente de la pasiva.\n\n4. Si hacemos mención en la oración del sujeto que realiza la acción (sujeto agente), este irá normalmente precedido por la preposición \"**by**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__La voz activa__:\n\n> **Example:** Mark Twain **wrote** the book.\n> **Translation:** (Mark Twain escribió el libro.)\n\n__La voz pasiva__:\n\n> **Example:** The book **was written** __by__ Mark Twain.\n> **Translation:** (El libro fue escrito por Mark Twain.)\n\n__La voz activa__:\n\n> **Example:** The housekeeper **will clean** the room.\n> **Translation:** (La ama de casa limpiará la habitación.)\n\n__La voz pasiva__:\n\n> **Example:** The room **will be cleaned** __by__ the housekeeper.\n> **Translation:** (La habitación será limpiada por la ama de casa.)\n\n## Uses (Usos)\n\n1. Usamos la voz pasiva cuando no sabemos quien ha realizado la acción.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** A civilian **has been killed**.\n> **Translation:** (Un civil ha sido asesinado.)\n\n> **Example:** The car **was stolen**.\n> **Translation:** (El coche fue robado.)\n\n2. Usamos la voz pasiva cuando queremos dar más importancia a lo que pasó, que a quién realizó la acción o cuando no queremos decir quien la realizó.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The letter **was delivered** yesterday.\n> **Translation:** (La carta fue entregada ayer.)\n\n> **Example:** A mistake **was made**.\n> **Translation:** (Un error fue cometido.)\n\n> **Nota**: No podemos usar la voz pasiva con verbos intransitivos como \"**die**\", \"**arrive**\" o \"**go**\". Verbos intransitivos son verbos que no llevan un objeto directo.",
                "en": "So far in this course, we have spoken only of the active voice, where the action of the verb is focused on the subject. **When we want to give more importance to the action, rather than the subject, we use what is known as the passive voice.**\n\nExamples:\n\n__Active Voice__\n\n> **Example:** He ate all of the cookies.\n\n__Passive Voice__\n\n> **Example:** All of the cookies **were eaten**\n\n## Grammatical Rules\n\nThe passive is formed using the auxiliary verb \"**to be**\" and the past participle of the principal verb.\n\n> **Tip:** Subject + auxiliary verb (to be) + past participle....\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The speech **is written** for the president.\n\n> **Example:** The house **was built** in 1975.\n\n> **Example:** My wallet **has been stolen.**\n\n> **Example:** The room **will be cleaned** while we are out.\n\nTo change the sentence from an active one to a passive one, there are several points to keep in mind:\n\n1. The object of an active voice sentence becomes the subject of the sentence in the passive.\n\n2. The principal verb in the active voice is substituted by the auxiliary verb \"**to be**\", in the same verb tense, and the verb is then in the past participle form.\n\n3. The subject in the active voice becomes the complement in the passive.\n\n4. If in the passive we mention the subject who completed the action (subject agent), this subject is normally introduced in the passive with the preposition \"**by**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n__Active Voice:__\n\n> **Example:** Mark Twain **wrote** the book.\n\n__Passive Voice:__\n\n> **Example:** The book **was written** __by__ Mark Twain.\n\n__Active Voice:__\n\n> **Example:** The housekeeper **will clean** the room.\n\n__Passive Voice:__\n\n> **Example:** The room **will be cleaned** __by__ the housekeeper.\n\n## Uses\n\n1. We use the passive voice when we do not know who completed the action.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** A civilian **has been killed**.\n\n> **Example:** The car **was stolen**.\n\n2. We use the active voice when we want to give more importance to the action and not who completed the action or when we don't want to say who completed the action.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The letter **was delivered** yesterday.\n\n> **Example:** A mistake **was made**.\n\n> **Note**: We cannot use the passive voice with intransitive verbs such as \"**die**\", \"**arrive**\" or \"**go**\" because these verbs are not used with direct objects."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 31,
          "order": 6,
          "slug": {
            "es": "direct-and-reported-speech",
            "en": "direct-and-reported-speech"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "El estilo directo e indirecto",
            "en": "Direct and Reported Speech"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 72,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "direct-and-reported-speech",
                "en": "direct-and-reported-speech"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "El estilo directo y indirecto",
                "en": "Direct and Reported Speech"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Cuando queremos comunicar o informar de lo que otra persona ha dicho, hay dos maneras de hacerlo: utilizando el estilo directo o el estilo indirecto**.\n\n## Direct Speech (El estilo directo)\n\n**Cuando queremos informar exactamente de lo que otra persona ha dicho, utilizamos el estilo directo**. Con este estilo lo que la persona ha dicho se coloca entre comillas (\"...\") y deberá ser palabra por palabra.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** \"I am going to London next week,\" she said.\n> **Translation:** (\"Voy a Londres la semana que viene,\" ella dijo.)\n\n> **Example:** \"Do you have a pen I could borrow,\" he asked.\n> **Translation:** (\"¿Tienes un bolígrafo que puedas prestarme?,\" él preguntó.)\n\n> **Example:** Alice said, \"I love to dance.\"\n> **Translation:** (Alice dijo, \"Me encanta bailar.\")\n\n> **Example:** Chris asked, \"Would you like to have dinner with me tomorrow night?\"\n> **Translation:** (Chris preguntó, \"¿Te gustaría cenar conmigo mañana por la noche?\")\n\n## Reported Speech (El estilo indirecto)\n\n**El estilo indirecto**, a diferencia del estilo directo, **no utiliza las comillas y no necesita ser palabra por palabra**. En general, **cuando se usa el estilo indirecto, el tiempo verbal cambia**. A continuación tienes una explicación de los cambios que sufren los tiempos verbales.\n\nA veces se usa \"**__that__**\" en las frases afirmativas y negativas para introducir lo que ha dicho la otra persona. Por otro lado, en las frases interrogativas se puede usar \"**__if__**\" o \"**__whether__**\".\n\n> **Nota: Ten en cuenta también que *las expresiones de tiempo* cambian en el estilo indirecto**. Fijate en los cambios de tiempo en los ejemplos más abajo y después, encontrarás una tabla con más explicaciones de los cambios de tiempo en el estilo indirecto.\n\n| Direct Speech | Reported Speech |\n| --- | --- |\n| **Present Simple** | **Past Simple** |\n| \"He **is** American,\" she said. | She said he **was** American. |\n| \"I **am** happy to see you,\" Mary said. | Mary said __that__ she **was** happy to see me. |\n| He asked, \"**Are** you busy *tonight*?\" | He asked me __if__ I **was** busy *that night*. |\n| **Present Continuous** | **Past Continuous** |\n| \"Dan **is living** in San Francisco,\" she said. | She said Dan **was living** in San Francisco. |\n| He said, \"**I'm making** dinner.\" | He told me __that__ he **was making** dinner. |\n| \"Why **are** you **working** so hard?\" they asked. | They asked me why I **was working** so hard. |\n| **Past Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple** |\n| \"We **went** to the movies *last night*,\" he said. | He told me they **had gone** to the movies *the night before*. |\n| Greg said, \"I **didn't go** to work *yesterday*.\" | Greg said __that__ he **hadn't gone** to work *the day before*. |\n| \"**Did** you **buy** a new car?\" she asked. | She asked me __if__ I **had bought** a new car. |\n| **Past Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous** |\n| \"I **was working** late *last night*,\" Vicki said. | Vicki told me **she'd been working** late *the night before*. |\n| They said, \"we **weren't waiting** long.\" | They said __that__ they **hadn't been waiting** long. |\n| He asked, \"**were** you **sleeping** when I called?\" | He asked __if__ **I'd been sleeping** when he called. |\n| **Present Perfect Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple** |\n| Heather said, \"**I've** already **eaten**.\" | Heather told me __that__ **she'd** already **eaten**. |\n| \"We **haven't been** to China,\" they said. | They said they **hadn't been** to China. |\n| \"**Have** you **worked** here before?\" I asked. | I asked her __whether__ **she'd worked** there before. |\n| **Present Perfect Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous** |\n| \"**I've been studying** English for two years,\" he said. | He said **he'd been studying** English for two years. |\n| Steve said, \"**we've been dating** for over a year now.\" | Steve told me __that__ **they'd been dating** for over a year. |\n| \"**Have** you **been waiting** long?\" they asked. | They asked __whether__ **I'd been waiting** long. |\n| **Past Perfect Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple (NO CHANGE)** |\n| \"**I'd been** to Chicago before for work,\" he said. | He said __that__ **he'd been** to Chicago before for work. |\n| **Past Perfect Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous (NO CHANGE)** |\n| She said, \"**I'd been dancing** for years before the accident.\" | She said **she'd been dancing** for years before the accident. |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Cuando hablamos de algo que no ha cambiado (que sigue siendo cierto) o de algo en el futuro, no es necesario cambiar el tiempo verbal.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** \"**I'm** 30 years old,\" she said. → She said she **is** 30 years old.\n>\n> > **Example:** Dave said, \"Kelly **is** sick.\" → Dave said Kelly **is** sick.\n>\n> > **Example:** \"We **are going** to Tokyo next week,\" they said. → They said they **are going** to Tokyo next week.\n>\n> > **Example:** \"**I'll cut** my hair tomorrow,\" Nina said. → Nina said she **is** cutting her hair tomorrow.\n\n### Modal Verbs (Los verbos modales)\n\nEl tiempo verbal cambia en el estilo indirecto también con algunos de los verbos modales.\n\n> **Nota**: Con \"**would**\", \"**could**\", \"**should**\", \"**might**\" y \"**ought to**\", el tiempo no cambia.\n\n| Direct Speech | Indirect Speech |\n| --- | --- |\n| **Will** | **Would** |\n| \"**I'll go** to the movies *tomorrow*,\" John said. | John said he **would go** to the movies *the next day*. |\n| \"**Will** you **help** me move?\" she asked. | She asked me __if__ I **would help** her move. |\n| **Can** | **Could** |\n| Debra said, \"Allen **can work** *tomorrow*.\" | Debra said Allen **could work** *the next day*. |\n| \"**Can** you **open** the window, please?\", he asked. | He asked me __if__ I **could open** the window. |\n| **Must** | **Had to** |\n| \"You **must wear** your seat belt,\" mom said. | My mom said I **had to wear** my seat belt. |\n| She said, \"You **must work** *tomorrow*.\" | She said I **had to work** *the next day*. |\n| **Shall** | **Should** |\n| \"**Shall** we **go** to the beach *today*?\" Tom asked. | Tom asked if we **should go** to the beach *that day*. |\n| \"What **shall** we **do** *tonight*?\" she asked. | She asked me what we **should do** *that night*. |\n| **May** | **Might/Could** |\n| Jane said, \"I **may not be** in class *tomorrow*.\" | Jane said she **might not be** in class *the next day*. |\n| \"**May** I **use** the bathroom, please?\", the boy asked. | The boy asked __if__ he **could use** the bathroom. |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : A continuación tienes una tabla donde puedes observar los cambios que sufren las expresiones de tiempo cuando usamos el estilo indirecto.\n>\n> | Direct Speech | Indirect Speech |\n> | --- | --- |\n> | today | that day |\n> | tonight | that night |\n> | **this** week/month/year | **that** week/month/year |\n> | tomorrow | the next day |\n> | **next** week/month/year | **the following** week/month/year |\n> | yesterday | the day before or the previous day |\n> | **last** week/month/year | the week/month year **before** or **the previous** week/month/year |\n> | now | then/at that moment |\n> | ***Otros cambios*** |  |\n> | here | there |",
                "en": "**When we want to communicate or report what another person has said, there are two ways of doing so: direct speech and indirect or reported speech**.\n\n## Direct Speech\n\n**To report exactly what another person has said, we use direct speech**. In direct speech, what the person has said is placed within quotation marks (\"...\") and should be word for word.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** \"I am going to London next week,\" she said.\n\n> **Example:** \"Do you have a pen I could borrow,\" he asked.\n\n> **Example:** Alice said, \"I love to dance.\"\n\n> **Example:** Chris asked, \"Would you like to have dinner with me tomorrow night?\"\n\n## Indirect/Reported Speech\n\n**With indirect or reported speech**, as opposed to direct speech, **we do not use quotation marks and it does not have to be word for word.** In general, when we use indirect or reported speech, **the verb tense changes**. Below is a table with an explanation of the tense changes in indirect or reported speech.\n\nWe sometimes use \"__**that**__\" in affirmative and negative sentences to introduce what the other person has said. In interrogative sentences, \"__**if**__\" or \"__**whether**__\" are used.\n\n> **Note: Keep in mind that *time expressions* also change in reported speech**. Note the changes in time in the examples below and at the end of the lesson you will find a table with more information regarding the changes in expressions of time in indirect or reported speech.\n\n| Direct Speech | Reported Speech |\n| --- | --- |\n| **Present Simple** | **Past Simple** |\n| \"He **is** American,\" she said. | She said he **was** American. |\n| \"**I'm** happy to see you,\" Mary said. | Mary said __that__ she **was** happy to see me. |\n| \" He asked, \"**Are** you busy *tonight*?\" | He asked me __if__ I **was** busy *that night*. |\n| **Present Continuous** | **Past Continuous** |\n| \"Dan **is living** in San Francisco,\" she said. | She said Dan **was living** in San Francisco. |\n| He said, \"**I'm making** dinner.\" | He told me __that__ he **was making** dinner. |\n| \"Why **are** you **working** so hard?\" they asked. | They asked me why I **was working** so hard. |\n| **Past Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple** |\n| \"We **went** to the movies *last night*,\" he said. | He told me they **had gone** to the movies *the night before*. |\n| Greg said, \"I **didn't go** to work *yesterday*.\" | Greg said __that__ he **hadn't gone** to work *the day before*. |\n| \"**Did** you **buy** a new car?\" she asked. | She asked me __if__ I **had bought** a new car. |\n| **Past Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous** |\n| \"I **was working** late *last night*,\" Vicki said. | Vicki told me **she'd been working** late *the night before*. |\n| They said, \"we **weren't waiting** long.\" | They said __that__ they **hadn't been waiting** long. |\n| He asked, \"**were** you **sleeping** when I called?\" | He asked __if__ **I'd been sleeping** when he called. |\n| **Present Perfect Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple** |\n| Heather said, \"**I've** already **eaten**.\" | Heather told me __that__ **she'd** already **eaten**. |\n| \"We **haven't been** to China,\" they said. | They said they **hadn't been** to China. |\n| \"**Have** you **worked** here before?\" I asked. | I asked her __whether__ **she'd worked** there before. |\n| **Present Perfect Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous** |\n| \"**I've been studying** English for two years,\" he said. | He said **he'd been studying** English for two years. |\n| Steve said, \"**we've been dating** for over a year now.\" | Steve told me __that__ **they'd been dating** for over a year. |\n| \"**Have** you **been waiting** long?\" they asked. | They asked __whether__ **I'd been waiting** long. |\n| **Past Perfect Simple** | **Past Perfect Simple<br>(NO CHANGE)** |\n| \"**I'd been** to Chicago before for work,\" he said. | He said __that__ **he'd been** to Chicago before for work. |\n| **Past Perfect Continuous** | **Past Perfect Continuous<br>(NO CHANGE)** |\n| She said, \"**I'd been dancing** for years before the accident.\" | She said **she'd been dancing** for years before the accident. |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : When we speak of something that has not changed (that is still true) or of something in the future, we don't need to change the verb tense.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** \"**I'm** 30 years old,\" she said. → She said she **is** 30 years old.\n>\n> > **Example:** Dave said, \"Kelly **is** sick.\" → Dave said Kelly **is** sick.\n>\n> > **Example:** \"We **are going** to Tokyo next week,\" they said. → They said they **are going** to Tokyo next week.\n>\n> > **Example:** \"**I'll cut** my hair tomorrow,\" Nina said. → Nina said she **is cutting** her hair tomorrow.\n\n### Modal Verbs\n\nThe verb tense also changes in indirect or reported speech with some of the modal verbs.\n\n> **Note:** With \"**would**\", \"**could**\", \"**should**\", \"**might**\" y \"**ought to**\", the verb tense does not change.\n\n| Direct Speech | Indirect Speech |\n| --- | --- |\n| **Will** | **Would** |\n| \"**I'll go** to the movies *tomorrow*,\" John said. | John said he **would go** to the movies *the next day*. |\n| \"**Will** you **help** me move?\" she asked. | She asked me __if__ I **would help** her move. |\n| **Can** | **Could** |\n| Debra said, \"Allen **can work** *tomorrow*.\" | Debra said Allen **could work** *the next day*. |\n| \"**Can** you **open** the window, please?\", he asked. | He asked me __if__ I **could open** the window. |\n| **Must** | **Had to** |\n| \"You **must wear** your seat belt,\" mom said. | My mom said I **had to wear** my seat belt. |\n| \" She said, \"You **must work** *tomorrow*.\" | She said I **had to work** *the next day*. |\n| **Shall** | **Should** |\n| \"**Shall** we go* to the beach *today*?\", Tom asked. | Tom asked __if__ we **should go** to the beach *that day*. |\n| \"What **shall** we **do** *tonight*?\" she asked. | She asked me what we **should do** *that night*. |\n| **May** | **Might/Could** |\n| \" Jane said, \"I **may not be** in class *tomorrow*.\" | Jane said she **might not be** in class *the next day*. |\n| \"**May** I **use** the bathroom, please?\", the boy asked. | The boy asked __if__ he **could use** the bathroom. |\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note:\n> >\n> > Below is a table with an explication of how expressions of time change in indirect or reported speech.\n>\n> | Direct Speech | Indirect Speech |\n> | --- | --- |\n> | today | that day |\n> | tonight | that night |\n> | **this** week/month/year | **that** week/month/year |\n> | tomorrow | the next day |\n> | **next** week/month/year | **the following** week/month/year |\n> | yesterday | the day before or the previous day |\n> | **last** week/month/year | the week/month year **before** or **the previous** week/month/year |\n> | now | then/at that moment |\n> | ***Other changes*** |  |\n> | here | there |"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 78,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "say-vs-tell",
                "en": "say-vs-tell"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Decir",
                "en": "Say vs. Tell"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**En español podemos traducir \"say\" o \"tell\" como \"decir\", pero en inglés se usan estos verbos de maneras distintas**. Hay unas reglas que indican el uso de uno u otro, aunque en general usamos \"**say**\" para \"decir algo\" y \"**tell**\" para \"decir algo a alguien.\"\n\n## Say\n\n**Se usa \"say\" en el estilo directo y el indirecto. Si queremos usar \"say\" con un objeto personal, necesitamos usar la preposición \"__to__\".**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Estilo directo__\n\n> **Example:** \"I'm hungry,\" he **said**.\n> **Translation:** (\"Tengo hambre,\" él dijo.)\n\n> **Example:** \"I need your help,\" Glen **said** __to__ Mike.\n> **Translation:** (\"Necesito tu ayuda,\" Glen dijo a Mike.)\n\n__Estilo indirecto__\n\n> **Example:** He **said** he was hungry.\n> **Translation:** (Él dijo que tenía hambre.)\n\n> **Example:** Glen **said** __to__ Mike that he needed his help.\n> **Translation:** (Glen dijo a Mike que necesitaba su ayuda.)\n\n## Tell\n\nTambién se puede usar \"**tell**\" con el estilo directo y el indirecto, aunque el uso con el estilo directo no es tan común. **Cuando usamos \"tell\" necesitamos usar un objeto indirecto que va detrás del verbo.**\n\nEjemplos:\n\n__Estilo directo__\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __me__, \"I'm hungry\".\n> **Translation:** (Me dijo, \"Tengo hambre.\")\n\n> **Example:** Glen **told** __Mike__, \"I need your help\".\n> **Translation:** (Glen dijo a Mike, \"Necesito tu ayuda.\")\n\n__Estilo indirecto__\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __me__ that he was hungry.\n> **Translation:** (Me dijo que tenía hambre.)\n\n> **Example:** Glen **told** __Mike__ that he needed his help.\n> **Translation:** (Glen dijo a Mike que necesitaba su ayuda.)\n\n### Otros usos de \"tell\":\n\n1. Se usa \"**tell**\" con órdenes o instrucciones.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I **told** __him__, \"Stop complaining.\"\n> **Translation:** (Le dije, \"Deja de quejarte.\")\n\n> **Example:** She **told** __us__ to hurry.\n> **Translation:** (Nos dijo que nos diéramos prisa.)\n\n2. Usamos \"**tell**\" cuando damos o pedimos información.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** \"Can you **tell** __me__ your name please?\"\n> **Translation:** (\"Díme tu nombre, por favor.\")\n\n> **Example:** You **told** __him__ the address of the office?\n> **Translation:** (¿Le dijiste la dirección de la oficina?)\n\n3. Se usa \"**tell**\" con cuentos o bromas. En este caso, se puede traducir \"**tell**\" como \"contar\" en español.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __us__ a great story.\n> **Translation:** (Nos contó un cuento maravilloso.)\n\n> **Example:** \"**Tell** __me__ a joke,\" she said.\n> **Translation:** (\"Cuéntame un chiste,\" dijo ella.)\n\n4. Con la verdad y las mentiras, se usa \"**tell**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** \"**Tell** __me__ the truth\", she demanded.\n> **Translation:** (\"Dime la verdad,\" dijo ella.)\n\n> **Example:** Keith never **tells** lies.\n> **Translation:** (Keith nunca miente.)\n\n5. Usamos \"**tell**\" con el tiempo o la fecha.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** \"Could you **tell** __me__ the time, please?\" she asked.\n> **Translation:** (\"Podrías decirme la hora, por favor?\" me preguntó.)\n\n> **Example:** Bob **told** __me__ the date.\n> **Translation:** (Bob me dijo la fecha.)",
                "en": "**The verbs \"say\" and \"tell\" are frequently confused in English. There are several rules indicating the use of one over the other**. Below is an explanation of these rules.\n\n## Say\n\n**\"Say\" is used in both direct and indirect or reported speech. If we want to use say with a object, we must use the preposition \"to\".**\n\nExamples:\n\n__Direct Speech:__\n\n> **Example:** \"I'm hungry\", he **said**.\n\n> **Example:** \"I need your help,\" Glen **said** __to__ Mike.\n\n__Indirect Speech:__\n\n> **Example:** He **said** he was hungry.\n\n> **Example:** Glen **said** __to__ Mike that he needed his help.\n\n## Tell\n\nWe may also use \"**tell**\" in both direct and indirect or reported speech, although it is not so common. **When we use \"tell\" we must use a indirect object immediately after the verb.** We do not use the preposition \"**to**\", as with \"**say**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n__Direct Speech:__\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __me__, \"I'm hungry\".\n\n> **Example:** Glen **told** __Mike__, \"I need your help\".\n\n__Indirect Speech__\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __me__ that he was hungry.\n\n> **Example:** Glen **told** __Mike__ that he needed his help.\n\n### Other uses of \"tell\":\n\n1. \"**Tell**\" is used for orders or instructions.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I **told** __him__, \"Stop complaining.\"\n\n> **Example:** She **told** __us__ to hurry.\n\n2. We use \"**tell**\" when giving or asking for information.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** \"Can you **tell** __me__ your name please?\"\n\n> **Example:** You **told** __him__ the address of the office?\n\n3. We \"**tell**\" jokes and stories.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** He **told** __us__ a great story.\n\n> **Example:** \"**Tell** __me__ a joke,\" she said.\n\n4. With truth and lies, we use \"**tell**.\"\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** \"**Tell** __me__ the truth\", she demanded.\n\n> **Example:** Keith never **tells** lies.\n\n5. We use \"**tell**\" with the time and the date.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** \"Could you **tell** __me__ the time, please?\" she asked.\n\n> **Example:** Bob **told** __me__ the date."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 10018,
          "order": 7,
          "slug": {
            "es": "collocations-and-expressions",
            "en": "collocations-and-expressions"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Colocaciones y expresiones",
            "en": "Collocations and Expressions"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 77,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "do-vs-make",
                "en": "do-vs-make"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Hacer",
                "en": "Do vs. Make"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**\"Do\" y \"make\" son dos verbos que se confunden frecuentemente en inglés. Ambos se pueden traducir como \"hacer\", pero hay algunas diferencias en su significado**. En general, \"**do**\" considera más la acción, mientras que utilizando \"**make**\" nos referimos más al resultado de la acción.\n\n## Do\n\n**Se usa \"do\" para acciones, actividades y trabajos.** Se utiliza en un sentido amplio, como de \"realizar\". En general, estas acciones y actividades no producen un objeto físico.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **do** homework\n\n> **Example:** **do** a job\n\n> **Example:** **do** the dishes\n\n> **Example:** **do** housework\n\n> **Example:** **do** exercise\n\n**Se utiliza \"do\" cuando hablamos de cosas en general**, cuando no especificamos la actividad. En este sentido, se utiliza mucho con los pronombres indefinidos como \"something\", \"anything\", \"nothing\", etc.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** What are you **doing** today? I'm not **doing** anything.\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué haces hoy? No hago nada.)\n\n> **Example:** He's always **doing** nice things for his girlfriend.\n> **Translation:** (Siempre hace cosas buenas para su novia.)\n\n> **Example:** Are you **doing** anything important right now?\n> **Translation:** (¿Haces algo importante ahora mismo?)\n\n### Expresiones\n\n> **Example:** **do** good\n> **Translation:** (hacer el bien)\n\n> **Example:** **do** right\n> **Translation:** (hacer bien)\n\n> **Example:** **do** wrong\n> **Translation:** (hacer mal)\n\n> **Example:** **do** damage\n> **Translation:** (hacer daño)\n\n> **Example:** **do** one's best\n> **Translation:** (hacer lo posible)\n\n> **Example:** **do** a favor\n> **Translation:** (hacer un favor)\n\n> **Example:** **do** justice\n> **Translation:** (hacer justicia)\n\n> **Example:** **do** research\n> **Translation:** (investigar)\n\n> **Example:** **do** harm\n> **Translation:** (hacer daño)\n\n> **Example:** **do** business\n> **Translation:** (hacer negocios)\n\n> **Example:** **do** one's hair\n> **Translation:** (arreglarse el pelo)\n\n> **Example:** **do** wonders\n> **Translation:** (hacer maravillas)\n\n## Make\n\n**Se utiliza \"make\" en el sentido de \"fabricar\", \"elaborar\" o \"crear\".** Se usa para actividades en que se crea algo que se puede tocar, un objeto físico.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **make** breakfast/lunch/dinner\n\n> **Example:** **make** a dress\n\n> **Example:** **make** furniture\n\n### Expresiones\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota: Hay muchas expresiones que utilizan \"make\".\n> >\n> > En muchas de estas, el sentido de \"make\" no es \"fabricar\", ni \"hacer\" y muy a menudo \"\n> >\n> > do\n> >\n> > \" parece más apropiado, pero son expresiones establecidas, así que hay que memorizarlas.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a decision\n> > **Translation:** (tomar una decisión)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a choice\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una elección)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a plan\n> > **Translation:** (trazar/hacer un plan)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** arrangements\n> > **Translation:** (hacer preparativos)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an appointment\n> > **Translation:** (pedir cita/hora, concertar una cita)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a mistake\n> > **Translation:** (cometer un error)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** money\n> > **Translation:** (ganar dinero)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an excuse\n> > **Translation:** (dar una excusa)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an effort\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un esfuerzo)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an attempt\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un intento)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** fun of\n> > **Translation:** (reírse/burlarse de)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** progress\n> > **Translation:** (hacer progresos)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an offer\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una oferta)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** [a] noise\n> > **Translation:** (hacer [un] ruido)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** peace\n> > **Translation:** (firmar la paz)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** war\n> > **Translation:** (hacer la guerra)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a phone call\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una llamada)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an exception\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una excepción)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a confession\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una confesión)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a discovery\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un descubrimiento)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a change\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un cambio)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** amends\n> > **Translation:** (reparar el daño [causado al alguien]/desagraviar a)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a comment\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un comentario)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a statement\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una declaración/afirmación)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a speech\n> > **Translation:** (pronunciar/hacer un discurso)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a difference\n> > **Translation:** (hacer diferencias/marcar la [una] diferencia)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** friends\n> > **Translation:** (hacer amigos)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** love\n> > **Translation:** (hacer el amor)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a fire\n> > **Translation:** (encender un fuego)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an impression\n> > **Translation:** (causar impresión)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a mess\n> > **Translation:** (hacer un lío)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a point\n> > **Translation:** (dar un argumento concreto)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a promise\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una promesa)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a suggestion\n> > **Translation:** (hacer una sugerencia)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** time\n> > **Translation:** (encontrar tiempo)\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** the bed\n> > **Translation:** (hacer la cama)",
                "en": "**\"Do\" and \"make\" are two verbs which are frequently confused in English as differences in their meaning are subtle**. In general, \"**do**\" refers more to the action, while with \"**make**\" we are referring more to the result of the action.\n\n## Do\n\n**\"Do\" is used for actions, activities and work.** In general, these actions and activities do not produce a physical object. It's broader meaning is \"**to perform**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **do** homework\n\n> **Example:** **do** a job\n\n> **Example:** **do** the dishes\n\n> **Example:** **do** housework\n\n> **Example:** **do** exercise\n\n**We use \"do\" when we are speaking in general**, when we don't say exactly what the action or activity is we are preforming. In this sense, \"**do**\" is often used with indefinite pronouns such as \"**something**\", \"**anything**\", \"**nothing**\", etc.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** What are you **doing** today? I'm not **doing** anything.\n\n> **Example:** He's always **doing** nice things for his girlfriend.\n\n> **Example:** Are you **doing** anything important right now?\n\n### Expressions\n\n> **Example:** **do** good\n\n> **Example:** **do** right\n\n> **Example:** **do** wrong\n\n> **Example:** **do** damage\n\n> **Example:** **do** one's best\n\n> **Example:** **do** a favor\n\n> **Example:** **do** justice\n\n> **Example:** **do** research\n\n> **Example:** **do** harm\n\n> **Example:** **do** business\n\n> **Example:** **do** one's hair\n\n> **Example:** **do** wonders\n\n## Make\n\n**\"Make\" can be defined as \"to produce\" or \"to create\".** It is used for activities which result in something physical.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **make** breakfast / lunch / dinner\n\n> **Example:** **make** a dress\n\n> **Example:** **make** furniture\n\n### Expressions\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note: There are many expressions which use the verb \"make\".\n> >\n> > In many of these expressions, \"\n> >\n> > make\n> >\n> > \" cannot be translated as \"to produce\" or \"\n> >\n> > to create\n> >\n> > \" and in many cases, \"\n> >\n> > do\n> >\n> > \" would appear more appropriate. As they are fixed expressions though, they must simply be memorized.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a decision\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a choice\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a plan\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** arrangements\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an appointment\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a mistake\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** money\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an excuse\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an effort\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an attempt\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** fun of\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** progress\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an offer\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** [a] noise\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** peace\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** war\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a phone call\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an exception\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a confession\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a discovery\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a change\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** amends\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a comment\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a statement\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a speech\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a difference\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** friends\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** love\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a fire\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** an impression\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a mess\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a point\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a promise\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** a suggestion\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** time\n>\n> > **Example:** **make** the bed"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 210,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "delexical-verbs",
                "en": "delexical-verbs"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Delexical Verbs",
                "en": "Delexical Verbs"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Delexical verbs son verbos comunes como \"have\", \"take\", \"make\" o \"give\" que cuando se usan con sustantivos particulares tienen muy poco significado propio. En estas estructuras la mayor parte del significado se encuentra en el sustantivo, no en el verbo**. En la mayoría de casos, hay un verbo que tiene un significado similar o igual a la estructura \"delexical\". En muchos casos, hay verbos y estructuras equivalentes en español (ver los ejemplos). Estas estructuras son muy comunes en inglés y una comprensión de ellas enriquecerá la fluidez de la lengua.\n\n**El uso de estas estructuras permite añadir información adicional a la acción mediante del uso de adjetivos**, en lugar de un adverbio, que a veces puede sonar torpe.\n\nEchemos un vistazo a algunos ejemplos con estos verbos.\n\n## Have\n\n**\"Have\" indica posesión, pero cuando se utiliza en estructuras \"delexical\", el sentido cambia.** Podemos usar \"**have**\" cuando hablamos de las comidas, las conversaciones, los desacuerdos, el lavado o los descansos.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** We **have breakfast** every morning at 8 o'clock.\n> **Translation:** (Desayunamos cada mañana a las 8.)\n\n> **Example:** Lets **have a drink**!\n> **Translation:** (¡Tomemos una copa!)\n\n> **Example:** They **had an argument** last night.\n> **Translation:** (Tuvieron una discusión anoche.)\n\n> **Example:** John **had a __hot__ shower** after his day out in the cold.\n> **Translation:** (John tuvo una ducha caliente después de un día en el frío.)\n\n> **Example:** I'm not happy. We need to **have a conversation**.\n> **Translation:** (No estoy contenta. Necesitamos tener una conversación.)\n\n> **Example:** Next year I **will have a __long__ holiday** in France.\n> **Translation:** (El año que viene tendré unas largas vacaciones en Francia.)\n\n> **Nota: En el ejemplo \"He had a shower...\", también podemos decir \"He showered,\" (\"Él se duchó...\"), pero utilizando la estructura \"delexical\" podemos incluir información adicional con el uso de __un adjetivo__ (\"hot\").** También es importante tener en cuenta que la estructura \"delexical\" tal vez es más utilizada que el verbo \"**to shower**\". Este es el caso no sólo con el ejemplo mencionado, sino en muchos de los ejemplos que presentamos aquí.\n\nOtros sustantivos con los que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**have**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** lunch, dinner, a snack, coffee, a chat, a discussion, a talk, a bath, a break, a rest, a dispute, a fight...\n\n## Take\n\n\"**Take**\", como \"**have**\", se usa con lavado o descansos, así como varios otros sustantivos.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I need to **take a __long__, __hot__ bath**.\n> **Translation:** (Necesito tomar un baño largo y caliente.)\n\n> **Example:** **Take a break**, you look exhausted.\n> **Translation:** (Toma un descanso, te veo agotado.)\n\n> **Example:** Nancy doesn't like to **take risks**.\n> **Translation:** (A Nancy no le gusta correr riesgos.)\n\n> **Example:** Can you **take care of** my dogs while I am on vacation?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puedes cuidar de mis perros mientras esté de vacaciones?)\n\nOtros sustantivos con que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**take**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** care, a chance, a photograph, a turn...\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Tanto \"\n> >\n> > have\n> >\n> > \" como \"\n> >\n> > take\n> >\n> > \" se pueden utilizar con las formas sustantivas de ciertos verbos.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Let's **have a swim**, it's hot.\n> > **Translation:** (Vamos a bañarnos, hace calor.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Can you **take a look** at my article before I submit it to the publisher?\n> > **Translation:** (¿Puedes echar un vistazo a mi artículo antes de enviarlo al editor?)\n\n## Make\n\nUtilizamos \"**make**\" con planes, viajes y en referencia a hablar.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Have you **made the arrangements** for your trip yet?\n> **Translation:** (¿Has hecho los arreglos para tu viaje?)\n\n> **Example:** My parents **made a __quick__ visit** to the British Museum when they were in London.\n> **Translation:** (Mis padres hicieron una visita rápida al Museo Británico cuando estaban en Londres.)\n\n> **Example:** Helen **made a __very important__ point** in the meeting this morning.\n> **Translation:** (Helen hizo una observación muy importante en la reunión esta mañana.)\n\n> **Example:** The President **will make his speech** at the end of the inauguration.\n> **Translation:** (El presidente hará su discurso al final de la inauguración.)\n\nOtros sustantivos con que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**make**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** a sound, conversation, a comment, a noise, a promise, a suggestion, a choice, a decision, a plan, a trip, a tour...\n\n## Give\n\n\"**Give**\" se utiliza con ruidos, expresiones faciales, cariño o en referencia a golpear y hablar.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** **Give me a shout** when you are ready to go.\n> **Translation:** (Dame un toque cuando estés listo para ir.)\n\n> **Example:** Please **give Sally a __big__ hug** for me!\n> **Translation:** (Por favor, dale a Sally un gran abrazo de mi parte.)\n\n> **Example:** My dad always **gives me __good__ advice**.\n> **Translation:** (Mi padre siempre me da buenos consejos.)\n\n> **Example:** Go ahead, **give it a kick**!\n> **Translation:** (Venga, dale una patada.)\n\nOtros sustantivos con los que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**give**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** a cry, a laugh, a scream, a smile, a look, a glance, a punch, a slap, a push, a kiss, an answer, information, an interview, a lecture, a report, a warning...\n\n## Go and Do\n\n\"**Go**\" y \"**do**\" también se pueden utilizar como verbos \"delexical\", pero la estructura con estos verbos es diferente. **Utilizamos estos verbos a menudo con sustantivos terminados en \"-ing\".**\n\n### Go\n\n\"**Go**\" se utiliza en general para las actividades comunes que implican movimiento. Utilizamos la estructura \"**go for a**\" cuando el sustantivo no termina en \"**-ing**\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Beth **goes swimming** every day.\n> **Translation:** (Beth va a nadar todos los días.)\n\n> **Example:** Nina doesn't like to **go shopping**.\n> **Translation:** (A Nina no le gusta ir de compras.)\n\n> **Example:** It's a beautiful day, we should **go for a walk**.\n> **Translation:** (Es un día hermoso, deberíamos dar un paseo.)\n\nOtros sustantivos con los que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**go**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** running, walking, jogging, skiing, a jog, a ride, a swim, a run, a stroll...\n\n### Do\n\n\"**Do**\" se utiliza a menudo con las actividades relacionadas con trabajo. También utilizamos \"**do**\" cuando la acción es evidente.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Can you please **do the washing**?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puedes hacer el lavado por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** You rest, I'll **do the cooking** today.\n> **Translation:** (Descansa, haré la comida hoy.)\n\n> **Example:** Let me help you **do your hair**.\n> **Translation:** (Déjame ayudarte a arreglar tu cabello.)\n\nOtros sustantivos con los que podemos utilizar el verbo \"**do**\" en las estructuras \"delexical\" pueden ser:\n\n> **Tip:** jobs, work, homework, the washing up, the cleaning, the dishes, exercise, research, damage...\n\n> **Nota:** Ver la lesson Do vs. Make para más estructuras \"delexical\" con estos dos verbos.",
                "en": "**Delexical verbs are common verbs such as \"have\", \"take\", \"make\" or \"give\" which when used with particular nouns have very little meaning of their own. In these delexical structures most of the meaning is found in the noun, not in the verb**. In most cases, there is a verb which has a similar meaning to the delexical structure. Delexical structures are very common in English and an understanding of them will enrich one's fluency of the language.\n\n**Using delexical structures allows us to add additional information to the action by using adjectives** with the nouns, rather than an adverb, which at times can sound awkward.\n\nLet's take a look at some examples with each particular verb.\n\n## Have\n\n**\"Have\" on it's own indicates possession, but when used in delexical structures the meaning changes.** We can use \"**have**\" when talking about meals, conversations and disagreements, washing or resting.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** We **have breakfast** every morning at 8 o'clock.\n\n> **Example:** Lets **have a drink**!\n\n> **Example:** They **had an argument** last night.\n\n> **Example:** John **had a __hot__ shower** after his day out in the cold.\n\n> **Example:** I'm not happy. We need to **have a conversation**.\n\n> **Example:** Next year I **will have a __long__ holiday** in France.\n\n> **Note: In the example above, \"He had a shower...\", we could also say \"He showered,\" but by using the delexical structure we are able to include additional details with the use of an __adjective__ (\"hot\").** It's also important to note that the delexical structure \"**have a shower**\" is perhaps more commonly used than the actual verb \"**to shower**\". This is the case not only with the above mentioned example, but in many of the examples discussed here.\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**have**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** lunch, dinner, a snack, coffee, a chat, a discussion, a talk, a bath, a break, a rest, a dispute, a fight...\n\n## Take\n\n\"**Take**\", like \"**have**\", is used with washing or resting as well as several other nouns.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I need to **take a __long__, __hot__ bath**.\n\n> **Example:** **Take a break**, you look exhausted.\n\n> **Example:** Nancy doesn't like to **take risks**.\n\n> **Example:** Can you **take care of** my dogs while I am on vacation?\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**take**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** care, a chance, a photograph, a turn...\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : Both \"\n> >\n> > have\n> >\n> > \" and \"\n> >\n> > take\n> >\n> > \" can be used with the noun forms of certain verbs.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Let's **have a swim**, it's hot.\n>\n> > **Example:** Can you **take a look** at my article before I submit it to the publisher?\n\n## Make\n\nWe use \"**make**\" with plans, travel and with reference to talking.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Have you **made the arrangements** for your trip yet?\n\n> **Example:** My parents **made a __quick__ visit** to the British Museum when they were in London.\n\n> **Example:** Helen **made a __very important__ point** in the meeting this morning.\n\n> **Example:** The President **will make his speech** at the end of the inauguration.\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**make**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** a sound, conversation, a comment, a noise, a promise, a suggestion, a choice, a decision, a plan, a trip, a tour...\n\n## Give\n\n\"**Give**\" is used with noises, facial expressions, affection, hitting and talking.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** **Give me a shout** when you are ready to go.\n\n> **Example:** Please **give Sally a __big__ hug** for me!\n\n> **Example:** My dad always **gives me __good__ advice**.\n\n> **Example:** Go ahead, **give it a kick**!\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**give**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** a cry, a laugh, a scream, a smile, a look, a glance, a punch, a slap, a push, a kiss, an answer, information, an interview, a lecture, a report, a warning...\n\n## Go and Do\n\n\"**Go**\" and \"**do**\" can also be used as delexical verbs, but the structure with these verbs is different. **We frequently use these verbs in delexical structures with \"-ing\" nouns.**\n\n### Go\n\n\"**Go**\" is generally used for common activities that involve movement. We use the construction \"**go for a**\" when the noun is not a \"**-ing**\" noun.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Beth **goes swimming** every day.\n\n> **Example:** Nina doesn't like to **go shopping**.\n\n> **Example:** It's a beautiful day, we should **go for a walk**.\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**go**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** running, walking, jogging, skiing, a jog, a ride, a swim, a run, a stroll...\n\n### Do\n\n\"**Do**\" is often used with work related activities. We also use \"**do**\" when the action is obvious.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Can you please **do the washing**?\n\n> **Example:** You rest, I'll **do the cooking** today.\n\n> **Example:** Let me help you **do your hair**.\n\nOther nouns which we use with the verb \"**do**\" in delexical structure include:\n\n> **Tip:** jobs, work, homework, the washing up, the cleaning, the dishes, exercise, research, damage...\n\n> **Note:** See the lesson Do vs. Make for more delexical structures with these two verbs."
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "code": 10033,
          "order": 8,
          "slug": {
            "es": "linking-words",
            "en": "linking-words"
          },
          "display": {
            "es": "Palabras de enlace",
            "en": "Linking Words"
          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 237,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "adding-information",
                "en": "adding-information"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Agregar información",
                "en": "Adding Information"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Linking words, también conocidos como \"connectors\", son palabras que vinculan o relacionan dos ideas**, dentro de una oración (conectando dos cláusulas) o dentro de un párrafo (conectando dos frases). Ya hemos introducido este concepto en una lección anterior (Conjunctions), ahora profundizaremos más en ellas.\n\nLos linking words o conectores, **tienen varias funciones, tales como contrastar información, hacer comparaciones, agregar información o dar razones o explicaciones. Si usamos incorrectamente estas palabras podemos cambiar completamente el significado de la frase y puede causar confusión.** Por lo tanto, es importante tener una buena comprensión de los diversos significados y usos de estas palabras. Mediante el uso de linking words mejoramos el nivel de inglés ya que nos permiten expresarnos de manera más compleja. Las siguientes lecciones proporcionan una explicación de las diferentes funciones de relacionar palabras y las reglas gramaticales para su uso.\n\n## Agregar información\n\nLa siguiente lista incluye linking words que se utilizan para agregar o proporcionar más información.\n\n### And\n\nTraducido como 'y', esta linking word es la más común para añadir información. \"**And**\" se utiliza en oraciones, con frecuencia en listas separadas por comas, aunque nunca se utiliza una coma antes ni después de \"**and**\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sport. He plays football, basketball **and** tennis.\n> **Translation:** (Le encanta el deporte. Juega a fútbol, baloncesto y tenis.)\n\n### Also\n\n\"**Also**\", o 'también' en español, se utiliza entre el sujeto y el verbo para dar información adicional o para dar énfasis.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He **also** likes to ski.\n> **Translation:** (También le gusta esquiar.)\n\n### In addition\n\nCon frecuencia se encuentra al principio de una oración, \"**in addition**\" ('además' en español) se usa para añadir información a la oración anterior.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **In addition** to playing many sports, he coaches a handball team.\n> **Translation:** (Además de practicar muchos deportes, él entrena a un equipo de balonmano.)\n\n### As well as\n\nEsta linking word, traducida como 'además de' en español, puede utilizarse al principio o en medio de una frase.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He plays football **as well as** basketball.\n> **Translation:** (Juega a fútbol además de baloncesto.)\n\n### Too\n\n\"**Too**\" puede encontrarse al final de una oración o entre el sujeto y el verbo; significa 'también'.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He plays tennis **too**.\n> **Translation:** (Juega a tenis también.)\n\n### Besides\n\nGeneralmente se encuentra al principio de una oración, \"**besides**\" tiene un significado muy similar a \"**as well**\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **Besides** playing many sports, he also coaches handball.\n> **Translation:** (Además de practicar muchos deportes, él también entrena balonmano.)\n\n### Furthermore\n\nEsta linking word se traduce como 'además', pero es más formal. Agrega información adicional a una idea y se encuentra generalmente al principio de una frase.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sports for the excitement and competition. **Furthermore**, the exercise is good for his health.\n> **Translation:** (Le encantan los deportes por la emoción y la competición. Además, el ejercicio es bueno para su salud.)\n\n### Moreover\n\nComo \"**furthermore**\", este añade información adicional a una idea y se encuentra generalmente al principio de una frase.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sports for the excitement and competition. **Moreover**, the exercise is good for his health.\n> **Translation:** (Le encantan los deportes por la emoción y la competición. Además, el ejercicio es bueno para su salud.)",
                "en": "**Linking words, sometimes also referred to as \"connectors\", are words that link or relate two ideas**, either within a sentence (connecting two clauses) or within a paragraph (linking two sentences). We have already introduced this concept in a previous lesson (Conjunctions), but with this lesson we will go into further detail.\n\nLinking words **have various functions, such as for contrasting information, making comparisons, adding information or giving reasons or explanations. Using the incorrect linking word can entirely change the meaning of the sentence and can cause quite a bit of confusion.** It is therefore important to have a good understanding of the various meanings and uses of these words. These words are also a great way of improving your English as they allow you to express yourself in a more complex manner. The following lessons provide an explanation of the various functions of linking words and the grammatical rules for their use.\n\n## Adding Information\n\nThe following list includes linking words used to add or provide more information.\n\n### And\n\nThe most common linking word for adding information, \"**and**\" is used within sentences, frequently in lists which are separated by commas, though a comma is never used before or after the \"**and**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sport. He plays football, basketball **and** tennis.\n\n### Also\n\n\"**Also**\" is used between a subject and verb to give extra information or to give emphasis.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He **also** likes to ski.\n\n### In addition\n\nFrequently found at the beginning of a sentence, \"**in addition**\" is used to add information to the previous sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **In addition** to playing many sports, he coaches a handball team.\n\n### As well as\n\nThis linking word can be used at the beginning or in the middle of a sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He plays football **as well as** basketball.\n\n### Too\n\n\"**Too**\" may be found at either the end of a sentence or between the subject and verb; it means \"**as well**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He plays tennis **too**.\n\n### Besides\n\nGenerally found at the beginning of a sentence, \"**besides**\" has a very similar meaning to \"**as well as**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **Besides** playing many sports, he also coaches handball.\n\n### Furthermore\n\nThis more formal linking word adds additional information to an idea and is generally found at the beginning of a sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sports for the excitement and competition. **Furthermore**, the exercise is good for his health.\n\n### Moreover\n\nLike \"**furthermore**\", this connector adds additional information to an idea and is generally found at the beginning of a sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** He loves sports for the excitement and competition. **Moreover**, the exercise is good for his health."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 243,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "contrasting-information",
                "en": "contrasting-information"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Contrastar información",
                "en": "Contrasting Information"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "Como hemos visto en la lección anterior, **las linking words**, palabras de vinculación, tienen diversas funciones. **Además de agregar información, permiten contrastar información o presentar ideas condicionales.**\n\n## Ideas contrastantes\n\n**Las siguientes palabras se utilizan para presentar el contraste entre dos ideas.** Cuando se utiliza una de estas palabras entre dos cláusulas contrastantes, debemos usar una coma al final de la primera cláusula, antes de la linking word.\n\n### But\n\n**La palabra más común para contrastar ideas, \"but\" generalmente se encuentra entre las dos ideas contrastantes** dentro de una oración y siempre sigue a una coma. Se traduce como \"pero\" en español.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **but** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, pero los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Yet\n\n\"**Yet**\" se utiliza de la misma manera que \"**but**\", aunque generalmente se considera más formal.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **yet** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, sin embargo, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### However\n\nGeneralmente se encuentra al principio de una frase, \"**however**\" es más formal que \"**but**\". Se traduce como \"sin embargo\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving. **However**, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando. Sin embargo, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Although\n\nEsta palabra puede utilizarse al principio de una oración o entre las dos cláusulas contrastantes. Se traduce como \"aunque\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **Although** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Aunque hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Though\n\nComo \"**although**\", puede utilizarse al principio de una oración o entre las dos cláusulas contrastantes. Se traduce como \"aunque\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs the economy is improving, **though** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, aunque los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Even though\n\nGeneralmente se encuentra al principio de una frase, \"**even though**\" también se puede utilizar entre dos cláusulas.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **Even though** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Aunque hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Despite\n\nEsta palabra debe ir seguida por un __sustantivo__ o un __gerundio__ (verbo+ing). Si va a ir seguida de una __cláusula__ (__verbo sujeto__), debemos usar \"**Despite the fact that**\". Se traduce como \"a pesar de\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **Despite** __signs__ that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (A pesar de los indicios de que la economía está mejorando, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### In spite of\n\nLas reglas para el uso de esta linking word son iguales que las de \"**despite**\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **In spite of the fact that** __there are signs__ that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (A pesar de que hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Nevertheless\n\nEl significado de \"**nevertheless**\" equivale a \"**in spite of**\" y puede ser utilizada al principio de una oración o entre las dos cláusulas. Siempre va seguida por una coma. Se traduce como \"no obstante\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving. **Nevertheless**, economists warn that it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando. No obstante, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### Nonetheless\n\nSe utiliza del mismo modo que \"**nevertheless**\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **nonetheless**, economists warn that it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando. No obstante, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años más antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n### While\n\nEncontramos \"**while**\" frecuentemente al principio de la frase.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **While** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn that it will be several years before the crisis ends.\n> **Translation:** (Si bien hay indicios de que la economía está mejorando, los economistas advierten que pasarán varios años antes de que la crisis termine.)\n\n## Conditional Ideas\n\n**Las siguientes palabras se utilizan cuando una idea es dependiente de otra**. Estas palabras condicionales siempre se encuentran delante de la cláusula condicional. Ver la lección sobre los conditionales para obtener más información.\n\n### Providing\n\nEsta palabra puede utilizarse en lugar de \"**if**\", aunque suele ser más formal. Se utiliza frecuentemente con permisos y puede ser utilizada al principio o en el medio de la oración.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **providing** it doesn't rain.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa si no llueve.)\n\n### Provided that\n\n\"**Provided that**\" se usa de la misma manera que \"**providing**\". Se traduce como \"a condición de\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** **Provided that** it doesn't rain, we will go to the beach.\n> **Translation:** (A condición de que no llueva, iremos a la playa.)\n\n### As/so long as\n\nEsta linking word funciona de la misma manera que \"**providing**\" o \"**provided that**\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **as long as** it doesn't rain.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa mientras no llueva.)\n\n### Unless\n\nEsta palabra indica una excepción a la condición. Se utiliza siempre antes de un verbo afirmativo para expresar la idea de \"**if...not**\". Se traduce como \"a menos que\"\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **unless** it rains.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa a menos que llueva.)\n\n### Only if\n\n\"**Only if**\" se utiliza para restringir la condición, indicando que sólo hay una condición que hará realidad la cláusula principal. Se traduce como \"sólo si\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **only if** it doesn't rain.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa sólo si no llueve.)\n\n### Even if\n\nEsta palabra se usa para expresar la idea de que la condición es irrelevante; que los resultados serán los mismos. Se traduce como \"aun si\" o \"incluso si\".\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **even if** it rains.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa aun si llueve.)\n\n### Whether or not\n\nComo \"**even if**\", \"**whether or not**\" se utiliza para expresar la irrelevancia de las condiciones, ya que el resultado será el mismo.\n\nEjemplo:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **whether or not** it rains.\n> **Translation:** (Iremos a la playa llueva o no llueva.)",
                "en": "As we learned in the previous lesson, **linking words** have various functions. In addition to adding information, **they can also be used to contrast information or to present conditional statements**.\n\n## Contrasting Ideas\n\n**The following linking words are used to present contrast between two ideas.** When the linking word is used in between the two contrasting clauses, we must use a comma at the end of the first clause, before the linking word.\n\n### But\n\n**The most common word used for contrasting ideas, \"but\" is generally found in between the two contrasting ideas** within a sentence and always follows a comma.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **but** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Yet\n\n\"**Yet**\" is used in much the same way as \"**but**\", though is generally considered more formal.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **yet** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### However\n\nGenerally found at the beginning of a sentence, \"**however**\" is more formal than '**but**'.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving. **However**, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Although\n\nThis linking word can be used at the beginning of a sentence or between the two contrasting clauses.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **Although** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Though\n\nLike \"**although**\", it can be used at the beginning of a sentence or between the two clauses.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs the economy is improving, **though** economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Even though\n\nGenerally found at the beginning of a sentence, \"**even though**\" can also be used between two clauses.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **Even though** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Despite\n\nThis linking word must be followed by a __noun__ or a __gerund__ (verb+ing). If we want to follow it by a __clause (subject + verb)__, we must use \"**despite the fact that**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **Despite** __signs__ that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### In spite of\n\nThe rules for the use of this linking word are the same as those for \"**despite**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **In spite of the fact that** __there are signs__ that the economy is improving, economists warn it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Nevertheless\n\nThe meaning of \"**nevertheless**\" is equivalent to \"**in spite of**\" and can be used at the beginning of a sentence or between the two clauses. It is always followed by a comma.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving. **Nevertheless**, economists warn that it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### Nonetheless\n\nThis connector is used in the same way as \"**nevertheless**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** There are signs that the economy is improving, **nonetheless**, economists warn that it will be several more years before the crisis ends.\n\n### While\n\n\"**While**\" is most frequently found at the beginning of a sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **While** there are signs that the economy is improving, economists warn that it will be several years before the crisis ends.\n\n## Conditional Ideas\n\n**The following linking words are used when one idea is dependent on another**. Conditional linking words are always found before the conditional clause. See the lesson on conditionals for more information.\n\n### Providing\n\nThis linking word can be used in place of \"**if**\", though it tends to be more formal. It is frequently used with permissions and can be used at the beginning or the middle of the sentence.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **providing** it doesn't rain.\n\n### Provided that\n\n\"**Provided that**\" is used in the same way as \"**providing**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** **Provided that** it doesn't rain, we will go to the beach.\n\n### As/so long as\n\nThis connector functions in the same way as \"**providing**\" or \"**provided that**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **as long as** it doesn't rain.\n\n### Unless\n\nThis linking word indicates an exception to the condition. It is always used before an affirmative verb to express the idea of \"**if...not**\".\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **unless** it rains.\n\n### Only if\n\n\"**Only if**\" is used to restrict the condition, indicating that there is only one condition which will make the main clause true.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **only if** it doesn't rain.\n\n### Even if\n\nThis linking word is used to express the idea that the condition is irrelevant; that the results will be the same.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **even if** it rains.\n\n### Whether or not\n\nLike \"**even if**\", \"**whether or not**\" is used to express the irrelevance of the conditions, as the result will be the same.\n\nExample:\n\n> **Example:** We will go to the beach **whether or not** it rains."
              }
