            {
              "code": 91,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "so-vs-such",
                "en": "so-vs-such"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Tan vs. tal",
                "en": "So vs. Such"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "**Utilizamos \"so\" (tan, así, entonces) y \"such\" (semejante, tal, tan, tanto) para añadir énfasis, mostrar sentimientos extremos o para dar la opinión sobre algo**. La diferencia entre los dos está en cómo los utilizamos en la estructura de las frases.\n\n## So\n\n### so + adjective/adverb (tan + adjetivo/adverbio)\n\n**Utilizamos \"so\" con adjetivos o adverbios para mostrar sentimientos o efectos extremos.** En estos casos, el adjetivo o adverbio va directamente despues de \"**so**\" en la frase.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I have been working since 7 this morning. I'm **so** __tired__!\n> **Translation:** (He estado trabajando desde las 7 de la mañana. ¡Estoy tan cansada!)\n\n> **Example:** Why are you driving **so** __fast__?\n> **Translation:** (¿Por qué estás conduciendo tan rápido?)\n\n> **Example:** Kate is **so** __beautiful__. I can't believe she's single!\n> **Translation:** (Kate es tan hermosa. íNo puedo creer que esté soltera!)\n\n> **Example:** My daughter studied **so** __hard__ for her exam.\n> **Translation:** (Mi hija estudió tan duramente para su examen.)\n\n### so + quantifier + noun (tan + cuantificador + sustantivo)\n\n**Podemos utilizar los cuantificadores (\"many\", \"much\", \"little\", etc.) con \"so\" para indicar extremos en cantidad**, pero hace falta recordar las reglas de usos de los cuantificadores y contables e incontables, singulares y plurales (para más información, ver la lección de los cuantificadores.) Estos son los únicos casos en los que \"**so**\" se usa con un sustantivo. \"**So much**\" o \"**so many**\" pueden ser traducidos también como \"tantos\" en español.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Teresa has **so** __many__ __talents__!\n> **Translation:** (¡Teresa tiene tantos talentos!)\n\n> **Example:** With three kids and a full-time job, my sister has **so** __little__ __free__ __time__.\n> **Translation:** (Con tres hijos y un trabajo de jornada completa, mi hermana tiene tan poco tiempo libre.)\n\n> **Example:** I have **so** __few__ __memories__ of my childhood.\n> **Translation:** (Tengo tan pocos recuerdos de mi infancia.)\n\n> **Example:** The children watch **so** __much__ __television__.\n> **Translation:** (Los niños miran tanta televisión.)\n\n### so + that (tan + que)\n\nPodemos utilizar \"**so**\" con \"**that**\" para mostrar resultados o consecuencias. En general, el uso de \"**that**\" es opcional.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** The music was **so** __loud__ **that** I couldn't hear my own voice.\n> **Translation:** (La música era tan fuerte que no podía oír mi propia voz.)\n\n> **Example:** He was driving **so** __fast__ **that** he had an accident.\n> **Translation:** (Estaba conduciendo tan rápido que tuvo un accidente.)\n\n> **Example:** My son studied **so** __hard__ **that** he received the best grade in the class.\n> **Translation:** (Mi hijo estudió tan duramente que recibió la mejor nota de la clase.)\n\n## Such\n\n### such + adjective + noun (tan + adjetivo + sustantivo)\n\nComo con \"**so**\", utilizamos \"**such**\" con adjetivos para mostrar extremos. **A diferencia de \"so\", \"such\" está seguido por un adjetivo más un sustantivo.** Las frases que utilizan \"**such**\" para dar énfasis se pueden traducir como \"¡Que!\" en español (ver el tercer ejemplo).\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I am **so** __lucky__. I have **such** __wonderful__ __friends__!\n> **Translation:** (Tengo tanta suerte. ¡Tengo amigos tan maravillosos!)\n\n> **Example:** That is **such** a __pretty__ __dress__! You should wear it more often.\n> **Translation:** (¡Este vestido es tan bonito! Debería llevarlo más a menudo.)\n\n> **Example:** It is **such** a __beautiful__ __day__\n> **Translation:** (¡Que día tan bonito!)\n\n> **Nota**: No se puede utilizar \"**such**\" con los cuantificadores como \"**much**\", \"**many**\", \"**few**\", o \"**little**\". Sólo con \"**so**\" se pueden utilizar estos cuantificadores.\n\n### such + that (tan + que)\n\nComo con \"**so**\", podemos utilizar \"**such**\" con \"**that**\" para mostrar extremos que terminan en un resultado. En general, el uso de \"**that**\" es opcional.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** It was **such** a __beautiful__ __day__ **that** we decided to go to the beach.\n> **Translation:** (Fue un día tan bonito que decidimos ir a la playa.)\n\n> **Example:** Dave has **such** a __small__ __car__ **that** he doesn't have to spend much money on gas.\n> **Translation:** (Dave tiene un coche tan pequeño que no tiene que gastar mucho dinero en gasolina.)\n\n> **Example:** It was **such** a __good__ __meal__ **that** we made it again the next night.\n> **Translation:** (Era una comida tan buena que la hicimos otra vez la siguiente noche.)\n\n### such + judgmental noun (tan + sustantivo critico)\n\nCon sustantivos críticos, el uso de \"**such**\" da énfasis.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I have never liked Andy. He is **such** a __jerk__!\n> **Translation:** (Nunca me ha gustado Andy. ¡Es tan idiota!)\n\n> **Example:** You are **such** a __clown__! Are you ever serious?\n> **Translation:** (Eres un payaso. ¿Jamás estás serio?)\n\n### such + noun (tal + sustantivo)\n\nCuando \"**such**\" está seguido directamente por un sustantivo, \"**such**\" significa \"tal\" o \"un tipo de\".\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I have never seen **such** __architecture__ before.\n> **Translation:** (Nunca he visto tal arquitectura antes.)\n\n> **Example:** We very rarely listen to **such** __music__.\n> **Translation:** (Muy raramente escuchamos tal música.)",
                "en": "**\"So\" and \"such\" are used to add emphasis, to show extreme emotions or to give an opinion on something**. The difference between the two is in their use within the structure of the sentence.\n\n## So\n\n### so + adjective/adverb\n\n**We use \"so\" with adjectives and adverbs to show emotions or extreme effects.** In these instances, the adjective or adverb is found directly after \"**so**\" in the sentence.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I have been working since 7 this morning. I'm **so** __tired__!\n\n> **Example:** Why are you driving **so** __fast__?\n\n> **Example:** Kate is **so** __beautiful__. I can't believe she's single!\n\n> **Example:** My daughter studied **so** __hard__ for her exam.\n\n### so + quantifier [many/few, much/little] + noun\n\n**\"So\" can be used with quantifiers to indicate extremes in quantity**, but it is important to remember the rules regarding the uses of quantifiers, countable and uncountable nouns, singulars and plurals. See the lesson on quantifiers for more information. These are the only cases in which \"**so**\" is used with a noun.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Teresa has **so** __many__ __talents__!\n\n> **Example:** With three kids and a full-time job, my sister has **so** __little__ __free__ __time__.\n\n> **Example:** I have **so** __few__ __memories__ of my childhood.\n\n> **Example:** The children watch **so** __much__ __television__.\n\n### so + that\n\nWe use \"**so**\" with \"**that**\", to show results or consequences. In general, the use of \"**that**\" is optional.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** The music was **so** __loud__ **that** I couldn't hear my own voice.\n\n> **Example:** He was driving **so** __fast__ **that** he had an accident.\n\n> **Example:** My son studied **so** __hard__ **that** he received the best grade in the class.\n\n## Such\n\n### such + adjective + noun\n\nAs with \"**so**\", we use \"**such**\" with adjectives to show extremes, but **as opposed to \"so\", \"such\" is followed by an adjective as well as a noun.**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I am so __lucky__. I have **such** __wonderful__ __friends__!\n\n> **Example:** That is **such** a __pretty__ __dress__! You should wear it more often.\n\n> **Example:** It is **such** a __beautiful__ __day__!\n\n> **Note:** \"**Such**\" cannot be used with quantifiers such as \"**much**\", \"**many**\", \"**few**\", o \"**little**\". Only \"**so**\" can be used with these quantifiers.\n\n### such + that\n\nAs with \"**so**\", \"**such**\" is used with \"**that**\" to show extremes that end in a particular result. In these cases, as with \"**so**\", the use of \"that\" is optional.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** It was **such** a __beautiful__ __day__ **that** we decided to go to the beach.\n\n> **Example:** Dave has **such** a __small__ __car__ **that** he doesn't have to spend much money on gas.\n\n> **Example:** It was **such** a __good__ __meal__ **that** we made it again the next night.\n\n### such + judgmental noun\n\nWith judgmental nouns, the use of \"**such**\" gives emphasis.\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I have never liked Andy. He is **such** a __jerk__!\n\n> **Example:** You are **such** a __clown__! Are you ever serious?\n\n### such + noun\n\nWhen \"**such**\" is followed directly by a noun, \"**such**\" means \"**a type of**\".\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I have never seen **such** __architecture__ before.\n\n> **Example:** We very rarely listen to **such** __music__."
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 199,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "enough-and-too",
                "en": "enough-and-too"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Suficiente y demasiado",
                "en": "Enough and Too"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "\"**Enough**\" y \"**too**\" se utilizan como calificadores con adjetivos, adverbios y nombres para indicar un grado de cantidad.\n\n## Enough (Suficiente)\n\n\"**Enough**\" es un adjetivo que se usa para indicar que es suficiente o igual que lo necesario. Se puede utilizar con otros adjetivos, adverbios o nombres.\n\n**1. Con adjetivos y adverbios:**\n\n> **Tip:** adjetivo/adverbio\n>\n> + \"enough\"\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Heather is __old__ **enough** now to make her own decisions.\n> **Translation:** (Heather es lo suficientemente mayor ahora para tomar sus propias decisiones.)\n\n> **Example:** Victor doesn't speak English __well__ **enough** for the job.\n> **Translation:** (Victor no habla suficientemente bien el inglés para este trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** The apartment is __big__ **enough** for three people.\n> **Translation:** (El piso es lo suficientemente grande para tres personas.)\n\n> **Example:** Ben runs __fast__ **enough** to win the race.\n> **Translation:** (Ben corre lo suficientemente rápido como para ganar esta carrera.)\n\n> **Example:** We aren't working __hard__ **enough**! We are never going to finish this project.\n> **Translation:** (No trabajamos lo suficientemente duro. Nunca acabaremos este proyecto.)\n\n**2. Con nombres:**\n\n> **Tip:** \"enough\" +\n>\n> nombre\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I don't have **enough** __time__ to finish all this work!\n> **Translation:** (No tengo tiempo suficiente para acabar este trabajo.)\n\n> **Example:** Is there **enough** __wine__ for everyone to try?\n> **Translation:** (¿Hay suficiente vino para que todos lo prueben?)\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, they have **enough** __space__ in the car for all of us.\n> **Translation:** (No se preocupe, tienen sitio suficiente en el coche para todos nosotros.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Podemos reemplazar \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" por \"\n> >\n> > the\n> >\n> > \" para indicar la misma cosa. Compare los ejemplos de arriba y abajo.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** I don't have **the** __time__ to finish all this work!\n> > **Translation:** (No tengo tiempo para acabar este trabajo.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Don't worry, they have **the** __space__ for all of us.\n> > **Translation:** (No se preocupe, tienen sitio para todos nosotros.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : También podemos utilizar \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" sin un nombre cuando está claro a que nos referimos.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** Would you like some more coffee? No, I've had **enough**, thank you.\n> > **Translation:** (¿Le gustaría un poco más de café? No, he tenido suficiente, gracias.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Do you have **enough** to pay for this?\n> > **Translation:** (¿Tienes suficiente para pagar esto?)\n\n**3. Podemos usar \"enough\" con un __adjetivo y un nombre__, pero el sentido de la frase cambia con la posición de \"enough\"**.\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** Is there **enough** __hot water__?\n> **Translation:** (¿Hay suficiente agua caliente?)\n\n> **Example:** Is there __hot__ **enough** __water__?\n> **Translation:** (¿Hay agua suficientemente caliente?)\n\n**4. \"Enough of\"**\n\n> **Tip:** \"enough of\" +\n>\n> determinante\n>\n> [articulo o pronombre]\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** I've been in **enough of** __these__ situations to know better!\n> **Translation:** (He estado en bastantes situaciones de estas como para conocer mejor.)\n\n> **Example:** We've had **enough of** __your__ complaints. Don't you have anything positive to say?\n> **Translation:** (Tenemos bastante con tus quejas. ¿No tienes nada positivo que decir?)\n\n> **Example:** Michael has studied **enough of** __the__ possibilities to make a good decision.\n> **Translation:** (Michael ha estudiado bastantes de las posibilidades como para tomar una buena decisión.)\n\n## Too (Demasiado)\n\n\"**Too**\" es un adverbio que indica que hay una cantidad más que suficiente.\n\n**1. Con un adjetivo o un adverbio:**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too\" +\n>\n> adjetivo/ adverbio\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** You are **too** __young__ to understand.\n> **Translation:** (Eres demasiado joven para entender.)\n\n> **Example:** Claire is **too** __irresponsible__ to have a dog.\n> **Translation:** (Claire es demasiado irresponsable como para tener un perro.)\n\n> **Example:** It's **too** __early__ to go to bed.\n> **Translation:** (Es demasiado temprano para ir a la cama.)\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Nota\n> >\n> > : Podemos usar \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" en una frase negativa para indicar que algo no es suficiente. Compara los ejemplos de arriba con los de abajo.\n>\n> Ejemplos:\n>\n> > **Example:** You are __not old__ **enough** to understand.\n> > **Translation:** (No eres lo suficientemente mayor para entender.)\n>\n> > **Example:** Claire is __not responsible__ **enough** to have a dog.\n> > **Translation:** (Claire no es lo suficientemente responsable como para tener un perro.)\n\n**2. Cuando usamos \"too\" con nombres, utilizamos las expresiones \"too many\" o \"too much\".**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too many\" +\n>\n> nombre contable\n\n> **Tip:** \"too much\" +\n>\n> nombre incontable\n\nEjemplos:\n\n> **Example:** There are **too many** __students__ in the classroom.\n> **Translation:** (Hay demasiados estudiantes para esta clase.)\n\n> **Example:** Is there **too much** __sugar__ in your coffee?\n> **Translation:** (¿Hay demasiado azúcar en tu café?)\n\n> **Example:** My daughter has **too many** __shoes__, she doesn't need any more!\n> **Translation:** (Mi hija tiene demasiados zapatos, no necesita más.)\n\n> **Example:** There is **too much** __work__ for just one person!\n> **Translation:** (Hay demasiado trabajo para una sola persona.)\n\n**3. \"Too much of\" o \"Too many of\"**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too many of\" +\n>\n> determinante\n>\n> +\n>\n> nombre contable\n\n> **Tip:** \"too much of\" +\n>\n> determinante\n>\n> +\n>\n> nombre incontable\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** His problem is that he spends **too much of** __his__ __time__ playing video games!\n> **Translation:** (Su problema es que pasa demasiado tiempo jugando a videojuegos.)\n\n> **Example:** That's enough. You have already eaten **too many of** __the__ __chocolates__!\n> **Translation:** (Basta ya. Ya has comido demasiados bombones.)",
                "en": "\"**Enough**\" and \"**too**\" are used to as qualifiers with adjectives, adverbs and nouns to indicate degree.\n\n## Enough\n\n\"**Enough**\" is an adjective which is used to mean sufficient or equal to what is necessary. It can be used with other adjectives, adverbs or nouns.\n\n**1. With adjectives and adverbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** adjective/adverb\n>\n> + \"enough\"\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Heather is __old__ **enough** now to make her own decisions.\n\n> **Example:** Victor doesn't speak English __well__ **enough** for the job.\n\n> **Example:** The apartment is __big__ **enough** for three people.\n\n> **Example:** Ben runs __fast__ **enough** to win the race.\n\n> **Example:** We aren't working __hard__ **enough**! We are never going to finish this project.\n\n**2. With nouns:**\n\n> **Tip:** \"enough\" +\n>\n> noun\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I don't have **enough** __time__ to finish all this work!\n\n> **Example:** Is there **enough** __wine__ for everyone to try?\n\n> **Example:** Don't worry, they have **enough** __space__ in the car for all of us.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : We can replace \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" with the \"\n> >\n> > the\n> >\n> > \" to indicate the same thing. Compare the examples above and below.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** I don't have **the** __time__ to finish all this work!\n>\n> > **Example:** Don't worry, they have **the** __space__ for all of us.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : We can also use \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" without a noun when it is clear what it is we are referring to.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** Would you like some more coffee? No, I've had **enough**, thank you.\n>\n> > **Example:** Do you have **enough** to pay for this?\n\n**3. We can use \"enough\" with an __adjective and a noun__, but the meaning of the sentence changes with the position of \"enough\".**\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** Is there **enough** __hot__ __water__? (**Meaning**: Is there sufficient hot water?)\n\n> **Example:** Is there __hot__ **enough** __water__? (**Meaning**: Is the water sufficiently hot?)\n\n**4. \"Enough of\"**\n\n> **Tip:** \"enough of\" +\n>\n> determiner\n>\n> [article or pronoun]\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** I've been in **enough of** __these__ situations to know better!\n\n> **Example:** We've had **enough of** __your__ complaints. Don't you have anything positive to say?\n\n> **Example:** Michael has studied **enough of** __the__ possibilities to make a good decision.\n\n## Too\n\n\"**Too**\" is an adverb which indicates that there is a quantity which is more than sufficient.\n\n**1. With adjectives and adverbs:**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too\" +\n>\n> adjective/adverb\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** You are **too** __young__ to understand.\n\n> **Example:** Clare is **too** __irresponsible__ to have a dog.\n\n> **Example:** It's **too** __early__ to go to bed.\n\n> **Tip:** > **Tip:** Note\n> >\n> > : We can use \"\n> >\n> > enough\n> >\n> > \" in negative sentences to indicate that something is less than sufficient. Compare the examples below to the ones above.\n>\n> Examples:\n>\n> > **Example:** You are __not old__ **enough** to understand.\n>\n> > **Example:** Clare is __not responsible__ **enough** to have a dog.\n\n**2. When using \"too\" with nouns, we use the expressions \"too many\" or \"too much\".**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too many\" +\n>\n> countable noun\n\n> **Tip:** \"too much\" +\n>\n> uncountable noun\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** There are **too many** __students__ in the classroom.\n\n> **Example:** Is there **too much** __sugar__ in your coffee?\n\n> **Example:** My daughter has **too many** __shoes__, she doesn't need any more!\n\n> **Example:** There is **too much** __work__ for just one person!\n\n**3. \"Too much of\" or \"Too many of\"**\n\n> **Tip:** \"too many of\" +\n>\n> determiner\n>\n> +\n>\n> countable noun\n\n> **Tip:** \"too much of\" +\n>\n> determiner\n>\n> +\n>\n> uncountable noun\n\nExamples:\n\n> **Example:** His problem is that he spends **too much of** __his__ __time__ playing video games!\n\n> **Example:** That's enough. You have already eaten **too many of** __the__ __chocolates__!"
              }
