          },
          "lecciones": [
            {
              "code": 108,
              "order": 1,
              "slug": {
                "es": "speaking-on-the-telephone",
                "en": "speaking-on-the-telephone"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Hablando por teléfono",
                "en": "Speaking on the Telephone"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "| Vocabulario |\n| --- |\n| bad line<br>mala señal |\n| caller<br>interlocutor |\n| collect call<br>cobro revertido |\n| directory<br>guía telefónica |\n| directory enquiry<br>información telefónica |\n| switchboard operator<br>telefonista |\n| **Verbs**<br>Verbos |\n| to call/ring back<br>volver a llamar |\n| to cut off<br>cortar |\n| to dial<br>marcar |\n| to hang up<br>colgar |\n| to hold [on]<br>esperar |\n| to pick up<br>descolgar |\n| to put through<br>pasar la llamada |\n| to transfer call<br>pasar / conectar la llamada |\n\n## Useful Phrases (Frases útiles)\n\n### Answering the telephone (Contestar al teléfono)\n\n> **Example:** Good morning/Good afternoon, Susan [your name] speaking.\n> **Translation:** (Buenos días/Buenas tardes. Le habla Susan [su nombre].)\n\n> **Example:** XY Company [Company name], this is Susan [your name] speaking, how can I help you?\n> **Translation:** ([Nombre de empresa], mi nombre es [su nombre], ¿cómo le puedo ayudar?)\n\n### Asking to speak with someone (Preguntar por alguien)\n\n> **Example:** May I/Could I speak with Mrs. Swanson please.\n> **Translation:** (¿Podría hablar con la Sra. Swanson, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** I'd like to speak with Mrs. Swanson, please.\n> **Translation:** (Me gustaría hablar con la Sra. Swanson, por favor.)\n\n> **Example:** I'm trying to contact Mrs. Swanson.\n> **Translation:** (Estoy intentando contactar con la Sra. Swanson.)\n\n### Asking for caller's name (Preguntar el nombre del que llama)\n\n> **Example:** May I get your name, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Podría darme su nombre, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** May I say who's calling?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puedo decirle quién está llamando?)\n\n> **Example:** With whom am I speaking?\n> **Translation:** (¿Con quién hablo por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** Who's calling, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Quién llama, por favor?)\n\n### Explaining the reason we're calling (Explicar el motivo de la llamada)\n\n> **Example:** I'm calling to ask about...\n> **Translation:** (Llamo referente...)\n\n> **Example:** I'm calling in regards to...\n> **Translation:** (Estoy llamando en cuanto a...)\n\n> **Example:** I'm phoning to tell you about...\n> **Translation:** (Estoy llamando para explicarle...)\n\n### Asking to wait (Poner a alguien en espera)\n\n> **Example:** Can you please hold a moment?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puede esperar un momento, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** One moment, please.\n> **Translation:** (Un momento, por favor.)\n\n> **Example:** Hold the line, please.\n> **Translation:** (Manténgase en línea, por favor.)\n\n> **Example:** Please hold.\n> **Translation:** (Espere por favor.)\n\n### Transferring a call (Conectar/Pasar la llamada)\n\n> **Example:** Thank you for holding.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por esperar.)\n\n> **Example:** I'll transfer you now.\n> **Translation:** (Ahora le paso.)\n\n> **Example:** I'll put you through now.\n> **Translation:** (Ahora le paso.)\n\n> **Example:** I'll connect you now.\n> **Translation:** (Ahora le conecto.)\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, but he/she is not available right now.\n> **Translation:** (Lo siento, pero no está disponible ahora.)\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, his/her line is busy.\n> **Translation:** (Lo siento, pero su línea está ocupada.)\n\n> **Example:** He/she is in a meeting at the moment.\n> **Translation:** (Está en una reunión en este momento.)\n\n> **Example:** Could you call back later?\n> **Translation:** (¿Podría volver a llamar más tarde?)\n\n### When we don't understand or can't hear (Cuando no entendemos o no oímos bien)\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, I don't understand. Could you repeat that, please?\n> **Translation:** (Lo siento, no he entendido. ¿Me lo podría repetir, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, I can't hear you very well. Could you speak up a little, please?\n> **Translation:** (Lo siento, no le oigo bien. ¿Podría hablar más fuerte, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** Could you spell that, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Me lo podría deletrear, por favor?)\n\n### Messages (Mensajes)\n\n> **Example:** Would you like to leave a message?\n> **Translation:** (¿Quiere dejar un mensaje?)\n\n> **Example:** May I leave a message, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puedo dejar un mensaje por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** Could you give him/her a message?\n> **Translation:** (¿Puede darle un mensaje?)\n\n> **Example:** Could you tell him/her that I called?\n> **Translation:** (¿Podría decirle que he llamado?)\n\n> **Example:** Could you ask him/her to call me back, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Podría pedirle que me llame, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** What's your name, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cómo se llama, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** What's your number, please?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuál es su número de teléfono de contacto, por favor?)\n\n> **Example:** When is a good time to call back?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cuándo es un buen momento para volver a llamar?)\n\n### Ending a call (Cierre de la llamada)\n\n> **Example:** Thank you very much for your help.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por su ayuda.)\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for the information.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por la información.)\n\n> **Example:** Thank you for calling/your call.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por su llamada.)\n\n> **Example:** Good-bye/Bye.\n> **Translation:** (Adiós)\n\n> **Example:** Take care.\n> **Translation:** (Tenga cuidado.)\n\n> **Example:** Have a nice day!\n> **Translation:** (¡Que le vaya bien!/¡Que tenga un buen día!)\n\n## Dialogue (Diálogo)\n\nA continuación tenemos algunos ejemplos de conversaciones telefónicas.\n\n### Conversation 1 (Conversación 1)\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Good morning, XY Company, Susan speaking. How can I help you?\n> **Translation:** <br>Buenos días, Compañía XY, le habla Susan. ¿Cómo puedo ayudarle?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello, my name is Mr. Smith and I'm calling for the Purchasing Department please.\n> **Translation:** <br>Hola, mi nombre es Sr. Smith y llamo para hablar con el Departamento de Compras por favor.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, which company do you represent?\n> **Translation:** <br>Vale, ¿a qué empresa representa Ud.?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Smith Office Materials.\n> **Translation:** <br>Materiales de Oficina Smith.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** I will transfer you now.\n> **Translation:** <br>Le transfiero ahora.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Thank you.\n> **Translation:** <br>Gracias.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Purchasing Department, this is Sarah speaking.\n> **Translation:** <br>Departamento de Compras, le habla Sarah.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello Sarah. My name is Mr. Smith and I am calling from Smith Office Materials. You have ordered materials from us in the past.\n> **Translation:** <br>Buenos días, Sarah. Mi nombre es Sr. Smith y llamo de Materiales de Oficina Smith. Uds. han comprado materiales nuestros en el pasado.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, of course. I'm familiar with the company.\n> **Translation:** <br>Sí, claro, les conozco.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** We have just printed our new catalog of office materials and I would like to make an appointment to show it to you and tell you about some of our new products.\n> **Translation:** <br>Acabamos de editar un nuevo catálogo con nuestro material de oficina y quisiera programar una visita con Uds. para enseñarselo y comentarles sobre algunos de nuestros nuevos productos.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, let's see. Can you come on September 15th at 9:00am?\n> **Translation:** <br>Bien, vamos a ver. ¿Puede venir el 15 de septiembre a las 9:00 de la mañana?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, that'd be great. I'll see you on the 15th then.\n> **Translation:** <br>Sí, estaría muy bien. Les veo el día 15 entonces.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, great. See you then.\n> **Translation:** <br>De acuerdo, muy bien. Hasta entonces.\n\n### Conversation 2 (Conversación 2)\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Good morning, XY Company, Susan speaking. How can I help you?\n> **Translation:** <br>Buenos días, Compañía XY, le habla Susan. ¿Cómo puedo ayudarle?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello, my name is Mr. Jones from Jones Computer Service and I'm calling for Mr. Kendall please.\n> **Translation:** <br>Hola, me llamo Sr. Jones, de Servicios Informáticos Jones y llamo para hablar con el Sr. Kendall por favor.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** One moment, please.\n> **Translation:** <br>Un momento, por favor.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry. His line is busy right now. Would you like to leave a message?\n> **Translation:** <br>Lo siento. Su línea está ocupada ahora mismo. ¿Quiere dejar un mensaje?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, please tell him that Mr. Jones called and to call me back when it's convenient.\n> **Translation:** <br>Sí, por favor, digale que ha llamado el Sr. Jones y que me llame cuando le sea más conveniente/posible.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Can I get your phone number, please?\n> **Translation:** <br>¿Puede decirme su número de teléfono, por favor?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, it is 888-564-7781.\n> **Translation:** <br>Sí, es 888-564-7781.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, thank you. I'll give him the message.\n> **Translation:** <br>Muy bien, gracias. Le daré el mensaje.\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Thank you. Good-bye.\n> **Translation:** <br>Gracias. Adiós.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Have a nice day!\n> **Translation:** <br>¡Que tenga un buen día!",
                "en": "| Vocabulary |\n| --- |\n| bad line |\n| caller |\n| collect call |\n| directory |\n| directory enquiry |\n| switchboard operator |\n| **Verbs** |\n| to call/ring back |\n| to cut off |\n| to dial |\n| to hang up |\n| to hold [on] |\n| to pick up |\n| to put through |\n| to transfer call |\n\n## Useful Phrases\n\n### Answering the telephone\n\n> **Example:** Good morning/Good afternoon, Susan [your name] speaking.\n\n> **Example:** XY Company [Company name], this is Susan [your name] speaking, how can I help you?\n\n### Asking to speak with someone\n\n> **Example:** May I/Could I speak with Mrs. Swanson please.\n\n> **Example:** I'd like to speak with Mrs. Swanson, please.\n\n> **Example:** I'm trying to contact Mrs. Swanson.\n\n### Asking for caller's name\n\n> **Example:** May I get your name, please?\n\n> **Example:** May I say who's calling?\n\n> **Example:** With whom am I speaking?\n\n> **Example:** Who's calling, please?\n\n### Explaining the reason we're calling\n\n> **Example:** I'm calling to ask about...\n\n> **Example:** I'm calling in regards to...\n\n> **Example:** I'm phoning to tell you about...\n\n### Asking to wait\n\n> **Example:** Can you please hold a moment?\n\n> **Example:** One moment, please.\n\n> **Example:** Hold the line, please.\n\n> **Example:** Please hold.\n\n### Transferring a call\n\n> **Example:** Thank you for holding.\n\n> **Example:** I'll transfer you now.\n\n> **Example:** I'll put you through now.\n\n> **Example:** I'll connect you now.\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, but he/she is not available right now.\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, his/her line is busy.\n\n> **Example:** He/she is in a meeting at the moment.\n\n> **Example:** Could you call back later?\n\n### When we don't understand or can't hear\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, I don't understand. Could you repeat that, please?\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry, I can't hear you very well. Could you speak up a little, please?\n\n> **Example:** Could you spell that, please?\n\n### Messages\n\n> **Example:** Would you like to leave a message?\n\n> **Example:** May I leave a message, please?\n\n> **Example:** Could you give him/her a message?\n\n> **Example:** Could you tell him/her that I called?\n\n> **Example:** Could you ask him/her to call me back, please?\n\n> **Example:** What's your name, please?\n\n> **Example:** What's your number, please?\n\n> **Example:** When is a good time to call back?\n\n### Ending a call\n\n> **Example:** Thank you very much for your help.\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for the information.\n\n> **Example:** Thank you for calling/your call.\n\n> **Example:** Good-bye/Bye.\n\n> **Example:** Take care.\n\n> **Example:** Have a nice day!\n\n## Dialogue\n\nBelow you will find some examples of telephone conversations.\n\n### Conversation 1\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Good morning, XY Company, Susan speaking. How can I help you?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello, my name is Mr. Smith and I'm calling for the Purchasing Department please.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, which company do you represent?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Smith Office Materials.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** I will transfer you now.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Thank you.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Purchasing Department, this is Sarah speaking.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello Sarah. My name is Mr. Smith and I am calling from Smith Office Materials. You have ordered materials from us in the past.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, of course. I'm familiar with the company.\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** We have just printed our new catalog of office materials and I would like to make an appointment to show it to you and tell you about some of our new products.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, let's see. Can you come on September 15th at 9:00am?\n\n**Mr. Smith:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, that'd be great. I'll see you on the 15th then.\n\n**Sarah:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, great. See you then.\n\n### Conversation 2\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Good morning, XY Company, Susan speaking. How can I help you?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Hello, my name is Mr. Jones from Jones Computer Service and I'm calling for Mr. Kendall please.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** One moment, please.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** I'm sorry. His line is busy right now. Would you like to leave a message?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, please tell him that Mr. Jones called and to call me back when it's convenient.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Can I get your phone number, please?\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Yes, it is 888-564-7781.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Okay, thank you. I'll give him the message.\n\n**Mr. Jones:**\n\n> **Example:** Thank you. Good-bye.\n\n**Receptionist:**\n\n> **Example:** Have a nice day!"
              }
            },
            {
              "code": 111,
              "order": 2,
              "slug": {
                "es": "writing-emails",
                "en": "writing-emails"
              },
              "display": {
                "es": "Escribir correos electrónicos",
                "en": "Writing Emails"
              },
              "view": {
                "es": "A continuación tenemos algunas sugerencias para redactar un correo electrónico profesional.\n\n| Do's |\n| --- |\n| - Write a clear subject in the subject line which explains the reason for the message.<br>Escribir un asunto claro en el apartado \"Asunto\" que explique el motivo del mensaje. |\n| - Write short and concise sentences.<br>Escribir frases cortas y concisas. |\n| - Write the most important information first.<br>Escribir la información más importante primero. |\n| - Use simple grammar. Avoid passive tense, etc.<br>Usar gramática sencilla. Evitar tiempos en pasivos, etc. |\n| - Use numbers or bullet points to make the message clearer.<br>Usar números o viñetas para hacer el mensaje más claro. |\n| - Use paragraphs to keep the email clear and orderly.<br>Usar párrafos para mantener el mensaje claro y ordenado. |\n\n| Don'ts |\n| --- |\n| - Write \"Hello\" in the subject line.<br>Escribir \"Hola\" en el asunto. |\n| - Write long, complicated sentences. E-mail readers want short, to-the-point messages.<br>Escribir frases largas y complicadas. Los lectores de correos electrónicos quieren mensajes cortes y precisos. |\n| - Give personal information that you don't want shared with others (your message could be sent to others).<br>Dar información personal que no quiere compartir con otros (su mensaje puede ser re-enviado a otros). |\n| - Use capitol letters to write words as this is considered shouting in e-mail language.<br>Usar mayúsculas para escribir palabras enteras ya que se entiende como un grito en el lenguaje de correos electrónicos. |\n| - Use different fonts in the message (the receiver may not be able to read it).<br>Usar diferentes fuentes de letra en el mensaje (puede que el receptor no lo pueda leer). |\n| - Use abbreviations or acronyms like \"BTW\" as the reader may not understand them or may be offended due to cultural differences.<br>Usar abreviaturas o acrónimos, ya que puede que el destinatario no los entienda o se ofenda debido a diferencias culturales. |\n| - Use symbols like this \":=)\"; they may be misunderstood and seem unprofessional.<br>Usar símbolos como \":=)\"; pueden ser malinterpretados o parecer poco profesional. |\n\n## Useful Phrases (Frases útiles)\n\n### Starting an E-mail (Empezar un correo electrónico)\n\n> **Example:** Hello, Ms. Brown [name of recipient].\n> **Translation:** (Hola, Sr. Brown [nombre del destinatario].)\n\n> **Example:** How are you?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cómo está?)\n\n> **Example:** How's everything?\n> **Translation:** (¿Cómo va todo?)\n\n> **Example:** I was glad to hear from you.\n> **Translation:** (Me alegró tener noticias suyas.)\n\n> **Example:** I hope thing are going well with you these days.\n> **Translation:** (Espero que todo vaya bien con Uds. estos días.)\n\n> **Example:** I hope you are well.\n> **Translation:** (Espero que esté bien.)\n\n> **Example:** What's new?\n> **Translation:** (¿Qué hay de nuevo?)\n\n### Reason for writing (Motivo del mensaje)\n\n> **Example:** I am writing because...\n> **Translation:** (Le escribo porque...)\n\n> **Example:** The reason I am writing is because...\n> **Translation:** (El motivo de mi mensaje es....)\n\n> **Example:** I wanted to ask you for a favor...\n> **Translation:** (Quería pedirle un favor...)\n\n> **Example:** I would like to...\n> **Translation:** (Me gustaría...)\n\n### Responding to an E-mail (Responder a un correo electrónico)\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for your email.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por su correo electrónico.)\n\n> **Example:** It was great to hear from you.\n> **Translation:** (Me alegró mucho recibir noticias tuyas.)\n\n> **Example:** Sorry for not writing earlier.\n> **Translation:** (Siento no haberle escrito antes.)\n\n> **Example:** I hope you and your family are well.\n> **Translation:** (Espero que Ud. y su familia estén bien.)\n\n### Responding to News (Responder a noticias)\n\n> **Example:** Glad to hear that you're well.\n> **Translation:** (Me alegra saber que estás bien)\n\n> **Example:** Sorry to hear about...\n> **Translation:** (Lamento oír sobre...)\n\n> **Example:** Good luck with...\n> **Translation:** (Buena suerte con...)\n\n> **Example:** Hope you feel better soon.\n> **Translation:** (Espero que se recupere pronto.)\n\n### Ending an email (Terminar un correo electrónico)\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for your attention.\n> **Translation:** (Gracias por su atención.)\n\n> **Example:** Please let me know if you have any questions or concerns.\n> **Translation:** (Por favor, avíseme si tiene Ud. cualquier pregunta o duda.)\n\n> **Example:** Many thanks.\n> **Translation:** (Muchas gracias.)\n\n> **Example:** I look forward to hearing from you.\n> **Translation:** (Tengo ganas de tener noticias suyas./Esperaré su respuesta.)\n\n## Sample E-mail (Ejemplo correo electrónico)\n\n**From:** hr@company.com<br>**Date:** Thursday, September 13, 2012 9:14 a.m.<br>**To:** bbrown@anemail.com<br>**Subject:** Interview for secretary position\n\n> **Example:** Hello Ms. Brown.\n\n> **Example:** It was nice meeting you in our interview last Monday. We would like to invite you back for a second interview with the Department head next week.\n\n> **Example:** Would you be available to come next Tuesday at 10:00 a.m.?\n\n> **Example:** I look forward to hearing from you.\n\n> **Example:** Best regards,\n\n> **Example:** Mrs. Samson\n\nDe:\n\nhr@company.com\n\nFecha:\n\nJueves, 13 de septiembre, 2012 9:14\n\nA:\n\nbbrown@anemail.com\n\nAsunto:\n\nEntrevista para puesto de secretaria\n\nHola Srta. Brown.\n\nFue un placer conocerle en nuesta entrevista el lunes pasado. Nos gustaría invitarle para hacer una segunda entrevista con el jefe del departamento la semana que viene.\n\n¿Estaría disponible para venir el martes que viene a las 10:00 de la mañana?\n\nEspero su respuesta.\n\nSaludos cordiales,\n\nSra. Samson",
                "en": "Below are some suggestions for writing a professional email.\n\n| Do's |\n| --- |\n| - Write a clear subject in the subject line which explains the reason for the message. |\n| - Write short and concise sentences. |\n| - Write the most important information first. |\n| - Use simple grammar. Avoid passive tense, etc. |\n| - Use numbers or bullet points to make the message clearer. |\n| - Use paragraphs to keep the email clear and orderly. |\n\n| Don'ts |\n| --- |\n| - Write \"Hello\" in the subject line. |\n| - Write long, complicated sentences. E-mail readers want short, to-the-point messages. |\n| - Give personal information that you don't want shared with others (your message could be sent to others). |\n| - Use capitol letters to write words as this is considered shouting in e-mail language. |\n| - Use different fonts in the message (the receiver may not be able to read it). |\n| - Use abbreviations or acronyms like \"BTW\" as the reader may not understand them or may be offended due to cultural differences. |\n| - Use symbols like this \":=)\"; they may be misunderstood and seem unprofessional. |\n\n## Useful Phrases\n\n### Starting an email\n\n> **Example:** Hello, Ms. Brown [name of recipient].\n\n> **Example:** How are you?\n\n> **Example:** How's everything?\n\n> **Example:** I was glad to hear from you.\n\n> **Example:** I hope thing are going well with you these days.\n\n> **Example:** I hope you are well.\n\n> **Example:** What's new?\n\n### Reason for writing\n\n> **Example:** I am writing because...\n\n> **Example:** The reason I am writing is because...\n\n> **Example:** I wanted to ask you for a favor...\n\n> **Example:** I would like to...\n\n### Responding to an email\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for your email.\n\n> **Example:** It was great to hear from you.\n\n> **Example:** Sorry for not writing earlier.\n\n> **Example:** I hope you and your family are well.\n\n### Responding to News\n\n> **Example:** Glad to hear that you're well.\n\n> **Example:** Sorry to hear about...\n\n> **Example:** Good luck with...\n\n> **Example:** Hope you feel better soon.\n\n### Ending an email\n\n> **Example:** Thanks for your attention.\n\n> **Example:** Please let me know if you have any questions or concerns.\n\n> **Example:** Many thanks.\n\n> **Example:** I look forward to hearing from you.\n\n## Sample Email\n\n**From:** hr@company.com<br>**Date:** Thursday, September 13, 2012 9:14 a.m.<br>**To:** bbrown@anemail.com<br>**Subject:** Interview for secretary position\n\n> **Example:** Hello Ms. Brown.\n\n> **Example:** It was nice meeting you in our interview last Monday. We would like to invite you back for a second interview with the Department head next week.\n\n> **Example:** Would you be available to come next Tuesday at 10:00 a.m.?\n\n> **Example:** I look forward to hearing from you.\n\n> **Example:** Best regards,\n\n> **Example:** Mrs. Samson"
              }
            },
